\h Yeshayah
\toc1 Yeshayah
\toc2 Yeshayah
\toc3 Yesh.
\mt1 Yeshayah
\mt2 (Isaiah)
\is1 Introduction
\ip The author of this document was Yeshayah, son of Amots (Amos). Called ‘Isaiah’ in older English translations, ‘Yeshayah’ means ‘Yahweh saves’. He was one of Yahweh’s prophets and lived in Yerushalem (Jerusalem) in the southern kingdom known by the name of its largest tribe, Yehudah (Judah). This document was written between 740 B.C. and 680 B.C., and is divided into three main parts:
\ip 1. \it Chapters 1–39\it*: This section tells how Yehudah was threatened by Assyria. Yeshayah saw that that was due to the people’s disobedience and failure to put their trust in Yahweh. Yeshayah warns the people and their teachers that they need to live godly lives that valued doing the right things, and promoting true justice. He warns them that if they don’t listen to Yahweh’s messages, destruction would indeed come to them. Yeshayah also predicts the birth of a descendants of David who would be followed by the people at some future time, plus he mentions a future period when there’s peace across the entire world.
\ip 2. \it Chapters 40–55\it*: In this second section, Yeshayah predicts the coming capture of many people from Yehudah, and how they’ll be taken to exile in Babylon. Yeshayah explains that even in those times, the people mustn’t become weak and lose hope, because Yahweh has a plan to save his people and return them there to Yerushalem to start a new life there. The theme of these chapters is how Yahweh controls what happens to his people and has a future plan for them, and included in that is that all nations will receive blessing from God by means of Yisrael (Israel).
\ip 3. \it Chapters 56–66\it*: Yeshayah also predicts the circumstances of those who God returns to Yerushalem. He passes on Yahweh’s instructions concerning godly living, true justice, observing the rest day, sacrificing, and praying. It’s in this section that we can read the source of Yeshua’s (Jesus’) speech about his being chosen in order to declare the good news (Yeshayah 61:1-2; Luke 4:18-19.)
\iot Main components of this document
\io1 Warnings and promises \ior 1:1–12:6\ior*
\io1 The cursing of nations \ior 13:1–23:18\ior*
\io1 Yahweh’s judgement of the world \ior 24:1–27:13\ior*
\io1 The other still warnings and promises \ior 28:1–35:10\ior*
\io1 Yehudah’s king Hizkiyah (Hezekiah) and the Assyrians \ior 36:1–39:8\ior*
\io1 The speeches about promise and hope \ior 40:1–55:13\ior*
\io1 Warnings and promises \ior 56:1–66:24\ior*
\rem This is still a very early look into the unfinished text of the Open English Translation of the Bible. Please double-check the text in advance before using in public.
\ie
\c 1
\p
\v 1 \add This is\add* the vision of Yeshayah (son of Amots), which he saw concerning Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* and Yerushalem in the days of Uzziyah, Yotam, Ahaz, and Hizkiyah, kings of Yehudah.\x + \xo 1:1: a \xt 2Ki 15:1-7; 2Ch 26:1-23; \xo b \xt 2Ki 15:32-38; 2Ch 27:1-9; \xo c \xt 2Ki 16:1-20; 2Ch 28:1-27; \xo d \xt 2Ki 18:1–20:21; 2Ch 29:1–32:33.\x*
\s1 Yahweh scolds Yehudah
\s4 Southern kingdom
\p
\v 2 Hear, heavens, and \add listen\add*, earth, because Yahweh has spoken:
\q1 “I’ve raised sons and brought them up,
\q1 ^but they’ve rebelled against me.
\q1
\v 3 The bull knows his owner,
\q1 and the donkey \add knows\add* its master’s feeding trough,
\q1 but Yisrael doesn’t know—
\q1 my people don’t understand.”
\b
\q1
\v 4 This sinful nation \add won’t come to a good end\add*.
\q1 these people \add who excel at disobeying\add*.
\q1 Descendants of \add those in the habit of doing evil things\add*.
\q1 Children who act corruptly.
\q1 They have abandoned Yahweh.
\q1 They have despised Yisrael’s holy one.
\q1 They have estranged themselves from him.
\q1
\v 5 Why do you \add want more beatings\add*?
\q1 Why do you keep rebelling?
\q1 \add Your\add* whole head is sick,
\q1 and \add your\add* \add motivation\add* is weak.
\q1
\v 6 From the sole of the foot \add up\add* to the head \add nothing is healthy\add*.
\q1 Bruises and sores and fresh wounds haven’t been \add cleaned\add* out,
\q1 and they haven’t been bandaged or \add treated\add* with \add olive\add* oil.
\b
\q1
\v 7 Your country is \add totally ruined\add* with your cities \add all\add* burnt down.
\q1 Right in front of you, strangers are \add taking all the harvest\add* from your field—
\q1 \add leaving devastation and destruction behind\add*.
\q1
\v 8 Tsiyyon’s \add (Zion’s)\add* daughter is left \add isolated\add*
\q1 like a hut in a vineyard,
\q1 like a shed in a cucumber field,
\q1 like a besieged city.
\q1
\v 9 If it wasn’t for the fact that Commander-in-chief Yahweh left a few survivors \add behind\add*,
\q1 we would have been \add wiped out\add* like \add both\add* Sodom and Amorah \add (Gomorrah)\add*.\x + \xo 1:9: \xt Gen 19:24; Rom 9:29.\x*
\b
\q1
\v 10 Hear \add what Yahweh has to say\add*, \add you who are like\add* Sodom’s rulers.
\q1 \add Listen\add* to God’s instructions, \add you who are like\add* Amorrah’s people:
\q1
\v 11 “What do your many sacrifices mean to me?” \add asks\add* Yahweh.
\q1 “I’ve had enough of the burnt offerings of rams,
\q1 and the fat of fattened animals,
\q1 and I’m not pleased by the blood of bulls or lambs or goats.\x + \xo 1:11-14: \xt Amos 5:21-22.\x*
\q1
\v 12 \add Who told you all that you had to appear in front of me\add*?
\q1 \add Who said that you all should come and\add* trample through my courtyards?
\q1
\v 13 Don’t \add keep bringing me worthless offerings\add*.
\q1 \add They smell terribly bad\add* to me.
\q1 New moon \add holidays\add* and sabbaths, calling of assemblies—
\q1 I \add can’t stand your disobedience mixed with your festive celebrations\add*.
\q1
\v 14 My spirit hates your \add religious holidays and your feasts on the calendar\add*.
\q1 They’ve become a burden to me that I’m tired of carrying.
\q1
\v 15 So when you spread out your hands, I \add just\add* hide my eyes from you all.
\q1 Even though you multiply prayers, I don’t listen
\q1 \add because\add* your hands are full of blood.
\q1
\v 16 Wash yourselves \add and\add* get cleaned up.
\q1 Remove the evil of your actions from \add in front of me\add*.
\q1 Stop doing evil things.
\q2
\v 17 Learn to do good.
\q1 Strive for justice.
\q1 Correct the oppressor.
\q1 Serve justice for the fatherless.
\q1 Stand up for the widow \add in court\add*.”
\b
\q1
\v 18 Yahweh says, “Come, now, and let’s \add work things out together\add*.
\q1 Even though your sins are like scarlet, they’ll become as white like snow.
\q1 Even though they’re red like crimson, they’ll become like wool.
\q1
\v 19 If you’re willing and \add ready\add* to obey,
\q1 you’ll all eat the best \add food\add* from the land,
\q1
\v 20 but if you refuse and rebel,
\q1 \add war will be what eats you all\add*.
\q1 That’s what Yahweh \add is telling you\add*.”
\s1 Disobedient Yerushalem
\p
\v 21 How did the faithful city become a prostitute?
\q1 She who was full of justice—
\q1 with righteousness embedded in her,
\q1 but now \add ended up as\add* murderers.
\q1
\v 22 Your \add city’s\add* silver has turned into \add junk metal\add*.
\q1 You wine is \add now\add* mixed with water.
\q1
\v 23 Your leaders are rebels and companions of thieves.
\q1 Everyone loves bribes and kick-backs.
\q1 They don’t defend the fatherless,
\q1 and \add don’t even think about standing up for\add* the widow.
\b
\q1
\v 24 Here’s the declaration of the Yisrael’s powerful master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh:
\q1 “\add Oh well\add*, I’ll get relief from my opponents,
\q1 and avenge myself on my enemies;
\q1
\v 25 I’ll turn my \add actions\add* against you,
\q1 and refine your \add junk metal\add* with \add chemicals\add*
\q1 to remove all your impurity.
\q1
\v 26 Then I’ll restore your judges like they were before,
\q1 and your counsellors like they were at the start.
\q1 Afterwards you’ll be a faithful city called ‘The city of integrity’.”
\b
\q1
\v 27 Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* will be set free by justice,
\q1 and \add those who repent\add*, \add set free\add* by \add doing what is right\add*.
\q1
\v 28 \add But those who rebel or disobey\add* will be shattered,
\q1 and those who abandon Yahweh will come to \add their\add* end,
\q1
\v 29 because they’ll be ashamed of \add the shrines\add* that you liked at the sacred oak trees,
\q1 and you’ll all be disgraced by the gardens that you chose \add to worship idols in\add*.
\q1
\v 30 You’ll all be like an oak tree with withered leaves,
\q1 and like a garden that has no \add access to\add* water.
\q1
\v 31 The strong \add man\add* will be like kindling and his work like a spark,
\q1 and both of them will burn together \add in a fire\add* \add that no one can put out\add*.
\c 2
\s1 Yahweh’s mountain is central
\r (Mic. 4:1-3)
\p
\v 1 This is the message the Amots’s son Yeshayah \add (Isaiah)\add* saw concerning Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* and Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add*:
\q1
\v 2 \add Near the end of time,\add* the mountain where Yahweh’s house is
\q1 will be established as the \add most important\add* mountain.
\q1 It will \add become more famous than any other hill\add*,
\q1 and all the nations will flow to \add visit\add* it.
\q1
\v 3 Many \add different\add* peoples will come and say,
\q1 “Come on, let’s go up to Yahweh’s mountain—
\q1 to the \add temple\add* of Yakov’s \add (Jacob’s)\add* God,
\q1 so he can teach us his ways and we can walk in his paths.”
\q1 Because \add God’s instructions\add* will \add emanate\add* from Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*,
\q1 and Yahweh’s message \add will spread out starting\add* from Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add*.
\q1
\v 4 He’ll judge between the nations,
\q1 and will \add settle cases\add* for many \add different\add* peoples.
\q1 They’ll hammer their swords into plough blades,
\q1 and their spears into pruning hooks.
\q1 \add The nations will stop attacking each other\add*,
\q1 and they won’t \add go to\add* war again.\x + \xo 2:4: \xt Yoel 3:10.\x*
\b
\q1
\v 5 \add You descendants\add* of Yakov,
\q1 come and walk in Yahweh’s light.
\s1 The day of Yahweh’s judging
\q1
\v 6 \add Yes,\add* you’ve abandoned your people, Yakov’s \add descendants\add*,
\q1 because they’re \add too influenced by eastern ideas\add*
\q1 and they practice divination like the Philistines,
\q1 and they \add make deals\add* with sons of foreigners.
\q1
\v 7 \add Their\add* land is full of silver and gold,
\q1 and there’s no limit to its wealth.
\q1 The land also is full of horses,
\q1 and there’s no limit to its chariots,
\q1
\v 8 \add Their\add* land is full of idols.
\q1 They worship the craftsmanship of \add their\add* \add own\add* hands—
\q1 what \add their\add* fingers have made.
\q1
\v 9 Then a person will be bowed down,
\q1 and a man will be humbled,
\q1 but not forgiven.
\q1
\v 10 Go into \add a cave\add* in the rocks,
\q1 or hide in \add a hole\add* in the ground
\q1 from the terror from Yahweh
\q1 and from the \add blinding light\add* of his majesty.\x + \xo 2:10: \xt Rev 6:15; 2Th 1:9.\x*
\q1
\v 11 \add Proud people will be humbled\add*,
\q1 and the arrogant will be \add take a lesson\add*,
\q1 and Yahweh alone will be \add honoured\add* on that day.
\q1
\v 12 because Commander-in-chief Yahweh \add has chosen\add* a day
\q1 \add for judgement against\add* those who are proud and aloof,
\q1 and against every arrogant person—\add they’ll all\add* be humbled.
\q1
\v 13 \add It’s also against\add* all the high and mighty cedars in Lebanon,
\q1 and all the oak trees in Bashan,
\q1
\v 14 against all the massive mountains
\q1 and all the high hills,
\q1
\v 15 against every high tower
\q1 and fortified wall,
\q1
\v 16 against all the ships from Tarshish
\q1 and all those beautiful sailing ships.
\q1
\v 17 Humankind’s pride will be humbled
\q1 and the arrogance of people will be \add cut off\add*,
\q1 and only Yahweh will be honoured \add at that time\add*.
\q1
\v 18 All the idols will be \add completely eliminated\add*.
\q1
\v 19 \add Yes,\add* men will go into the caves in the rocks
\q1 and into holes in the ground,
\q1 \add to escape\add* from the terror of Yahweh,
\q1 and from the \add blinding light\add* of his majesty,
\q1 when he \add takes action\add* to terrify the earth.
\q1
\v 20 On that day, \add people\add* will throw away
\q1 their gold and silver idols which they made to worship.
\q1 \add They’ll throw them\add* into \add rabbit holes\add* and \add bat caves\add*.
\q1
\v 21 \add Then they’ll crawl\add* into the crevices in the rocks
\q1 and into the openings in the ragged cliffs,
\q1 \add to escape\add* from the terror of Yahweh,
\q1 and from the \add blinding light\add* of his majesty,
\q1 when he \add takes action\add* to terrify the earth.
\q1
\v 22 \add Don’t put your faith in humankind who need air to breathe\add*,
\q1 because what \add can they do about anything\add*?
\c 3
\s1 Judgement on Yerushalem and Yehudah
\q1
\v 1 \add Yes, listen,\add* the master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh will take supply and support
\q1 away from Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* and from Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*—
\q1 all the supply of bread and of water,
\q1
\v 2 the \add top warriors and regular soldiers\add*,
\q1 the judges and prophets,
\q1 the diviners and elders,
\q1
\v 3 the unit captains and respected officials,
\q1 the counsellors and expert craftsman,
\q1 and any skillful enchanters.
\q1
\v 4 “Then I’ll put young people in place as their leaders,
\q1 and children will rule over them.
\q1
\v 5 \add After that,\add* the people will be oppressed—
\q1 \add one person\add* \add fighting\add* \add another\add*,
\q1 and a man \add being taken advantage of\add* by his neighbour.
\q1 The lad will insult the elderly,
\q1 and the dishonourable \add insult\add* the honourable.
\b
\q1
\v 6 \add Indeed\add*, a man will seize his brother in his \add own\add* father’s house:
\q1 ‘You have a coat \add so\add* be our ruler,
\q1 and this ruin will be under your \add control\add*.’
\q1
\v 7 \add That will cause him to shout out\add*,
\q1 ‘I \add have no intention of helping\add*. \add I don’t even have enough food and clothes for my own household\add*.
\q1 and in my house there is no bread and there is no clothing.
\q1 \add Don’t try to make me\add* the ruler of the people.’ ”
\b
\q1
\v 8 \add Yes,\add* Yerushalem has stumbled,
\q1 and Yehudah has fallen,
\q1 because their \add words and actions\add* are against Yahweh,
\q1 defying his \add royal authority\add*.
\q1
\v 9 \add You can tell their intentions\add* by the look on their faces,
\q1 and they \add talk about their disobedience like the people in Sodom did\add*.
\q1 They don’t \add try to\add* hide it.
\q1 \add Their lives won’t end well\add* because they’ve \add brought suffering on themselves\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 10 Tell \add those who do what’s right\add*
\q1 that they’ll \add be rewarded for their good deeds\add*.
\q1
\v 11 \add But\add* the wicked \add won’t end well\add*.
\q1 They’ll be repaid \add appropriately\add* for \add their actions\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 12 Even children will oppress my people,
\q1 and women rule over them.
\q1 Those who guide you lead my people astray
\q1 and confuse \add your progress to make you follow the wrong\add* path.
\s1 Yahweh judges his people
\q1
\v 13 Yahweh is \add getting ready\add* to \add make his case\add*
\q1 and is standing \add ready\add* to judge the peoples.
\q1
\v 14 \add He\add* will come \add to pronounce\add* judgement on the elders of his people and their leaders:
\q1 “Yes, all of you, you’ve \add taken all the fruit from\add* the vineyard—
\q1 the plunder from the poor is in your houses.
\q1
\v 15 Why do you crush my people
\q1 and \add rub\add* the poor people’s faces \add into the ground\add*?”
\q1 \add That’s\add* the declaration of my master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh.
\s1 A warning for Yerushalem’s women
\p
\v 16 Then Yahweh said:
\q1 “Because Tsiyyon’s \add (Zion’s)\add* daughters are proud,
\q1 and they walk \add with their chins stuck out\add* and with flirting eyes—
\q1 walking and mincing their steps and tinkling their feet,
\q1
\v 17 Then my master will \add shave\add* the heads of Tsiyyon’s daughters,
\q1 and Yahweh will make their foreheads bald.”
\p
\v 18 \add At that time\add* my master will remove their fancy ankle bracelets and headbands, crescent \add necklaces\add*
\q1
\v 19 and earrings, bracelets and veils,
\q1
\v 20 scarves, armlets, and sashes, perfume bottles and charms,
\q1
\v 21 rings on their fingers and in their noses,
\q1
\v 22 festive robes and capes, veils and purses,
\q1
\v 23 fine clothes and underwear, and their turbans and shawls.
\p
\v 24 When that happens, there’ll be a stink instead of fragrance,
\q1 a rope instead of a \add nice\add* sash,
\q1 baldness instead of a styled hairdo,
\q1 sackcloth instead of fancy clothes,
\q1 brands \add on the skin\add* instead of beauty,
\q1
\v 25 Your men will die from the sword
\q1 and your warriors in the battle.
\q1
\v 26 The \add city\add* gates will mourn and wail,
\q1 and she’ll \add end up\add* \add just\add* sitting their on the ground, alone.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 \add When that happens\add*, seven women will take hold of one man, saying,
\q1 ‘We’ll eat our food and wear our clothes.
\q1 \add Just\add* \add let us marry you so\add* we can take your name
\q1 to remove our shame.’
\s1 Yahweh blesses Yerushalem again
\p
\v 2 \add At that time\add*, Yahweh’s branch will become beautiful and glorious,
\q1 and the produce of the land will be \add a source of\add* pride and delight for \add what remains of the Israelis\add*.
\v 3 All who remain in Tsiyyon, i.e., the remnant in Yerushalem, will \add then be his people\add* who are destined \add to continue\add* to live.
\v 4 Surely my master will wash away the filth of Tsiyyon’s daughters, and clean up the blood stains from the middle of Yerushalem using the spirit of judgement and the spirit of fire.
\v 5 Then over all of Mt. Zion and her assemblies there, Yahweh will place a canopy over all the splendour—creating cloud during the day, and smoke and the brightness of a flaming fire during the night.\x + \xo 4:5: \xt Exo 13:21; 24:16.\x*
\v 6 During the day, it’ll be a shelter that gives shade from the heat, as well as being a cover and place to get out of the storm and rain.
\c 5
\s1 The song about Yahweh’s vineyard
\q1
\v 1 Let me sing, please, to my dearest one,
\q1 a song for my darling about his vineyard.
\q1 My dearest had a vineyard on \add very fertile\add* hillside.\x + \xo 5:1-2: \xt Mat 21:33; Mrk 12:1; Luk 20:9.\x*
\q1
\v 2 He dug it over and cleared it
\q1 and planted it with choice vines.
\q1 He built a watchtower in the middle of it
\q1 and also hewed a wine-pressing \add pit\add* \add in a rocky portion\add*.
\q1 Then he waited for it to produce grapes,
\q1 but it produced \add sour\add*, wild grapes.
\b
\p
\v 3 \add So\add* now, you who lives in Yerushalem
\q1 and man from Yehudah,
\q1 judge, please, between me and between my vineyard.
\q1
\v 4 What more could have been done for my vineyard,
\q1 that I haven’t \add already\add* done for it?
\q1 I waited for it to produce grapes,
\q1 but why did it produce wild grapes?
\b
\q1
\v 5 \add So\add* now, \add listen\add* please,
\q1 \add because\add* I’ll tell you what I’m going to do to my vineyard:
\q1 I’ll remove the hedge \add around it\add* and \add burn it in a fire\add*.
\q1 I’ll tear its wall down so \add people can trample over it\add*.
\q1
\v 6 Then I’ll \add allow it\add* to become overgrown.
\q1 It won’t be pruned or hoed, and thistles and thorns will grow through it.
\q1 Then I’ll command the clouds not to rain on it \add any more\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 7 \add Yes,\add* Commander-in-chief Yahweh’s vineyard is Yisrael,
\q1 and the people from Yehudah are his nice plants.
\q1 Then he waited for justice, but look, slaughter \add came\add*.
\q1 \add He waited\add* for \add people to do what’s right\add*, but listen, screaming \add came\add*.
\s1 The bad deeds of people
\q1
\v 8 Those who \add acquire houses won’t end well\add*,
\q1 or \add those who add to their fields\add* until there’s no room left.
\q1 →Then \add the poor\add* are made to remain alone in the middle of the \add country\add*.
\q1
\v 9 \add I heard Commander-in-chief Yahweh say\add*:
\q1 ‘Surely many houses will \add end up\add* empty—
\q1 \add even\add* large and nice ones \add won’t have anyone living in them\add*.
\q1
\v 10 A \add large\add* vineyard will produce \add a measly amount\add* \add of juice\add*,
\q1 and \add ten baskets\add* of seed will only \add give a harvest of one basket\add* \add of grain\add*.
\q1
\v 11 Those who get up early in the morning to get a strong drink \add won’t end well\add*,
\q1 \add yes,\add* those who loiter into the night as wine inflames them.
\q1
\v 12 \add They celebrate with\add* harp and lyre,
\q2 tambourine and flute and wine,
\q1 but they don’t \add care about anything that Yahweh does\add*,
\q1 \add in fact\add*, they don’t \add even\add* \add know what he’s done for them\add*.
\q1
\v 13 Therefore, my people will be exiled because of \add their\add* for lack of understanding,
\q1 and its honourable people are hungry,
\q1 and the parched crowds are thirsty.
\q1
\v 14 Therefore, \add the grave\add* has enlarged its appetite
\q1 and opened its mouth without limit.
\q1 and its elite and its crowd will descend \add into it\add*,
\q1 along with its \add noisy crowd\add* and \add those celebrating\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 15 Everyone will be \add brought into submission\add* and humbled.
\q1 All the proud people will be \add humiliated\add*,
\q1
\v 16 and Commander-in-chief Yahweh will be \add honoured for his justice\add*.
\q1 God will demonstrate his holiness by \add doing what is right\add*.
\q1
\v 17 Then the lambs will feed in their pastures,
\q1 and fattened \add calves\add* will graze \add around the houses\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 18 Those who pull in wickedness with cords of lies \add won’t end well\add*,
\q1 and nor will those who drag disobedience along \add behind them\add* with cart ropes.
\q1
\v 19 They say, ‘Let him hurry,
\q1 let him \add speed up\add* his work so we can see \add what he’s doing\add*,
\q1 and let the counsel of the holy one of Yisrael approach,
\q1 and let it come and let us know.’
\q1
\v 20 Those who call evil good, and good evil, \add won’t end well\add*.
\q1 \add Nor will those\add* who make darkness for light and light for darkness,
\q1 or who set bitter as sweet and sweet as bitter!
\b
\q1
\v 21 Those who are wise in their own eyes \add won’t end well\add*,
\q1 nor those who \add think they’re clever\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 22 Those who are experts at drinking wine \add won’t end well\add*,
\q1 nor those whose strength is mixing strong drinks,
\q1
\v 23 or those who take a bribe then say a wicked person is innocent,
\q1 or those that deny justice to innocent people.
\q1
\v 24 Therefore, the roots \add of their families\add* will rot,
\q1 and their flowers will \add flower away\add* like dust
\q1 just like how a tongue of fire devours stubble \add in a field\add*
\q1 and the dry grass goes up in flame,
\q1 because they’ve rejected Commander-in-chief Yahweh’s instructions,
\q1 and they’ve despised the message from the holy one of Yisrael.
\q1
\v 25 That’s why Yahweh \add got very angry at\add* his people,
\q1 and he’s \add taken action\add* against them and has struck them.
\q1 The mountains tremble and their corpses become like garbage in the streets.
\q1 In all these things, his \add anger doesn’t subside\add*,
\q1 and \add he doesn’t withdraw the actions he’s started\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 26 He’ll signal to faraway nations
\q1 and will whistle to those at the ends of the earth.
\q1 Then \add wow, how quickly they’ll show up\add*.
\q1
\v 27 \add Those enemy armies\add* won’t get tired or stumble.
\q1 They won’t stop for a rest or to sleep.
\q1 They never \add take their weapons off\add*,
\q1 or loosen the straps on their sandals.
\q1
\v 28 Their arrows are sharp,
\q1 and all their bows are strung.
\q1 Their horses have hooves as hard as flint,
\q1 and their chariot wheels are like a windstorm.
\q1
\v 29 Their roar sounds like a lion,
\q1 and they growl like young lions.
\q1 They seize their prey and carry it off,
\q1 →and there’s no rescuer \add in sight\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 30 They will roar above \add their prey\add* on that day,
\q1 like the roaring of the ocean.
\q1 If \add someone\add* looks across the land they’d only see darkness \add and\add* distress.
\q1 The light has been darkened by the clouds.
\c 6
\s1 The showing of God to Yeshayah
\p
\v 1 In the year \add that King Uzziyah died\add*, I saw my master sitting on a tall, elevated throne, and his \add long robe covered the temple floor\add*.\x + \xo 6:1: \xt 2Ki 15:7; 2Ch 26:23.\x*
\v 2 There were ‘serafs’ standing above him. They each had six wings—they used two to cover their faces, two to cover their feet, and two to fly with.
\v 3 They were calling out to each other,
\q1 “Commander-in-chief Yahweh is holy, \add yes, fully holy\add*.
\q1 The whole earth is filled with his splendour.”\x + \xo 6:3: \xt Rev 4:8.\x*
\p
\v 4 Whenever one of them spoke, the sound of their voices make the doorways shake, and the \add temple\add* was filled with smoke,\x + \xo 6:4: \xt Rev 15:8.\x*
\v 5 and I said,
\q1 “\add This isn’t going to end well for\add* me. \add Yes,\add* I’m doomed because I am a man with unclean lips,
\q1 and I live among a people with unclean lips,
\q1 \add and yet\add* my eyes have seen the king: Commander-in-chief Yahweh.”
\p
\v 6 Then one of the ‘serafs’ flew to me. He was holding a hot coal that he’d taken off the altar with \add a pair of\add* tongs.
\v 7 He touched my mouth with that coal and said,
\q1 “Look, this has touched your lips,
\q1 and your guilt has been taken away
\q1 and \add the price has been paid for\add* your sin.”
\p
\v 8 Then I heard my master \add ask\add*, “Who will I send? Who will go \add on our behalf\add*?”
\p “I’m here,” I \add answered\add*. “Send me.”
\p
\v 9 Then he said,
\q1 “Go and tell that \add nation\add*:
\q1 ‘Listen closely, but don’t understand,
\q1 and see clearly, but don’t perceive.’\x + \xo 6:9-10: \xt Mat 13:14-15; Mrk 4:12; Luk 8:10; Yhn 12:40; Acts 28:26-27.\x*
\q1
\v 10 Fatten the heart of this people,
\q1 and dull its ears and dim its eyes.
\q1 Otherwise it might see with its eyes
\q1 and hear with its ears
\q1 and understand with its heart,
\q1 →and turn and be healed.”
\p
\v 11 \add So\add* I \add asked\add*, “Until when, master?”
\p And he \add replied\add*:
\q1 “Until cities are desolate—without inhabitants,
\q1 and the houses are without people,
\q1 →and the land is a ruined wasteland,
\q1
\v 12 and Yahweh has driven the people far away,
\q1 →and \add the middle of the country is almost totally deserted\add*.
\q1
\v 13 If there’s still a tenth \add of the people\add* in it,
\q1 →then \add disaster\add* will turn back and burn everything.
\q1 Like an elm or an oak tree that’s been cut down \add but\add* still has a stump—
\q1 →\add so too\add* the \add sacred remnant\add* is \add the nation’s\add* stump.”
\c 7
\s1 A message for Ahaz
\p
\v 1 \add During the reign\add* of King Ahaz (son of Yotam, son of Uzziyah) in Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*, King Retsin from Aram and King Pekah (son of Remaliah) from Yisrael, went up to Yerushalem \add attack\add* it, but they \add weren’t able to conquer\add* it.\x + \xo 7:1: \xt 2Ki 16:5; 2Ch 28:5-6.\x*
\v 2 Tt was reported to David’s \add descendants\add* that Aram \add (Syria)\add* stands by with Efrayim, and \add the king\add* and the people trembled just like the trees in the forest shaking in the wind.
\p
\v 3 Then Yahweh told Yeshayah, “Please go out with your son Shear-Yashuv to meet Ahaz at the end of the channel from the upper pool, \add near\add* the road to the field \add where they wash clothes\add*,
\v 4 and tell him, ‘Be careful and calm \add and\add* don’t be afraid. \add Don’t let your courage melt away because\add* of these two tails of smoldering firebrands, \add i.e., by the anger\add* of Retsin and Aram and Remalyah’s son.
\v 5 \add Yes,\add* \add they’ve\add* \add plotted together\add* against you, saying,
\v 6 “Let’s go up against Yehudah \add together\add* and terrify her. Let’s break into her and crown Taveal’s son as king \add right there\add* in the middle of her.” ’
\p
\v 7 \add However,\add* my master Yahweh says:
\q1 ‘\add That’s not going to happen\add*.
\q1 They won’t succeed
\q1
\v 8 because Aram’s capital is Damascus
\q1 and Damascus’ leader is Retsin.
\q1 \add Nevertheless,\add* with sixty-five years Efrayim \add (Yisrael)\add* will \add no longer exist as a nation\add*.
\q1
\v 9 Efrayim’s capital is Shomron \add (Samaria)\add*.
\q1 and Shomron’s leader is Remalyah’s son.
\q1 If you don’t \add keep\add* believing,
\q1 then you’ll \add end up\add* not standing.’ ”
\s1 Immanuel will precede the thorns
\p
\v 10 \add Later,\add* Yahweh spoke again to Ahaz,
\v 11 “Ask your god Yahweh for a sign \add of confirmation\add* for yourself. \add Request an incredible miracle\add*.”
\p
\v 12 “\add No,\add* I won’t ask,” Ahaz \add replied\add*. “I \add refuse to\add* test Yahweh.”
\p
\v 13 Then \add Yeshayah\add* said, “\add You descendants\add* of David \add need to listen\add*. \add It’s bad enough that you’re wearing out the people, but why are you also annoying\add* my god?
\v 14 \add Because of that\add*, my master will \add take the initiative himself to choose\add* a sign: listen, a young, virgin woman\f + \fr 7:14 \ft See https://textandcanon.org/does-isaiah-predict-the-virgin-birth.\f* will \add become pregnant\add* and give birth to a son, and will name him ‘Immanuel’ \add (which means ‘God is with us’.)\add*.\x + \xo 7:14: \xt Mat 1:23.\x*
\v 15 He’ll know how to refuse evil and do good \add by the time that he can\add* eat yoghurt and honey.
\v 16 \add However,\add* before the child \add is old enough to do that\add*, the \add countries\add* of the two kings that you’re afraid of, will become deserted.
\p
\v 17 \add But instead,\add* Yahweh will bring the Assyrian king to \add attack\add* you and your people, and \add David’s dynasty will be under it’s greatest stress\add* since Efrayim \add (Yisrael)\add* broke away from Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*.”
\p
\v 18 \add When that happens,\add* Yahweh will whistle for a fly that’s in Egypt’s distant streams, and for a bee that’s in Assyria.
\v 19 They’ll all come and settle down in deserted valleys and cracks in the rocks, and in all the thornbushes and watering holes.
\p
\v 20 \add At that time,\add* my master will use a hired razor from beyond the \add Euphrates\add* to shave the head and legs of the Assyrian king, and to remove his beard.
\p
\v 21 In those days, a \add farmer\add* will preserve a \add single,\add* young cow alive, and a couple of sheep.
\v 22 \add However,\add* because they’ll produce so much milk, they’ll produce yoghurt, because everyone left in the \add country\add* will eat yoghurt and honey.
\p
\v 23 \add During that period,\add* every \add block of land\add* with a thousand grapevines that would have been worth a thousand silver coins, will \add just be full\add* of thistles and thorns.
\v 24 Because it’ll be \add so overgrown with\add* briers, men will \add hunt\add* there with their bows and arrows.
\v 25 All the hills that had been \add cultivated\add*, will now be \add off limits\add* because of all the thistle and thorns, and sheep and cattle will be left there to \add tread it down\add*.
\c 8
\s1 Yeshayah’s son is born
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told me, “Get yourself a large, \add stone\add* tablet and inscribe \add the name\add* ‘Maher-Shalal-Hash-Baz’ \add (which means ‘Quickly plunder and grab the loot’)\add* on it,
\v 2 and I’ll get my reliable witnesses to attest for me: the priest Uriyah, and Yeverekyah’s son Zekaryah.
\p
\v 3 Then I \add slept with\add* \add my wife\add*, the prophetess, and she got pregnant and \add in due course,\add* gave birth to a son. Yahweh told me, “Name him Maher-Shalal-Hash-Baz,
\v 4 because before he’s old enough to call out ‘papa’ or ‘mama’, the riches from Damascus and the plunder from Shomron \add (Samaria)\add* will \add all\add* be taken \add to be presented to\add* the Assyrian king.
\s1 Invasion by the Assyrians
\p
\v 5 Then Yahweh continued to speak to me again, saying,
\v 6 “\add Yehudah\add* has refused the gentle waters of Shiloah and \add instead\add* \add requests help\add* from \add King\add* Retsin and Remalyah’s son \add King Pekah\add*,
\v 7 so therefore my master will send the waters of a large, powerful river onto them: the Assyrian king and all his \add majestic power\add*. It’ll come like a flood filling all the channels then overflowing all its banks.
\v 8 It will sweep across Yehudah, flooding yet moving on until it reaches your neck. It’s \add edges\add* will cover your entire \add country\add*, Immanuel.”
\q1
\v 9 Raise the war cry, peoples, and be \add terrified\add*,
\q1 and \add listen\add*, all you distant places in the world.
\q1 \add Prepare\add* yourselves for war and to be shattered.
\q1 \add Prepare\add* yourselves for war and to be shattered.
\q1
\v 10 \add Make whatever plans you want\add*, but they’ll \add come to nothing\add*.
\q1 \add Give a presentation but\add* it won’t stand, because God is with us.
\s1 Yahweh warns Yeshayah
\p
\v 11 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh spoke strongly to me, and warned me not to \add behave like other people\add*, saying,
\v 12 “Don’t say ‘conspiracy’ everyone time that other people do, and don’t be afraid when they’re afraid, and don’t \add live in dread\add*.\x + \xo 8:12-13: \xt 1Pe 3:14-15.\x*
\v 13 Only \add honour\add* Commander-in-chief Yahweh, and \add be concerned about him\add* and fear him.
\v 14 He’ll be like your \add safe retreat\add*. He’ll be \add both\add* the stone that strikes and the rock that makes both Yisrael and Yehudah stumble, and \add like\add* a trap for the inhabitants of Yerushalem.\x + \xo 8:14-15: \xt 1Pe 2:8.\x*
\v 15 Many people will stumble over \add that stone and that rock\add* and fall and be broken, or be snared and captured.”
\s1 Warning about consulting mediums
\p
\v 16 Tie up this report and seal up these instructions for my apprentices.
\v 17 I’ll wait for Yahweh \add to act\add*. He’s \add distanced himself\add* from Yakov’s descendants, \add but I’ll continue to expect his help\add*.\x + \xo 8:17: \xt Heb 2:13.\x*
\p
\v 18 \add Both\add* I \add myself,\add* and the children that Yahweh has given me, are like directions and warning signs for Yisrael, that come from Commander-in-chief Yahweh who lives on Mt. Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*.\x + \xo 8:18: \xt Heb 2:13.\x*
\p
\v 19 \add When\add* they tell you all to consult mediums and fortunetellers who chirp and mutter, shouldn’t the people consult their god \add rather than the dead guiding\add* the living?
\s1 The time of sadness
\p
\v 20 Shouldn’t it be the written instructions that they talk about? If they’re not \add following\add* this message, dawn will never arrive for them,
\v 21 and they’ll be distressed and hungry as they pass it by. Then because they’re hungry and angry, they’ll curse their king and their god as they look upwards.
\v 22 They’ll look \add back\add* to the ground, and wow, \add only\add* see trouble and darkness—gloom, distress, and thick darkness thrusting out \add at them\add*.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 \add However,\add* it won’t not cover over those who are distressed. Previously he humiliated the Zevulun and Naftali \add regions\add*, but later, he’ll \add honour\add* the way of the sea—beyond the Yarden \add river\add*—Galilee of the nations.\x + \xo 9:1: \xt Mat 4:15.\x*
\s1 The coming king
\q1
\v 2 The people who walked in darkness have seen a \add powerful\add* light.
\q1 The light has shone on those who’ve lived in a land of darkness.\x + \xo 9:2: \xt Mat 4:16; Luk 1:79.\x*
\q1
\v 3 You have multiplied the nation itself.
\q1 You’ve increased its happiness.
\q1 They \add celebrate in front of you\add*
\q1 like the happiness at harvest time.
\q1 Like \add their excitement\add* when dividing the plunder,
\q1
\v 4 because you’ve shattered the \add chains on its neck\add*,
\q1 and the \add stick\add* \add whacking\add* its shoulders.
\q1 You’ve broken the rod of his oppressor
\q1 \add like when you defeated Midyan\add*.
\q1
\v 5 \add Yes,\add* every \add warrior’s\add* boot treading loudly will be burnt,
\q1 \add along with every piece of clothing with blood on it\add*,
\q1
\v 6 because a child is born for us.
\q1 A son is given to us
\q1 and the government will be on his shoulder.
\q1 He’ll be called ‘Amazing adviser’,
\q1 ‘Greatest God’, ‘Forever father’, ‘Prince of peace’.
\q1
\v 7 His government will be \add without borders\add*—
\q1 with peace \add that’s never broken\add*.
\q1 He’ll rule on David’s throne, and over his kingdom,
\q1 to establish it and sustain it with justice and with fairness from now \add onwards\add*.
\q1 The zeal of Commander-in-chief Yahweh will do that.\x + \xo 9:7: \xt Luk 1:32-33.\x*
\s1 Yahweh’s anger at Yisrael
\q1
\v 8 My master sent a message against Yakov,
\q1 and it \add dealt with\add* Yisrael,
\q1
\v 9 and all the people will know it—
\q1 Efrayim and those who live in Samarya.
\q1 With a proud and arrogant heart they’ll say,
\q1
\v 10 “The bricks have fallen, but we’ll rebuild with \add beautiful\add* chiselled stone.
\q1 The sycamores are felled, but we’ll replace them with \add expensive\add* cedar.”
\q1
\v 11 \add But\add* Yahweh will \add send\add* \add King\add* Retsin against them as an adversary,
\q1 and will stir up their enemies—
\q1
\v 12 the Arameans on the east and the Philistines on the west,
\q1 and they’ll \add be a big mouth that’ll gobble\add* Yisrael up.
\q1 Even then, \add Yahweh’s\add* \add anger won’t subside\add*.
\q1 He’ll \add still be taking action against them\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 13 The people still won’t return to the one who struck them,
\q1 and they won’t \add strive to know\add* Commander-in-chief Yahweh
\q1
\v 14 \add so\add* \add he’ll\add* cut off Yisrael’s head and tail—
\q1 \add high\add* palm branches and \add low\add* reeds, all \add on the same\add* day.
\q1
\v 15 Yisrael’s leaders are that head,
\q1 and the lying prophets are that tail.
\q1
\v 16 These people’s guides have \add led them the wrong way\add*,
\q1 \add so\add* the ones being guided \add were destroyed\add*.
\q1
\v 17 \add Therefore,\add* my master won’t be happy about their young men,
\q1 nor will he have compassion for their fatherless and their widows,
\q1 because everyone one of them is godless and \add does evil things\add*,
\q1 and every mouth speaks \add out\add* foolish things.
\q1 \add With all that going on, his anger never goes away\add*,
\q1 and \add he continues to take action\add* \add against them\add*
\q1
\v 18 because wickedness burns like fire.
\q1 It burns up the thistles and thorns,
\q1 and it \add spreads to the trees\add* in the forest
\q1 \add as smoke swirls up into the air\add*.
\q1
\v 19 Commander-in-chief Yahweh’s anger causes the entire land to be scorched,
\q1 and then the people become the fuel for the fire
\q1 as \add each\add* man doesn’t \add even\add* spare his own brother.
\q1
\v 20 They devoured on the right but were still hungry.
\q1 They ate on the left, but \add it didn’t fill them up\add*,
\q1 \add so\add* everyone ate the flesh on their own arms.
\q1
\v 21 Menashsheh \add fought\add* Efrayim, then Efrayim found Menashsheh,
\q1 then they fought together against Yehudah.
\q1 \add Even through all that, his anger didn’t subside\add*,
\q1 and \add he continues to take action\add* \add against them\add*.
\c 10
\q1
\v 1 Those who make wicked laws \add won’t end well\add*,
\q1 nor will administrators who write troublesome edicts,
\q1
\v 2 suppressing the rights of the needy,
\q1 and robbing the poor among my people of justice,
\q1 making widows become plunder,
\q1 and preying on the fatherless.
\q1
\v 3 Then what will you all do for the judgement day,
\q1 and for the destruction coming from far away?
\q1 Who will you all flee to for help \add then\add*,
\q1 and where will you leave your wealth?
\q1
\v 4 \add All they can do is to\add* crouch among the prisoners,
\q1 or fall among the killed.
\q1 In all these things, \add Yahweh’s\add* \add anger doesn’t subside\add*,
\q1 and \add he continues to take action\add* \add against them\add*.
\s1 Yahweh uses but judges Assyria
\p
\v 5 Assyria \add won’t end well\add*.
\q1 The rod of my anger and the staff of my rage is in their hands,\x + \xo 10:5-34: \xt Isa 14:24-27; Nah 1:1–3:19; Zeph 2:13-15.\x*
\q1
\v 6 I’ve sent \add their king\add* against an arrogant nation
\q1 and against the people \add that I’m angry with\add*.
\q1 I order him to plunder the plunder and to prey on the prey,
\q1 and to trample them—trodden down like the mud in the streets.
\b
\q1
\v 7 \add However, that’s not what’s in his mind\add*,
\q1 and \add he doesn’t even think about those things\add*,
\q1 because \add he’s bent on destruction\add*
\q1 and \add the elimination\add* of not \add just\add* a few nations.
\q1
\v 8 \add In fact\add*, he says,
\q1 “Aren’t all my commanders \add like\add* kings?
\q1
\v 9 \add We destroyed\add* Kalno liked \add we did at\add* Karkemish,
\q1 Hamat like Arpad, and Shomron \add (Samaria)\add* like Damascus.
\q1
\v 10 \add I’ve already punished\add* idolatrous kingdoms,
\q1 and their idols and images were \add more impressive\add* that those in Yerushalem and Shomron,
\q1
\v 11 so just like I did to Shomron and its idols,
\q1 I’ll will \add also\add* do to Yerushalem and its idols.”
\p
\v 12 \add In due course,\add* when my master has finished all his work against Mt. Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* and against Yerushalem, I’ll deal with the result of the Assyrian king’s \add proud plans and the arrogant attitude that he displays\add*,
\v 13 because he says,
\q1 “\add It was my own strength and initiatives that got me this far\add*,
\q1 and by using my wisdom, because I was discerning.
\q1 \add Now\add* I’ve removed the boundaries of the peoples,
\q1 and I’ve stolen their treasures,
\q1 and like a \add powerful animal\add*, I’ve brought down the inhabitants.
\q1
\v 14 My hand has seized the wealth of the nations
\q1 just like someone taking the eggs out of a nest.
\q1 I gathered it from \add all over the world\add*
\q1 \add but\add* no one fluttered a wing, or opened a mouth and chirped.
\p
\v 15 Will the axe \add say its greater\add* than the person who swings it?
\q1 Will the saw praise itself more than the one who uses it?
\q1 As if a rod could move those who are lifting it up,
\q1 or a staff could lift up what’s not made from wood.
\b
\q1
\v 16 Therefore, my master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh
\q1 will \add make his muscular warriors waste away\add*,
\q1 and instead of \add the Assyrian king getting\add* glory,
\q1 \add he’ll get his fingers burnt\add* like with a burning flame.
\q1
\v 17 Then Yisrael’s light will become a fire,
\q1 and its holy one a flame,
\q1 →and it will burn and devour his thorns and his briers in one day.
\q1
\v 18 His \add beautiful\add* forest and his fruitful land
\q1 \add will be steadily destroyed\add*,
\q1 like a sick person who wastes away.
\q1
\v 19 There’ll be so few trees left in his forest that \add even\add* a child could count them.
\s1 Only a remnant will return
\p
\v 20 \add At that time,\add* the remnant of Yisrael, i.e., the survivors of Yakov’s descendants, will no longer rely on that \add king\add* who makes them suffer, but instead will rely on Yahweh, Yisrael’s holy one.
\v 21 A remnant of \add Yisrael\add* will return to their powerful god.
\v 22 Although the \add Israelis\add* are \add currently\add* very numerous, \add only\add* a remnant will return. Destruction has been decreed \add because justice must prevail\add*\x + \xo 10:22-23: \xt Rom 9:27.\x*
\v 23 \add Yes,\add* complete destruction has been decreed by my master Yahweh and he’s about to apply it \add throughout the country\add*.
\s1 Yahweh will punish Assyria
\p
\v 24 \add Because of that,\add* my master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says, “My people living in Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*, don’t be afraid of the Assyrians. They’ll beat you with a rod and raise their staff against you \add like the Egyptians did\add*
\v 25 for a little while longer, and then I’ll \add be upset with\add* \add the Assyrians\add* and my anger will \add lead to\add* their destruction.
\v 26 Commander-in-chief Yahweh will wave a whip against them, like when the Midianites were struck at Orev rock, and \add wave\add* his staff over the sea like they did leaving Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*.
\v 27 Then \add at that time,\add* he’ll lift his load off your shoulders and his yoke from off your neck, and that yoke will be broken \add as you begin to thrive again\add*.
\s1 Enemy invasion
\q1
\v 28 \add The enemy\add* has come to Ayat, passed through Migron, \add storing their supplies\add* \add north of Yerushalem\add* at Mikmas.
\v 29 They’ve crossed over the pass. They camped at Geba. Ramah is trembling, and Gibeah of Shaul has fled.
\q1
\v 30 \add Cry out for help\add* daughter of Gallim,
\q1 pay attention Layshah,
\q1 you’ll suffer Antoti.
\q1
\v 31 Madmenah flees,
\q1 the residents of Gevim are taken to safety.
\q1
\v 32 Yet today he will stand at Nod,
\q1 shaking his \add fist\add* at the daughter of Tsiyyon—
\q1 the hill of Yerushalem.
\b
\q1
\v 33 Listen, my master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh will cut off the branches with a crash,
\q1 and the tallest of the tall will be cut down,
\q1 and the \add high and mighty\add* will be brought low.
\q1
\v 34 He’ll chop down the thickets in the forest with an axe,
\q1 →and Lebanon will be felled by the mighty one.
\c 11
\s1 The future, peaceful kingdom
\p
\v 1 Then a shoot will come out from the stump of Yishay \add (Jesse)\add*,
\q1 and a branch from his roots will \add grow to\add* produce fruit.\x + \xo 11:1: \xt Rev 5:5; 22:16.\x*
\q1
\v 2 Yahweh’s spirit will \add be with him\add*—
\q1 a spirit of wisdom and understanding,
\q1 a spirit of good advice and strength,
\q1 a spirit of knowledge and \add striving to obey\add* Yahweh.
\q1
\v 3 ≈He’ll be happy to \add respect and honour\add* Yahweh.
\q1 He won’t judge \add just\add* by what \add can be seen\add*,
\q1 or \add make decisions\add* \add just\add* from \add what can be heard\add*,
\q2
\v 4 \add but\add* he’ll judge the \add ordinary people\add* with justice
\q1 and decide fairly for the poor in the world.
\q1 He will strike the earth with the rod of his mouth,
\q1 and with the breath of his lips, he’ll execute the wicked.\x + \xo 11:4: \xt 2Th 2:8.\x*
\q1
\v 5 His waistbelt will be \add doing what’s right\add*,
\q1 and the strap for his hips will be faithfulness.
\b
\q1
\v 6 \add At that time.\add* the wolf will live with the lamb,
\q1 the leopard will lie down with the young goat,
\q1 and the cow and the young lion and the calf,
\q1 →all \add there\add* together, and a little child will lead them.\x + \xo 11:6-9: \xt Isa 65:25.\x*
\q1
\v 7 The cow and the bear will graze together.
\q1 Their young will lie down together,
\q1 and the lion will eat straw like the ox.
\q1
\v 8 A child will play over the cobra’s hole,
\q1 and the toddler will stretch his hand over the viper’s nest.
\q1
\v 9 There’ll be no more pain or destruction on all my sacred mountain,
\q1 because the world will be full of knowledge about Yahweh,
\q1 \add just\add* as the waters cover the sea.\x + \xo 11:9: \xt Hab 2:14.\x*
\s1 The return of a remnant
\p
\v 10 Then on that day, Yishay’s \add (Jesse’s)\add* root will stand as a signal to the peoples. Nations will search for him, and his residence will be \add wonderful\add*.\x + \xo 11:10: \xt Rom 15:12.\x*
\v 11 \add At that time\add*, my master will again \add exercise\add* \add his power\add* to recover a remnant of his people who remain in Assyria, Egypt, Patros, Kush \add (Ethiopia)\add*, Elam, Shinar, Hamat, and from \add various\add* islands.
\q1
\v 12 He’ll raise a banner for the nations,
\q1 and gather the \add Israelis\add* who were banished—
\q1 assembling the \add Jews\add* who were scattered \add right around the world\add*.
\q1
\v 13 Efrayim’s jealousy will go, and Yehudah’s enemies will be \add eliminated\add*.
\q1 Efrayim will no longer be jealous of Yehudah, and Yehudah will no longer treat Efrayim as enemies.
\q1
\v 14 They will swoop down the slopes to attack the Philistines on the west.
\q1 Together they’ll plunder the peoples in the east.
\q1 They’ll \add take over\add* Edom and Moab,
\q1 and the Ammonites will become their subjects.
\q1
\v 15 Then Yahweh will completely destroy the gulf from the Egyptian sea,
\q1 and wave his hand with his scorching wind over the \add Euphrates\add* river
\q1 →and divide it into seven streams that can be crossed in sandals.\x + \xo 11:15: \xt Rev 16:12.\x*
\q1
\v 16 There’ll be a highway for the remnant of his people coming from Assyria,
\q1 just like when Yisrael came out of Egypt.
\c 12
\s1 Song of praise
\p
\v 1 Then on that day you’ll say,
\q1 “I’ll praise you, Yahweh, because although you were angry at me,
\q1 \add your anger subsided\add* and you’ve comforted me.
\q1
\v 2 \add Yes\add*, God is \add the one who saves me\add*.
\q1 I will trust \add him\add* and not be afraid
\q1 because my strength and \add the one I sing about\add* is Yah—Yahweh,
\q1 and he’s \add rescued me\add* \add from my enemies\add*.\x + \xo 12:2: \xt Exo 15:2; Psa 118:14.\x*
\p
\v 3 Then you’ll cheerfully get water
\q1 from the springs of salvation.
\q1
\v 4 “Give thanks to Yahweh,” you’ll say at that time.
\q1 “\add Ask him for help\add*.
\q1 Tell all the people groups \add what he’s done\add*.
\q1 \add Tell everyone how wonderful he is\add*.
\q1
\v 5 Sing to Yahweh because he’s done amazing things.
\q1 \add Make sure everyone in the world knows about them\add*.
\q1
\v 6 Yell and shout happily, you inhabitants of Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*,
\q1 because Yisrael’s holy one is powerful among you.”
\c 13
\s1 Yahweh’s punishment of Babylon
\p
\v 1 \add This is\add* the heavy message about Babylon, which Amots’ son Yeshayah \add (Isaiah)\add* saw:\x + \xo 13:1–14:23: \xt Isa 47:1-15; Jer 50:1–51:64.\x*
\q1
\v 2 Raise a banner on the bare mountain.
\q1 \add Call out\add* to them \add and\add* wave \add your\add* hand,
\q1 and enter the gates of the princes.
\q1
\v 3 I have commanded my sanctified \add ones\add*
\q1 as well as \add angrily\add* summoning warriors—
\q1 my boasting, arrogant \add ones\add*.
\q1
\v 4 There’s a loud noise from the mountains,
\q1 like that from many people.
\q1 It’s the sound of uproar from the kingdoms—
\q1 nations that are gathering.
\q1 Commander-in-chief Yahweh is mustering an army for battle.
\q1
\v 5 They’re coming from a far country,
\q1 from the end of the heavens.
\q1 \add They’re\add* the instruments of Yahweh’s judgement,
\q1 \add coming\add* to destroy the entire country.
\q1
\v 6 \add Start\add* wailing because Yahweh’s day is close,
\q1 and destruction from the powerful \add one\add* will come.\x + \xo 13:6: \xt Yoel 1:15.\x*
\q1
\v 7 That’s why all hands hang limp,
\q1 and the heart of every person melts.
\q1
\v 8 They’ll have pangs of dismay,
\q1 and agony will seize them like a woman who writhes in labour.
\q1 They’ll stare at their neighbours in astonishment
\q1 with their faces flushed red.
\q1
\v 9 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh’s day is coming—
\q1 a cruel day with of fierce anger and rage,
\q1 to make the earth a desolate place
\q1 as sinners are destroyed from it.
\q1
\v 10 The stars in the sky and their constellations
\q1 won’t shine their light.
\q1 The sun coming out will be dark,
\q1 and the moon won’t be shining its light.\x + \xo 13:10: \xt Eze 32:7; Mat 24:29; Mrk 13:24-25; Luk 21:25; Rev 6:12-13; 8:12.\x*
\q1
\v 11 I will punish the world for its evil
\q1 and the wicked for their disobedience.
\q1 I’ll put an end to the pride of the arrogant,
\q1 and bring down the arrogance of the ruthless.
\q1
\v 12 I’ll make humans more rare than pure gold,
\q1 and people more scarce than the gold from Ofir.
\q1
\v 13 \add So\add* I’ll make the sky wobble,
\q1 and the earth will be shaken out of its place
\q1 by the fury of Commander-in-chief Yahweh
\q1 on the day of his raging ≈anger.
\q1
\v 14 Then like a gazelle being hunted
\q1 or sheep \add without a shepherd\add*,
\q1 everyone will turn to their own people group
\q1 and they’ll all flee back to their own \add countries\add*.
\q1
\v 15 Everyone who’s discovered \add (in Babylon)\add* will be run through \add with a spear\add*,
\q1 and everyone who’s caught will be killed by the sword.
\q1
\v 16 Their children will be smashed to pieces \add right in front of them\add*.
\q1 Their homes will be looted and their wives \add raped\add*.
\q1
\v 17 Listen, I’m stirring the Medes up against them,
\q1 who don’t value silver or care about gold.
\q1
\v 18 Their \add arrows\add* will strike down the young men.
\q1 They’ll have no mercy on \add your infants\add*,
\q1 and \add won’t show\add* any pity on your children.
\q1
\v 19 \add Yes,\add* that admirable kingdom of Babylon,\x + \xo 13:19: \xt Gen 19:24.\x*
\q1 the pride of the Chaldeans,
\q1 will be destroyed by God like Sodom and Amorah \add (Gomorrah)\add* \add were\add*.
\q1
\v 20 It’ll never be inhabited again,
\q1 or lived in from \add one generation to the next\add*.
\q1 The Arabs won’t even set up their tents there,
\q1 and the shepherds won’t rest \add their flocks\add* there.
\q1
\v 21 \add But\add* desert animals will live there,
\q1 and jackals will live in the houses.
\q1 Ostrich chicks will \add grow\add* there
\q1 and wild goats will \add romp around\add* there.
\q1
\v 22 Hyenas will howl in its towers,
\q1 and jackals in the nice palaces.
\q1 Her time is \add coming to an end\add*,
\q1 and her lifetime won’t be extended.
\c 14
\s1 Return from exile
\p
\v 1 Yahweh will have compassion on Yakov,
\q1 and will choose Yisrael again,
\q1 and settle them on their own land.
\q1 Foreigners will join with them,
\q1 and attach themselves to the \add Israeli people\add*.
\q1
\v 2 The nations will take them back to their \add own\add* place,
\q1 and in Yahweh’s land, the \add Israelis\add* will take them as male and female servants.
\q1 They’ll take their captors captive,
\q1 and they’ll rule over their oppressors.
\q1
\v 3 Then at the time when Yahweh gives you \add a break\add* from your anguish and suffering,
\q1 and from the hard \add labour\add* you did as slaves,
\q1
\v 4 then you’ll \add taunt\add* Babylon’s king \add with this song\add*,
\q1 “How the oppressor has stopped,
\q1 and how his fury has ceased.
\q1
\v 5 Yahweh has broken the wicked \add peoples’\add* staff,
\q1 the \add golden rod\add* of the rulers.
\q1
\v 6 In your rage, you struck the people groups with never-ending blows,
\q1 ruling the nations in anger—persecuting them without restraint.
\q1
\v 7 \add Now\add* the whole \add world\add* is in restful peace.
\q1 People have broken out with a shout of \add celebration\add*.
\q1
\v 8 Even the cypress trees are happy \add about your demise\add*,
\q1 as as the cedars in Lebanon.
\q1 Now that you’re \add powerless\add*,
\q1 →no one comes up to cut us down.
\p
\v 9 \add Down\add* below, the grave \add is excited\add*
\q1 \add waiting for your arrival\add*.
\q1 It wakes up the dead for you—all the kings of the earth,
\q1 raising them from their thrones—all the kings of the nations.
\q1
\v 10 They’ll all speak and tell you
\q1 that you have been made weak like them,
\q1 \add in fact\add* become \add completely\add* like them.
\q1
\v 11 Your \add reputation\add* has been brought down to the grave,
\q1 along with the sound of your harps.
\q1 Maggots are spread to be your \add mattress\add*,
\q1 and worms are your \add blanket\add*.
\p
\v 12 How you’ve fallen from heaven, you shining son of the dawn.\x + \xo 14:12: \xt Rev 8:10; 9:1.\x*
\q1 You’ve been cut down to the ground, you who defeated nations.
\q1
\v 13 You had said \add to yourself\add*,
\q1 ‘I will climb up to the heavens above God’s stars.
\q1 I will elevate my throne and I will \add rule\add* on the mountain
\q1 where they assemble on Tsafon’s heights.
\q1
\v 14 I’ll go up above the tops of the clouds,
\q1 I’ll make myself like the most high \add one\add*.’
\q1
\v 15 Nevertheless you’ve been taken down to the grave—
\q1 to the remotest parts of the pit.
\q1
\v 16 Those who see you \add there\add* will stare at you.
\q1 They’ll \add ponder your fate\add*—
\q1 if you’re the man who make the earth tremble?
\q1 \add The one\add* who made kingdoms shake?
\q1
\v 17 \add The one\add* who \add turned\add* the world into a wilderness,
\q1 and tore down its cities?
\q1 \add The one\add* wouldn’t release his prisoners \add of war\add* to go home?
\q1
\v 18 All the kings of the nations have laid down in honour—
\q1 each one in his own tomb,
\q1
\v 19 \add but\add* you have been thrown out of your grave,
\q1 like an unwanted branch \add that’s thrown away\add*.
\q1 Those killed with the sword \add surround you like how clothes wrap around a person\add*.
\q1 They went down to the stones in the pit like a trampled corpse.
\q1
\v 20 You won’t be buried with them because you’ve ruined your land.
\q1 You’ve killed your people—
\q1 the offspring of the wicked will \add never be mentioned again\add*.
\q1
\v 21 Prepare for the slaughter of his children because of their fathers’ disobedience,
\q1 in case they rise up and possess the earth,
\q1 and fill the world with \add their\add* cities.
\s1 Yahweh will destroy Babylon
\p
\v 22 Commander-in-chief Yahweh declares, “I will \add take action\add* against them and \add erase\add* Babylon’s name and their remnant and their future offspring.
\v 23 I’ll make it into a place where owls live, and pools of water, and I’ll sweep her with the broom of destruction.” That’s the declaration from Commander-in-chief Yahweh.
\s1 Destroyed by God the ones from-Asirya
\p
\v 24 Commander-in-chief Yahweh has promised,\x + \xo 14:24-27: \xt Isa 10:5-34; Nah 1:1–3:19; Zeph 2:13-15.\x*
\q1 “Everything that I intended will certainly happen,
\q1 and what I’ve planned will come to pass.
\q1
\v 25 To break Asirya \add (Assyria)\add* in my land,
\q1 and trample them \add down\add* on my hills.
\q1 Its yoke will be lifted from their \add necks\add*
\q1 and its burden lifted from their shoulder.
\q1
\v 26 That’s the plan for the whole \add world\add*,
\q1 and \add Yahweh’s\add* hand \add is ready to strike all the nations\add*.
\q1
\v 27 Commander-in-chief Yahweh has \add made his plans\add* and who could \add prevent\add* him?
\q1 His \add arm\add* is stretched out and who could turn it back?
\s1 Yahweh will destroy the Philistines
\p
\v 28 In the year that King Ahaz \add died\add*, this \add message\add* came:\x + \xo 14:28: \xt 2Ki 16:20; 2Ch 28:27.\x*
\p
\v 29 All you Philistines, don’t celebrate that the rod that struck you is \add now\add* broken,
\q1 because out of the root of that snake, a viper will grow,
\q1 and its \add result\add* will be a \add darting adder\add*.\x + \xo 14:29-31: \xt Jer 47:1-7; Eze 25:15-17; Yoel 3:4-8; Amos 1:6-8; Zeph 2:4-7; Zech 9:5-7.\x*
\q1
\v 30 Then the poor will graze in my pastures,
\q1 and the needy will lie down in safety.
\q1 I will kill your root with famine,
\q1 and it will kill your survivors.
\p
\v 31 Wail, \add you\add* gate. Cry out, \add you\add* city.
\q1 Philistia, all of you will melt away,
\q1 because smoke comes from the north,
\q1 and no \add soldier\add* is alone in his ranks.
\p
\v 32 What will \add Philistia\add* answer to the messengers from \add that\add* nation?
\q1 \add Remember\add* that Yahweh has founded Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*,
\q1 and \add it’s\add* in her that the afflicted among his people will find \add safety\add*.
\c 15
\s1 Yahweh will destroy Moav
\p
\v 1 \add Here is\add* a message for Moav \add (Moab)\add*:\x + \xo 15:1–16:14: \xt Isa 25:10-12; Jer 48:1-47; Eze 25:8-11; Amos 2:1-3; Zeph 2:8-11.\x*
\p So, in a night Ar in Moav will be laid waste, destroyed.
\q1 So, in a night Kir in Moav will be laid waste, destroyed.
\q1
\v 2 They’ve gone up to the temple, and Divon up to the \add hills\add* to weep.
\q1 Moav wails about Nevo and Medeva.
\q1 All their heads are bald.
\q1 All \add their\add* beards are cut off.
\q1
\v 3 In their streets they wear sackcloth.
\q1 On their \add (flat)\add* roofs and in the square, everyone wails,
\q1 →coming down in tears.
\q1
\v 4 Heshbon and Elealeh cry out—their voice is heard as far as Yahats.
\q1 So too, the soldiers from Moav call out as their spirit trembles inside them.
\q1
\v 5 My heart cries out for Moav, those who flee to Tsoar and to Eglat-Shelishiyah,
\q1 because they weep as they climb the Luhit ascent,
\q1 \add yes,\add* on the road to Horonaim, they cry \add loudly\add* from their suffering.
\q1
\v 6 The Nimrim \add spring has dried up\add* \add so\add* the grass has withered.
\q1 The vegetation has disappeared \add so\add* there’s no more greenery.
\q1
\v 7 Because of that, they \add take\add* the wealth they’ve made and their \add savings\add*,
\q1 →\add and\add* they carry it away across the stream with the willows.
\q1
\v 8 \add Yes,\add* the cry has surrounded the Moav region,
\q1 and \add her wailing\add* \add has carried\add* as far as Eglayim and Beyt-Eylim,
\q1
\v 9 because the Dimon stream is full of blood,
\q1 →However, I’ll bring more on Dimon.
\q1 \add I’ll send\add* a lion for Moav’s survivors,
\q1 and for the remnant of the land.
\c 16
\s1 Moav’s hopeless situation
\p
\v 1 Send a ram to \add Yehudah’s\add* ruler
\q1 from Sela in the wilderness to the mountain of the daughter of Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*.
\q1
\v 2 Then just like birds flutter away from a nest that’s disturbed,
\q1 \add so too\add* the Moav women \add will head to\add* the fords at the Arnon \add river\add*.
\q1
\v 3 Bring \add some\add* advice. Make a decision.
\q1 Make some shade \add that’s dark\add* in the middle of the day.
\q1 Hide the fugitives.
\q1 Don’t expose the refugees.
\q1
\v 4 Let Moav’s refugees live among you.
\q1 Be a shelter for them from the destroyer,
\q1 because the oppressor will \add give up\add*.
\q1 Destruction will cease.
\q1 The oppressors will disappear from the land.
\q1
\v 5 A \add king\add* will be established based on loyal commitment.
\q1 A descendant of David who will \add rule with\add* faithfulness—
\q1 one who judges \add fairly\add* and \add strives for\add* justice,
\q1 and who \add quickly does what is right\add*.
\p
\v 6 We’ve heard about Moav’s excessive pride,
\q1 and their haughtiness and arrogance,
\q1 \add but\add* their boasting is empty.
\p
\v 7 So Moav mourns for \add itself\add*—all of them.
\q1 \add They long\add* for the raisin-cakes from Kir-Hareset.
\q1 They’re \add completely overcome\add*
\q1
\v 8 because Heshbon’s fields have \add dried up\add*
\q1 as have Sevmah’s grapevines.
\q1 The rulers of nations have trampled down its best grapevines.
\q1 They reached Yazer—wandering through the wilderness.
\q1 Its shoots spread out—passing over the ocean.
\q1
\v 9 So I’ll weep along with those weeping in Yazer for Sevmah’s grapevines.
\q1 I’ll water you with my tears, Heshbon and Elealeh,
\q1 because they’re shouting about your summer fruits and your harvest.
\q1
\v 10 \add People\add* \add will no longer be happy\add* \add in their orchards\add*,
\q1 and celebrations \add will disappear\add* from the vineyards.
\q1 There won’t be any singing or shouting in the wine-pressing \add pits\add*,
\q1 and the shouting of those treading the grapes will cease.
\q1
\v 11 My \add stomach tightens like a harp\add* \add string when I think\add* about Moav.
\q1 My insides \add groan\add* about Kir-Hareset.
\q1
\v 12 \add The people of\add* Moav \add wear themselves out\add* \add praying\add* at \add their\add* \add hilltop shrines\add*.
\q1 They go to their \add temple\add* to pray, \add but it doesn’t help them\add*.
\p
\v 13 That’s \add what Yahweh already said about\add* Moav,
\v 14 and now \add he\add* says that within three years like a hirer labourer, Moav’s honour will \add disappear\add*, because \add out of their large population\add*, only a small and insignificant group \add will remain\add*.
\c 17
\s1 Bad news for Damascus
\p
\v 1 A \add message\add* for Damascus:\x + \xo 17:1-3: \xt Jer 49:23-27; Amos 1:3-5; Zech 9:1.\x*
\q1 Listen, Damascus will \add cease\add* to be a city
\q1 and will become a \add heap\add* of rubble.
\q1
\v 2 Aroer’s cities will be abandoned \add to sheep and goats\add*.
\q1 They’ll lie down there and there’ll be no one \add around\add* to frighten them.
\q1
\v 3 Forts will disappear from Efrayim
\q1 and Damascus will lose its kingdom.
\q1 The remnant from Syria \add (Heb. Aram)\add* \add will be a prize\add* for the \add Israelis\add*.
\m That’s what Commander-in-chief Yahweh says.
\p
\v 4 \add At that time,\add* Yakob \add (Jacob/Israel)\add* will become \add insignificant\add*.
\q1 The fat on his body will \add waste away\add*.
\q1
\v 5 \add Originally\add* the harvester reaped \add all the grain\add*,
\q1 →then it was stalks of grain,
\q1 →then \add an individual\add* picking up a stalk of grain,
\q1 →in the Refa’im valley.
\q1
\v 6 ≈\add There’ll be a few stalks left over\add*,
\q1 like beating an olive tree to ge the two or three olives at the top,
\q1 or four or five on the upper branches.
\m That’s what Yisrael’s god Yahweh says.
\p
\v 7 \add At that time\add* humankind will look at \add their maker\add*,
\q1 and turn their eyes to the holy one of Yisrael.
\q1
\v 8 They’ll \add stop trusting\add* the altars that \add they themselves made\add*,
\q1 They’ll stop \add noticing\add* the Asherah poles and incense altars \add crafted\add* with their own fingers.
\p
\v 9 \add At that time,\add* their \add fortified\add* cities will be abandoned like a deserted part of the forest,
\q1 and their summits will be abandoned and desolate as Yisrael \add advances\add*,
\q1
\v 10 because you’ve forgotten the god \add who saved you\add*,
\q1 and you didn’t remember the rock \add that you used for protection\add*.
\q1 So you sow pleasant plantations
\q1 and plant vine cuttings from a stranger.
\q1
\v 11 You nurture what you’ve planted,
\q1 and in the morning, your seed will have sprouted,
\q1 but the harvest will become a heap in a time of sickness,
\q1 and the pain will be incurable.
\s1 The defeat of enemies nations
\p
\v 12 The \add confusion\add* of many peoples \add won’t end well\add*.
\q1 they roar like the roaring oceans
\q1 and the nations rumble like the rumble of a \add large waterfall\add*.
\q1
\v 13 \add Yes,\add* the nations rumble like \add many rivers\add*,
\q1 \add but\add* he’ll scold them and they’ll flee away.
\q1 and be chased like how the wind chases chaff over the hills
\q1 \add and\add* like whirling dust blown ahead of a storm.
\q1
\v 14 Then in the evening, oh my, terror!
\q1 by it’s gone by morning.
\q1 That’s \add what happens\add* to those who plunder us,
\q1 and the outcome for those who rob us.
\c 18
\s1 Yahweh’s message to Ethiopia/Cush
\p
\v 1 You won’t end well, you land of whirring wings
\q1 that’s on the far side of Ethiopia’s \add (Cush’s)\add* rivers.\x + \xo 18:1-7: \xt Zeph 2:12.\x*
\q1
\v 2 You who send ambassadors across the ocean
\q1 skimming over the water in papyrus vessels.
\q1 You swift messengers, go to the nation where the people are tall and smooth-skinned—
\q1 a people who are feared—a \add very\add* powerful nation
\q1 from a land that’s divided by rivers.
\p
\v 3 All you inhabitants of the world
\q1 and those who live on the earth,
\q1 look when a signal is raised on the hills,
\q1 and listen when you hear a trumpet sounding.
\p
\v 4 This is what Yahweh told me:
\q1 I’ll remain quite and pay attention from my place,
\q1 like when heat shimmers with light,
\q1 like a cloud of mist in the heat at harvest \add time\add*.
\q1
\v 5 Before the harvest starts, when the blossoming has finished,
\q1 and the flowers are \add forming\add* into grapes,
\q1 then he’ll cut off the \add unwanted\add* shoots with the pruning knife
\q1 and cut away the \add long\add* tendrils.
\q1
\v 6 They’ll be left there for the birds of prey from the hills,
\q1 and the \add wild\add* animals \add across\add* the land.
\q1 The birds of prey will spend the summer on them,
\q1 and then the animals \add across\add* the land will spend the winter on them.
\p
\v 7 At that time, a gift will be brought for Commander-in-chief Yahweh,
\q1 from those tall, smooth-skinned people who are feared by every nation.
\q1 That \add very\add* powerful nation whose land is divided by rivers.
\q1 \add They’ll take it\add* to Mt. Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* where Commander-in-chief Yahweh’s name \add is known\add*.
\c 19
\s1 Yahweh’s punishment for Egypt
\p
\v 1 A \add message\add* for Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*:\x + \xo 19:1-25: \xt Jer 46:2-26; Eze 29:1–32:32.\x*
\p Look, Yahweh’s riding on a swift cloud and he’s coming to Egypt.
\q1 Egypt’s idols will tremble in front of him,
\q1 and \add its\add* people will \add lose their courage\add*.
\q1
\v 2 Then I’ll stir Egypt up against Egypt,
\q1 →\add so\add* brothers will fight their brothers and neighbours against neighbours,
\q1 city against city and kingdom against kingdom.
\q1
\v 3 Egypt’s spirit will be weakened from within
\q1 →and I will confuse its advice,
\q1 \add so\add* they’ll consult idols and the spirits of the dead,
\q1 \add as well as\add* mediums and diviners.
\q1
\v 4 Then I’ll hand Egypt over to a cruel master—
\q1 a strong king will rule over them.
\m That’s what the master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says.
\p
\v 5 The waters from the sea will dry up,
\q1 and any river will \add drop in level and empty out\add*.
\q1
\v 6 Then the low rivers will stink,
\q1 and Egypt’s canals will dry up.
\q1 The reeds and rushes will wither.
\q1
\v 7 There’ll be exposed areas at the river mouth,
\q1 and all the \add cultivated\add* land \add along\add* the river
\q1 will \add turn to dust\add* and \add cease to exist\add*.
\q1
\v 8 The fishermen will wail and mourn—
\q1 everyone who throws a hook into the \add Nile\add* will grieve,
\q1 \add along with\add* all those who spread a fishing net over the surface of the waters.
\q1
\v 9 Flax workers will be ashamed,
\q1 as will those who weave white cloth.
\q1
\v 10 \add Egypt’s\add* foundations will be crushed,
\q1 and their \add hired workers\add* will be \add discouraged\add*.
\p
\v 11 Tsoan \add city’s\add* officials are \add foolish\add*.
\q1 Far’oh’s \add (Pharaoh’s)\add* wise counsellors are stupid.
\q1 How could you all tell Far’oh that you’re the son of wise \add people\add*—
\q1 a son of ancient kings?
\q1
\v 12 \add So\add* where are your wise \add advisors\add* \add now\add*?
\q1 Please let them \add explain\add* to you
\q1 \add so\add* they’ll know what Commander-in-chief Yahweh has planned for Egypt.
\q1
\v 13 Tsoan’s officials have become fools.
\q1 Memphis’s leaders have been deceived.
\q1 Their tribal \add leaders\add* have led Egypt astray.
\q1
\v 14 Yahweh has mixed a confused spirit into them,
\q1 \add so\add* they’ve misled Egypt is \add everything it does\add*,
\q1 making them stagger like a drunkard in his \add own\add* vomit.
\q1
\v 15 No one in Egypt can do anything—
\q1 \add whether\add* head or tail, palm branch or reed.
\s1 Egypt will fear Yahweh
\p
\v 16 \add When that happens\add*, the \add Egyptians\add* will tremble like women, dreading Commander-in-chief Yahweh’s \add raised fist held\add* against them.
\v 17 Yehudah (the land of \add Judah)\add* will become an object of terror to Egypt. Whenever they’re reminded \add of Yehudah\add* they’ll become afraid, because of what Commander-in-chief Yahweh is planning against them.
\p
\v 18 \add At that time,\add* there’ll be five cities in Egypt where they’ll speak out in \add Hebrew\add*, and make oaths by Commander-in-chief Yahweh. (One of those cities will be called ‘the city of destruction’.)
\p
\v 19 \add At that time,\add* there’ll be an altar to Yahweh in the middle of Egypt, and a stone pillar to \add him\add* on \add their shared\add* border.
\v 20 It’ll be for a sign in Egypt and a witness to Commander-in-chief Yahweh, because when they’re oppressed \add and\add* cry out to Yahweh \add for help\add*, he’ll send a saviour and defender for them \add who\add* will rescue them.
\v 21 Then Yahweh will become known to Egypt, and \add the Egyptians\add* will know Yahweh that day, and they’ll worship \add him\add* with sacrifices and offerings, and they’ll \add make a commitment\add* to Yahweh and then they’ll \add honour\add* it.
\v 22 Then Yahweh will strike Egypt—striking then healing, and they’ll turn to Yahweh and he will \add take notice of their requests\add* and will heal them.
\p
\v 23 \add At that time,\add* there’ll be a highway from Egypt to Assyria \add (Heb. Ashshur)\add*, \add so\add* Assyrians will go to Egypt and Egyptians will go to Assyria, and \add they’ll\add* worship together.
\v 24 Yisrael \add (Israel)\add* will be the third \add in the group\add* with Egypt and Assyria—a blessing in the middle of the region
\v 25 when Commander-in-chief Yahweh will bless them saying, “Blessed be my people Egypt, and Assyria, the work of my hands, and Israel, my inheritance.”
\c 20
\s1 The undressed prophecy about Egypt and Ethiopia
\p
\v 1 In the year \add before\add* the Assyrian King Sargon sent his top army commander to Ashdod, and he attacked and captured it,
\v 2 Yahweh told Yeshayah \add (Isaiah,\add* Amots’ son), “Take off the sackcloth and the sandals \add that you’ve been wearing\add*.” \add So he started\add* walking around naked\f + \fr 20:2 \ft This doesn’t necessarily mean that he wore absolutely nothing.\f* and barefoot.
\v 3 \add Later\add* Yahweh said, “Just as my servant Yeshayah has been walking around naked and barefoot for three years, it’s a sign and a \add prophecy\add* about Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add* and Ethiopia \add (Heb. Kush)\add*.
\v 4 It’s a sign that the Assyrian king will lead away captives from Egypt and Ethiopia—young men and old, barefoot and naked with their buttocks exposed—to Egypt’s shame.
\v 5 They’ll be discouraged and ashamed \add because of\add* their \add unfounded\add* confidence in Ethiopia and their boasting about Egypt.
\v 6 Those who live \add along those coastlines\add* will say, “Listen, we fled there for help because that was our hope to \add be saved\add* from the Assyrian king—how can we escape \add now\add*?”
\c 21
\s1 Babylon’s coming destruction
\p
\v 1 A \add message\add* for the wilderness \add beside\add* the ocean:
\p It comes like whirlwinds sweeping through the desert,
\q1 coming from a nation \add that induces terror\add*.
\q1
\v 2 I’ve been \add given\add* a distressing vision.
\q1 The deceitful deceive and the destroyer destroys.
\q1 Go up Elam. Lay siege, Media.
\q1 I’ll make all her groaning \add come to an end\add*.
\p
\v 3 \add That’s why\add* my \add stomach tightens\add*.
\q1 Pangs of anguish seize me like \add a woman\add* giving birth.
\q1 I’m \add stunned\add* \add by what I hear\add*.
\q1 I’m terrified \add by what I see\add*.
\q1
\v 4 My heart \add falters\add*—I’m overwhelmed and I shudder.
\q1 The twilight that I \add longed for\add* \add has turned\add* into trembling.
\p
\v 5 They’re setting the table \add and\add* spreading out the rugs.
\q1 They’re eating and drinking.
\q1 \add Take action you\add* officials. \add Oil up\add* your shields.
\p
\v 6 My master has told me \add to\add* station a watchman who’ll tell what he sees.
\v 7 When he sees a rider \add or\add* a pair of horses, \add or\add* \add someone riding\add* a camel or a donkey, he must pay attention—very careful attention.
\p
\v 8 Then the watchman\f + \fr 21:8 \ft We follow the Dead Sea Scrolls here—the Hebrew has ‘a lion’.\f* calls out,
\q1 “My master, I’ve stood day after day on this watchtower,
\q1 and spent the nights stationed at my post,
\v 9 \add so listen,\add* a rider is coming with a pair of horses, and he \add brings the news\add* that Babylon has fallen, \add yes\add* fallen, and all its \add carved idols lie\add* broken on the ground.”\x + \xo 21:9: \xt Rev 14:8; 18:2.\x*
\p
\v 10 \add Oh\add* my down-trodden \add people\add* \add who’ve been trampled all over\add*.
\q1 I’ve \add passed on\add* to you all what I heard from Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh.
\s1 A message about Edom/Seir
\p
\v 11 A \add message\add* for Dumah:
\p Someone’s calling me from \add Edom\add*, “Watchman, how long will it be before the night is over?”
\p
\v 12 “The morning’s coming \add but\add* also the \add next\add* night. If you all want to ask, ask now, \add then\add* come back \add again later\add*.”
\s1 A message about Arabia
\p
\v 13 A \add message\add* for Arabia:
\p You’ll all \add overnight\add* in Arabia’s forest, you Dedanite caravans.
\q1
\v 14 Bring water out to meet the thirsty.
\q1 You who live in Tema bring \add some\add* food \add for\add* the fugitives
\q1
\v 15 because they’ve fled from \add the approaching army\add* with their swords held out in front of them,
\q1 and from the \add taut\add* bows and from the \add stress\add* of battle.
\p
\v 16 Yahweh told me \add that\add* in exactly one year from now,
\q1 like the end of the labourer’s \add contract\add*,
\q1 all the greatness of Kedar \add in Arabia\add* will come to an end.
\q1
\v 17 \add Only a few\add* of Kedar’s archers will remain from their warriors,
\q1 because Yisrael’s god Yahweh has spoken.
\c 22
\s1 A message about Yerushalem
\p
\v 1 A \add message\add* for the Valley of Vision \add (Yerushalem/Jerusalem)\add*:
\p What’s happening to you all that you’ve all gone up to your \add flat\add* rooftops?
\q1
\v 2 The city is full of noise \add and commotion\add*.
\q1 The town is so boisterous.
\q1 Those dead bodies weren’t \add killed in fighting\add*.
\q1 They didn’t die in battle.
\q1
\v 3 All your leaders fled together \add but\add* they were captured without \add an arrow being shot\add*.
\q1 All the others were captured together, \add even though\add* they had fled far away.
\q1
\v 4 Therefore I said: Don’t look at me!
\q1 I’m weeping bitterly \add so\add* don’t rush to comfort me
\q1 concerning the destruction of my people,
\q1
\v 5 because it’s a day of panic and trampling and confusion
\q1 from the master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh—
\q1 breaking down a wall in the Valley of Vision and crying out to the mountain.
\p
\v 6 Elam picked up the quiver with chariots and horseriders,
\q1 and Kir uncovered \add their shields\add*.
\q1
\v 7 Our \add most productive\add* valleys became full of chariots,
\q1 and the horseriders took position at the \add city\add* \add gates\add*.
\q1
\v 8 He uncovered Yehudah’s \add defences\add*,
\q1 and that day you looked for the weapons in the Forest House.
\q1
\v 9 You all saw that there were many breaches on the David’s City,
\q1 and you fetched water from the lower pool.
\q1
\v 10 You all counted Yerushalem’s houses,
\q1 and pulled \add some\add* down to fortify the city wall.
\q1
\v 11 You all made a reservoir between the two walls for the water from the old pool,
\q1 \add but\add* you didn’t \add put your trust\add* in the one who made it
\q1 and didn’t consider its designer from \add long ago\add*.
\p
\v 12 Tnen my master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh called for weeping and wailing,
\q1 and for \add heads to be shaved\add* and for sackcloth to be worn.
\v 13 \add But look!\add* \add There’s\add* celebration and gladness.
\q1 They’re killing cattle and slaughtering sheep,
\q1 and eating meat and drinking wine,
\q1 saying, ‘Let’s eat and drink \add today\add* because we’ll die tomorrow.’\x + \xo 22:13: \xt 1Cor 15:32.\x*
\p
\v 14 \add So now,\add* Commander-in-chief Yahweh has revealed \add to me\add*: ‘You all won’t be \add forgiven\add* for that \add wickedness\add* until you die.’
\s1 A message about Shevna
\p
\v 15 My master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says:
\q1 Go to the \add administrator\add* who’s \add in charge\add* of Shevna.
\q1
\v 16 \add Ask\add* what \add right you have\add* \add to come\add* here to \add carve\add* yourself a tomb—
\q1 \add chiselling\add* a tomb to rest in, out of the tall \add cliff\add*?
\q1
\v 17 Listen man, Yahweh is about to take firm hold of you,
\q1 and he’s about to hurl you away.
\q1
\v 18 He’ll swing you round and round like a ball,
\q1 \add tossed out\add* into a wide open land where you’ll die.
\q1 Your \add impressive\add* chariots will be there,
\q1 \add but\add* \add what a terrible\add* disgrace for your master’s household.
\q1
\v 19 I will push you out of your \add official role\add*,
\q1 and he’ll pull you down from your position.
\p
\v 20 Then at that time, I’ll summon my servant Elyakim (Hilkiyah’s son)
\v 21 and I’ll put your robe and sash on him, and give him the authority \add that you had\add*. He’ll be like a father to those who live in Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* and \add right across\add* Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*.
\v 22 Then I’ll place the key to David’s house on his shoulder and he’ll open \add the door\add* that no one will be able to shut. Then he’ll shut it, and no one will be able to open it.\x + \xo 22:22: \xt Rev 3:7.\x*
\v 23 I’ll fasten him in, like a peg into something solid, and he’ll become a \add wonderful throne\add* for his father’s house.
\p
\v 24 Then they’ll hang all the \add great things\add* from his father’s house onto him—the offspring and descendants from the small containers and cups through to the \add largest\add* jugs.
\v 25 Commander-in-chief Yahweh declares that \add at that time\add*, the peg driven into the firm place will give way, and break off and fall, and the burden that was \add relying\add* on it \add will fail\add*. Yahweh has spoken.
\c 23
\s1 A message for Tsor and Tsidon
\p
\v 1 A \add message\add* for Tsor \add (Tyre)\add*:\x + \xo 23:1-18: \xt Eze 26:1–28:19; Yoel 3:4-8; Amos 1:9-10; Zech 9:1-4; Mat 11:21-22; Luk 10:13-14.\x*
\p \add Cry loudly\add*, \add you\add* ships from Tarshish because your home \add port\add* has been destroyed. It’s been \add reported\add* to them from Kittim \add (Cyprus )\add*.
\v 2 Be silent \add you who live along\add* the coast, you traders from Tsidon \add (Sidon)\add* who cross the ocean to be filled.
\v 3 The \add grain\add* from Shihor across the waters \add and\add* the harvest from the \add Nile\add* became hers, and it became the \add commerce\add* of the nations.
\p
\v 4 Be ashamed Tsidon because the ocean has spoken.
\q1 The stronghold by the sea said,
\q1 ‘I haven’t been in labour or given birth,
\q1 and I haven’t raised young men or young women.’
\p
\v 5 When the report reaches Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*,
\q1 they’ll be \add very upset about what happened to\add* Tsor.
\q1
\v 6 \add Sail\add* over to Tarshish.
\q1 \add Cry loudly\add*, you \add who live along the coast\add*.
\q1
\v 7 Is this your happy \add city\add* that’s been around since ancient times—
\q1 whose feet carried her to \add settle\add* in a \add far away place\add*?
\q1
\v 8 Who planned that for Tyre, the bestower of crowns,
\q1 whose traders are princes,
\q1 whose merchants were honoured \add around the world\add*?
\p
\v 9 Commander-in-chief Yahweh planned it to dishonour the pride from all that splendour—
\q1 to treat the honoured people of the world with contempt.
\q1
\v 10 Go across your land like the river does.
\q1 \add You\add* daughter of Tarshish, there’s no restraint any more.
\q1
\v 11 He’s stretched his hand over the ocean.
\q1 He’s made the kingdoms tremble.
\q1 Yahweh has commanded Kanaan to destroy its fortresses.
\q1
\v 12 He said, ‘You won’t continue celebrating, \add you\add* oppressed young daughter of Tsidon.
\q1 \add Take action and\add* go across to Cyprus \add but\add* you won’t \add get any peace\add* there.’
\p
\v 13 Look at the Chaldeans’ country—those people have come to nothing.
\q1 The Assyrians allocated it to \add animals\add* that live in the wilderness.
\q1 They erected siege-towers against it—
\q1 demolishing its palaces and turning it into \add a pile of rubble\add*.
\p
\v 14 \add Cry loudly\add*, \add you\add* ships from Tarshish.
\q1 because your fortress has been destroyed.
\p
\v 15 \add After\add* that \add time\add*, Tsor \add (Tyre)\add* will be forgotten for seventy years like the \add lifespan\add* of a single king. At the end of those seventy years, what will happen to Tsor will be like the prostitute in \add this\add* song:
\q1
\v 16 Take a harp and go around the city, \add you\add* forgotten prostitute.
\q1 ^Play many songs so that you’ll be remembered.
\p
\v 17 Then at the end of those seventy years, Yahweh will visit Tsor. It’ll return to hiring itself out and to her prostitution with all the world’s kingdoms on \add this planet\add*.
\v 18 \add But\add* their earnings and profits will be set apart for Yahweh. It won’t be stored up or hoarded, because it will belong to those who live in Yahweh’s \add presence\add* for buying \add plenty of food\add* and beautiful \add clothes\add*.
\c 24
\s1 The cursing of God of world
\p
\v 1 Listen, Yahweh is about to \add devastate\add* the \add world\add*
\q1 and about to \add leave it in ruins\add*.
\q1 He’ll twist its surface and scatter its inhabitants.
\q1
\v 2 Then the priest \add won’t be any better off\add* than the people,
\q1 the master than his slave,
\q1 the mistress than her maids,
\q1 the seller than the buyer,
\q1 the borrower than the lender,
\q1 \add or\add* the creditor than the debtor.
\q1
\v 3 The \add world\add* will be totally devastated and completely plundered.
\q1 It’ll be plundered because Yahweh has spoken this message.
\p
\v 4 The land has dried up \add and everything has\add* withered.
\q1 The world has \add declined\add* and withered.
\q1 \add Its\add* prominent people \add declined\add* \add as well\add*.
\q1
\v 5 The \add world\add* has been defiled by its inhabitants
\q1 because they’ve broken the laws,
\q1 disregarded the decree,
\q1 broken the eternal agreement.\f + \fr 24:5 \ft Perhaps referring to the instructions given to Noah and family in \xt Genesis 9:1.\f*
\q1
\v 6 That’s why a curse has consumed the \add world\add*,
\q1 and its inhabitants are found guilty.
\q1 Therefore earth’s inhabitants will decrease
\q1 and \add only\add* a few will be left.
\q1
\v 7 The new wine has dried up—the grapevine has deteriorated.
\q1 All the people \add who were cheery\add* are \add now\add* groaning.
\q1
\v 8 The \add happy sound\add* of the tambourines ceases.
\q1 The loud celebrations stop.
\q1 The harp’s cheery \add music\add* \add has gone silent\add*.
\q1
\v 9 They don’t sing \add and\add* drink wine \add any more\add*.
\q1 Strong drink \add now\add* tastes bitter when they drink it.
\q1
\v 10 The town is \add completely disorganised\add*.
\q1 \add All the homes have been boarded up to keep people out\add*.
\q1
\v 11 There’s an outcry in the streets \add about\add* the wine.
\q1 Cheeriness has \add degraded\add* into \add twilight\add*.
\q1 Happiness has departed from the \add world\add*.
\q1
\v 12 Desolation has remained in the city.
\q1 The \add gates\add* will be crushed into \add ruins\add*.
\q1
\v 13 It’ll be like that \add all over the world\add*—among the nations
\q1 like when an olive tree is beaten \add to shake the fruit off\add*
\q1 \add or\add* like the \add few left-over grapes\add* when the grape harvest is finished.
\p
\v 14 They’ll \add start singing with gusto and with happiness\add*.
\q1 From the west they’ll shout cheerfully \add about\add* Yahweh’s \add greatness\add*.
\q1
\v 15 Therefore in the east, \add praise\add* Yahweh.
\q1 On the islands, \add praise\add* the name of Yisrael’s god, Yahweh.
\q1
\v 16 We’ve heard songs from the end of the earth, ‘\add Praise to the one who’s always fair and right\add*.’
\p Then I said, ‘I’m wasting away—\add losing weight\add*—\add I won’t end well\add*.
\q1 The treacherous have been treacherous,
\q1 \add yes,\add* the treacherous have been treacherously treacherous.’
\q1
\v 17 Terror and pit-traps and snare-traps \add await\add* you,
\q1 \add you\add* \add inhabitants\add* of the earth.
\q1
\v 18 The one who runs away from the sound of terror, will fall into the pit,
\q1 and those who get up out of the pits, will be caught in the snare,
\q1 because the windows in the high place have been opened,
\q1 and the earth’s foundations have been shaken.
\q1
\v 19 The earth will be totally shattered.
\q1 The earth will be split completely through.
\q1 The earth will be violently shaken.
\q1
\v 20 The earth staggers around like a drunkard,
\q1 and sways like a hut \add in a gale\add*.
\q1 Its sin will \add weigh it down\add*
\q1 →and it’ll fall—never to rise again.
\p
\v 21 \add At that time\add*, Yahweh will \add punish\add* the heavenly \add army\add*
\q1 and the earthly kings on the earth.
\q1
\v 22 They’ll be rounded up and imprisoned in a pit.
\q1 They’ll be shut up in that prison and after a long time, they’ll be \add punished\add*.
\q1
\v 23 Then the moon will go shy, and the sun will \add hide in shame\add*,
\q1 because Commander-in-chief Yahweh will reign on Mt. Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* \add there\add* in Yerushalem
\q1 and with splendour in front of his elders.
\c 25
\s1 A song for praising Yahweh
\p
\v 1 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh, you’re my god.
\q1 I will \add honour\add* you and thank your \add name/reputation\add*
\q1 because you’ve done \add incredible things\add*,
\q1 planned long back in \add perfect\add* faithfulness.
\q1
\v 2 \add Yes,\add* you \add can\add* make a city into a heap \add of rubble\add*,
\q1 \add or\add* a fortified town into ruins.
\q1 You’ve destroyed some strangers’ fortresses—never to be rebuilt \add again\add*.
\q1
\v 3 \add So yes,\add* strong people will honour you—
\q1 The towns in ruthless nations will fear you,
\q1
\v 4 because you’ve been a \add safe place\add* to be shelter for \add those who are distressed\add*—
\q1 a shelter from the rain and a shade from the \add hot sun\add*,
\q1 because the breath of ruthless \add people\add* is like rain beating against a wall,
\q1
\v 5 \add and\add* like heat in a dry land.
\q1 You subdued the uproar from foreigners,
\q1 like the shade of a cloud \add reduces\add* the heat.
\q1 He’ll quieten down the song of ruthless \add people\add*.
\s1 Yahweh hosts a banquet
\p
\v 6 Then Commander-in-chief Yahweh will hold a banquet of good things for all that people on that mountain.
\q1 There’ll be \add vintage\add* wine \add and choice meat\add*.
\q1
\v 7 Then on that mountain, he’ll swallow up the \add bedsheet\add* that’s covering all the peoples,
\q1 and the web that’s woven over all the nations.
\q1
\v 8 My master will \add permanently\add* swallow death up.
\q1 Yahweh will wipe the tears away from every face.
\q1 He’s removed his people’s disgrace from all the earth, because Yahweh has spoken.\x + \xo 25:8: a \xt 1Cor 15:54; \xo b \xt Rev 7:17; 21:4.\x*
\p
\v 9 Then \add at the time\add* it will be said, ‘Look, that’s our god.
\q1 We put our hope in him, and he saved us.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* that’s Yahweh—\add we maintained our trust\add* in him.
\q1 We’ll be happy and celebrate \add how he’s saved us\add*.’
\s1 The cursing of God of Moab
\p
\v 10 Yahweh’s hand rests on this mountain \add to secure it\add*.
\q1 Moav will be trampled down like a heap of straw in a dung pile.\x + \xo 25:10-12: \xt Isa 15:1–16:14; Jer 48:1-47; Eze 25:8-11; Amos 2:1-3; Zeph 2:8-11.\x*
\q1
\v 11 Yahweh will spread out his hands in the middle of it,
\q1 like a swimmer spreading his arms to swim,
\q1 and he’ll \add cancel\add* their pride with \add the skill of\add* his hands.
\q1
\v 12 He’ll knock down your high fortress walls,
\q1 and \add Moav’s cities\add* will be broken right down low.
\c 26
\s1 Yehudah’s victory song
\p
\v 1 A song will be sung in Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* \add at that time\add*:
\q1 \add Yerushalem\add* city is strong.
\q1 He \add gave us\add* walls and ramparts to keep us safe.
\q1
\v 2 Open the gates so a righteous nation can enter—
\q1 one that remains faithful.
\q1
\v 3 The \add one\add* with \add their mind made up firmly\add* will \add have true peace\add*,
\q1 because he \add puts\add* his trust in you.
\q1
\v 4 \add Put your\add* trust in Yahweh \add forever\add*,
\q1 because Yah (Yahweh) is a \add stable\add* rock.
\q1
\v 5 \add That’s\add* because he humbles those who live in high \add places\add*.
\q1 He’ll bring low the town that’s been elevated.
\q1 He’ll will lay it low to the ground—\add levelling it down\add* to dust.
\q1
\v 6 It will be trampled down by feet—
\q1 the feet of the oppressed,
\q1 the footsteps of the poor.
\b
\q1
\v 7 The righteous \add person’s\add* path is level.
\q1 \add You\add*, the \add one who does what’s right\add*, will \add flatten\add* \add their\add* paths.
\q1
\v 8 \add We’ve\add* we’ve \add followed your instructions\add*, Yahweh, we’ve \add kept our trust in\add* you—
\q1 \add we\add* desire \add to honour\add* your name and \add reputation\add*
\q1
\v 9 \add From deep inside me\add*, I have longed for you in the night—
\q1 my spirit within me earnestly \add waits\add* for you,
\q1 because when \add people have your instructions\add*,
\q1 the world’s inhabitants learns \add to discern\add* \add what’s right\add*.
\q1
\v 10 \add If\add* the wicked \add person\add* is shown favour,
\q1 they won’t learn \add to do what’s right\add*.
\q1 \add Even\add* in a land where \add doing right is valued\add*,
\q1 they act unjustly and won’t \add get to\add* see Yahweh’s majesty.
\q1
\v 11 Yahweh, when \add you take action\add*, they don’t \add perceive it\add*.
\q1 Let them see and be ashamed by the people’s zeal,
\q1 Also, the fire will consume your enemies.\x + \xo 26:11: \xt Heb 10:27.\x*
\b
\q1
\v 12 Yahweh, you’ll establish peace for us,
\q1 because you indeed \add have taken action on our behalf.\add*
\q1
\v 13 Yahweh our god, we’ve been ruled over by other masters,
\q1 but you only, are the one that we \add honour\add*.
\q1
\v 14 \add Those\add* dead ones won’t live—those departed spirits won’t rise \add again\add*,
\q1 \add indeed\add* you’ve visited and destroyed them,
\q1 and \add erased\add* all memory of them.
\q1
\v 15 You’ve \add enlarged\add* the nation, Yahweh,
\q1 \add yes,\add* \add enlarged\add* \add it\add* and gained \add honour\add*—
\q1 you’ve extended all the land’s boundaries.
\q1
\v 16 Yahweh, \add when they were distressed\add*,
\q1 the \add people\add* \add went to find you\add* with their quiet \add request\add*, when you’d \add disciplined\add* them.
\q1
\v 17 Like a pregnant \add woman\add* who’s close to giving birth cries out from her labour pains,
\q1 that’s what we were like \add in front\add* of you, Yahweh.
\q1
\v 18 \add It’s like\add* we were pregnant and in labour, giving birth to wind.
\q1 We haven’t \add rescued anyone\add* on the earth,
\q1 and the world’s inhabitants haven’t fallen.
\b
\q1
\v 19 Your dead will live—their corpses will rise.
\q1 Wake up and sing happily, you all who’ve lived in the dust,
\q1 because your dew is the dew \add that gives\add* light
\q1 and the earth \add will release her dead\add*.
\s1 Judgement is coming then restoration
\p
\v 20 \add Go\add* my people—enter into your rooms and shut the door behind you.
\q1 Hide a \add little while\add* until the indignation has passed by.
\q1
\v 21 Listen, Yahweh is about to come out of his place, \add to punish\add* all the world’s inhabitants,
\q1 and the earth will reveal \add all\add* its bloodshed and will no longer cover over \add those who were killed\add*.
\c 27
\p
\v 1 \add At that time\add*, Yahweh will \add use his extremely powerful\add* sword,
\q1 to punish the slithering \add sea monster\add* Leviathan—Leviathan the twisting \add snake-like creature\add*,
\q1 and he’ll kill the monster that’s in the ocean.\x + \xo 27:1: \xt Yob 41:1; Psa 74:14; 104:26.\x*
\p
\v 2 \add When that happens\add*, sing \add about a delightful\add* vineyard.
\q1
\v 3 I, Yahweh, will \add look after\add* it.
\q1 I’ll \add keep\add* it \add watered\add* in case someone \add attacks\add* it.
\q1 I’ll guard it night and day.
\q1
\v 4 I don’t have \add any\add* anger—who will give me thorn bushes?
\q1 I will march against it—I’ll \add completely burn it up\add*.
\q1
\v 5 If anyone takes \add advantage\add* of my protection,
\q1 then they’ll make peace to me—
\q1 let them make peace with me.
\p
\v 6 The (time) is coming when Yakov \add (Jacob)\add* will take root.
\q1 Yisrael \add (Israel)\add* will blossom and bud,
\q1 and they’ll fill the world with fruit.
\p
\v 7 Has he attacked \add us\add* like he attacked those who attacked \add us\add*,
\q1 or did he kill \add us\add* like he killed those who killed \add us\add*?
\q1
\v 8 \add By sending her away, you have contended with her\add*.
\q1 He released his fierce breath on an east-wind day.
\q1
\v 9 So Yakob’s \add disobedience\add* \add will be made right again\add* by that,
\q1 and this is all the fruit of the removal of his sin:
\q1 when he’ll make all the altar stones like pulverised pieces of chalk.
\q1 No Asherah poles or incense altars will \add remain\add* standing,
\q1
\v 10 because the fortified city is desolate.
\q1 That habitation is deserted and abandoned like a wilderness.
\q1 A calf grazes there, then it will lie down.
\p It will bring its branches to an end—
\q1
\v 11 when its branches dry up, they’ll be broken \add off\add*.
\q1 Women will come and \add light fires with them\add* because they’re not a people with understanding.
\q1 Therefore the \add one\add* who made and formed it, won’t show \add any\add* favour towards it.
\p
\v 12 Then \add at that time\add*, Yahweh will thresh \add people\add*
\q1 from the Euphrates river \add in the northeast\add* to Egypt’s river \add down in the southwest\add*,
\q1 and you \add Israelis\add* will be gathered \add in\add* one by one.
\q1
\v 13 Then on that \add same\add* day, a \add loud\add* trumpet will be blown,
\q1 and those who are perishing in Assyria will come
\q1 along with those who were banished to Egypt,
\q1 and they will bow down to Yahweh on Yerushalem’s sacred mountain.
\c 28
\s1 A warning for Shomron \add (Samaria)\add*
\p
\v 1 \add You won’t end well\add* \add Shomron\add*, you proud crown of Efrayim’s drunkards
\q1 or it’s beauty \add and\add* splendour that’s fading like a flower \add past its prime\add*.
\q1 There at the head of a lush valley that’s struck down by wine.
\q1
\v 2 Look, the master \add is sending\add* a \add very powerful\add* \add one\add*,
\q1 like a hailstorm, a destructive windstorm, or a \add huge flood\add*.
\q1 He’ll drive it down to the ground with \add his\add* hand.
\q1
\v 3 The proud crown of Efrayim’s drunkards will be trampled \add underfoot\add*.
\q1
\v 4 The fading flower of its beauty \add and\add* splendour at the head of a lush valley
\q1 will be like a \add very\add* early fig before summer.
\q1 The \add ones\add* who see it \add will grab it and\add* swallow it.
\p
\v 5 \add At that time,\add* Commander-in-chief Yahweh will become a beautiful crown,
\q1 and a splendid diadem for the remnant of his people,
\q1
\v 6 and a spirit of justice for \add those who need judgements\add*,
\q1 and strength for those who turn the battle back at the \add gates\add*.
\s1 Yehudah’s drunken prophets
\p
\v 7 Even those reeled from wine
\q1 and stagger from strong drink.
\q1 Priest and prophet reeled from the strong drink,
\q1 and they were confused by from the wine.
\q1 They staggered from the strong drink—
\q1 reeling in vision, they stagger in \add indecision\add*.
\q1
\v 8 \add Indeed,\add* all their tables are \add covered with\add* vomit—
\q1 \add there’s no place without\add* filth.
\p
\v 9 Who will he teach knowledge \add to\add*,
\q1 and who will he get to understand the message?
\q1 Those who’ve been weaned from milk—
\q1 who’ve already been taken off the breasts.
\p
\v 10 Because it’s ‘command to command to command, line to line to line, a little there, a little there’.\f + \fr 28:10 \ft The Hebrew for this verse (and v13) includes ‘tsav latsav, tsav latsav, kav lakav, kav lakav,’ etc., suggesting that it might possibly have been intended as drunken gibberish.\f*
\p
\v 11 \add Indeed,\add* with stammering lips and foreign language,
\q1 he will speak to this people \add group\add*\x + \xo 28:11-12: \xt 1Cor 14:21.\x*
\q1
\v 12 telling them, ‘This is the resting \add place\add* \add where\add* the weary \add ones\add* can rest’,
\q1 and, ‘This is the place for refreshing’.
\q1 \add but\add* they weren’t willing to listen.
\q1
\v 13 So Yahweh’s message to them,
\q1 ‘command to command to command, line to line to line, a little there, a little there’,
\q1 so they can go, \add but\add* they’ll stumble backwards and will be broken,
\q1 \add plus\add* they’ll become trapped and will be captured.
\s1 A vital foundation for Tsiyyon/Zion
\p
\v 14 Therefore, listen to Yahweh’s message,
\q1 you people \add who are always mocking\add*,
\q1 you rulers of the people \add there\add* in Yerushalem,
\q1
\v 15 because you’ve all said, “We’ve come to an agreement with death,
\q1 and we have an understanding with the grave.
\q1 When the overwhelming scourge goes past,
\q1 it won’t \add bother\add* us because we’ve made lies our shelter,
\q1 and we hide in deception.”
\q1
\v 16 Therefore, my master Yahweh says:
\q1 Look, I’ve put a \add foundation\add* stone \add in place\add* in Tsiyyon—\add one\add* that’s been tested.
\q1 \add It’s a\add* valuable cornerstone—a reliable foundation.
\q1 Anyone who trusts \add in it\add* won’t \add have to\add* \add rush away\add*.\x + \xo 28:16: \xt Rom 9:33; 10:11; 1Pe 2:6.\x*
\q1
\v 17 Then I’ll make justice into a measuring stick,
\q1 and righteous into a levelling tool.
\q1 Hail will sweep away the shelter of lies,
\q1 and \add floods\add* will drown the hiding place.\x + \xo 28:17b: \xt 28:15b.\x*
\q1
\v 18 Then your agreement with death will be dissolved,
\q1 and your understanding with the grave \add will collapse\add*.
\q1 When the overwhelming scourge comes past,
\q1 →you’ll all be overwhelmed by it.\x + \xo 28:18: \xt 28:15.\x*
\q1
\v 19 When it comes past, it’ll take you all
\q1 because it’ll come past morning by morning, \add and\add* day and night.
\p Understanding the message will bring only terror,
\q1
\v 20 because the bed is too short for stretching yourself out on,
\q1 and the woven \add blanket\add* is too narrow to wrap around you.
\q1
\v 21 Yahweh will \add take action like he did\add* at Mt. Peratsim.\x + \xo 28:21: \xt 2Sa 5:20, 1Ch 14:11.\x*
\q1 He’ll \add stir himself up like he did\add* in Giveon valley\x + \xo 28:21: \xt Josh 10:10-12.\x*
\q1 to do his work—his special work.
\q1 To perform his task—his special task.
\v 22 \add So\add* now, don’t show yourselves to be mockers
\q1 in case your \add chains become heavier\add*,
\q1 because I’ve heard from my master, Commander-in-chief Yahweh
\q1 about complete destruction and \add the rest\add* that’s been determined against the entire land.
\s1 The wisdom of God
\p
\v 23 \add Listen carefully\add* to \add what I say\add*.
\q1 Pay attention \add to my words\add*.
\q1
\v 24 Does a \add farmer spend all day ploughing and not sow anything\add*?
\q1 Does he \add just continue\add* to \add break up\add* and harrow his land?
\q1
\v 25 Doesn’t he level its surface and scatter fennel and sow cumin,
\q1 and put the wheat in rows and the barley in plots, and spelt \add around\add* the border?
\q1
\v 26 \add Yes,\add* his god instructs him,
\q1 he teaches him to \add make good decisions\add*.
\q1
\v 27 Fennel isn’t threshed with a threshing board,
\q1 nor is a cart wheel rolled over cumin,
\q1 but rather, fennel is beaten with a stick,
\q1 and cumin with a rod.
\q1
\v 28 \add Grain for\add* bread \add must be ground\add* because anyone threshing it doesn’t \add keep at it\add* forever.
\q1 He \add can run his cart wheel over it\add* and his horses don’t crush it.
\q1
\v 29 That too comes from Commander-in-chief Yahweh
\q1 who \add gives good advice\add*—he has great wisdom.
\c 29
\s1 The siege of Yerushalem
\p
\v 1 \add You won’t end well\add* Ariel—the town where David camped.
\q1 Year \add follows\add* year—let the holidays come around,
\q1
\v 2 \add but\add* I’ll bring distress to Ariel
\q1 and there’ll be mourning and wailing
\q1 and it’ll become like an altar hearth\f + \fr 29:2 \ft Here we use one of the possible translations of ‘ʼArīʼēl’ (rather than transliterating it as a name), but none of those three possible options seem to make a lot of sense.\f* to me.
\q1
\v 3 Then I’ll \add get troops\add* \add to camp all around you and besiege\add* you—
\q1 \add building towers and ramps against your fortified walls\add*.
\q1
\v 4 You’ll be \add brought down\add* and will speak from the ground,
\q1 and your \add words will come\add* from the dust.
\q1 Your voice will sound like a spirit speaking out of the ground,
\q1 and your speech will whisper from the dust.
\p
\v 5 \add But\add* the multitude of foreigners will be like fine dust,
\q1 and that mass of ruthless \add people\add* will be like chaff \add that gets blown away\add*.
\q1 and it \add will happen so suddenly\add*.
\q1
\v 6 Commander-in-chief Yahweh \add will send\add* thunder, an earthquake, and a loud noise,
\q1 a strong gale, a windstorm and a fire \add burning things up\add*.
\q1
\v 7 It’ll be like a dream—a vision in the night.
\q1 Many of \add the world’s\add* nations will go to war against Ariel.
\q1 All those will \add attack\add* its fortifications and put her under distress.
\q1
\v 8 It’ll be like a hungry \add person\add* dreaming and eating \add in the dream\add*, then waking up with an empty \add stomach\add*.
\q1 Or like a thirsty \add person\add* dreaming and drinking \add in the dream\add*, then waking up with a dry throat and feeling faint.
\q1 That’s what it’ll be like for all those nations which go to war against Mt. Tsiyyon (Zion).
\s1 Compromised prophets
\p
\v 9 Astonish yourselves and be astonished.
\q1 Blind yourselves and be blind.
\q1 Get drunk, but not with wine.
\q1 Stagger, but not from strong drink,
\q1
\v 10 because Yahweh has poured a spirit of deep sleep out onto you all,\x + \xo 29:10: \xt Rom 11:8.\x*
\q1 and has shut your prophets’ eyes,
\q1 and has covered your visionaries’ heads.
\q1
\v 11 Then to you all, the entire vision will be like the words sealed in a scroll—
\q1 if it’s handed to \add a person who’s educated\add* to read out, they’ll say, ‘I can’t, because it is sealed up.’
\q1
\v 12 ^\add Or if\add* the scroll is given to \add an uneducated person\add* to read out, they’ll say, ‘I can’t read.’
\p
\v 13 My master says,
\q1 “\add Yes,\add* \add those people\add* come close to me with \add what their mouths say\add*,
\q1 and honour me with \add lipservice\add*,
\q1 \add but\add* their heart is far from me,
\q1 and their \add respect\add* for me is \add just something\add* that they’ve been taught \add to do\add*.\x + \xo 29:13: \xt Mat 15:8-9; Mrk 7:6-7.\x*
\q1
\v 14 Because of that, I’ll confound those people again with wonder upon wonder.
\q1 The wisdom of the wise will vanish,
\q1 and the intelligence of the intelligent will be hidden.”\f + \fr 29:14 \ft Septuagint: \fqa I will destroy the wisdom of the wise, and will hide the intelligence of the intelligent. \ft Cited in \xt 1 Corinthians 1:19.\f*\x + \xo 29:14: \xt 1Cor 1:19.\x*
\s1 Hope for the future
\p
\v 15 Those who \add keep\add* their plans down deep to hide them from Yahweh, \add won’t end well\add*,
\q1 and they did \add what they wanted\add* in dark places, saying, “Who can see us? Who \add could\add* know \add what we’re doing\add*?”
\q1
\v 16 Your \add thinking is crazy\add*!
\q1 It’s as if the potter’s clay, the thing that was made by him, would be considered to say, ‘He didn’t make me.’
\q1 Or if the pot said to the potter, ‘He doesn’t understand.’\x + \xo 29:16: \xt Isa 45:9; Rom 9:20.\x*
\p
\v 17 Hasn’t it been just a little while,
\q1 and Lebanon will turn into an orchard,
\q1 and the orchard will be considered as a forest?\x + \xo 29:17 \xt 32:15\x*
\p
\v 18 \add At that time\add*, deaf \add people\add* will \add be able to\add* hear the words from a scroll,
\q1 and from \add their\add* gloom and darkness, the eyes of blind \add people\add* will \add be able to\add* see.
\q1
\v 19 The \add people of low status\add* will \add be happy again because of\add* Yahweh,
\q1 and the poor \add people\add* \add among us\add* will \add celebrate because of\add* Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*,
\q1
\v 20 because ruthless \add people\add* and \add mockers\add* will come to an end,
\q1 and all those who \add plan wicked schemes\add* will be \add eliminated\add*—
\q1
\v 21 those who \add give false evidence\add* against a person,
\q1 and lay a trap at the \add city\add* gate for \add the person\add* who arbitrates,
\q1 and who \add deprive the innocent\add* \add person\add* \add of justice\add*.
\p
\v 22 That’s why Yahweh (who redeemed Avraham) says this to Yakob’s \add descendants\add*:
\q1 “\add My people\add* will no longer be ashamed—
\q1 no longer will their faces be pale \add with fear\add*,
\q1
\v 23 because when they see their children who are the result of my work among them,
\q1 they will \add regard my name and reputation as\add* sacred
\q1 and they will regard \add me\add* as sacred and \add and will show respect\add* \add to me\add*.
\q1
\v 24 Then those whose spirits go astray, will know understanding,
\q1 and those who murmur will learn insight.
\c 30
\s1 Yehudah’s worthless treaty with Egypt
\p
\v 1 Yahweh declares that \add you\add* rebellious children \add won’t end well\add*.
\q1 \add You’re\add* \add making plans that don’t come\add* from me,
\q1 and pouring out drink offerings \add but\add* not by my spirit,
\q1 thus adding \add disobedience\add* to \add disobedience\add*.
\q1
\v 2 Those who go down to Egypt \add didn’t ask my advice\add*,
\q1 \add before\add* trying to reach safety with Far-oh \add (Pharaoh)\add*,
\q1 and trying to find security in Egypt’s \add (Heb. Mitsrayim’s)\add* shadow.
\q1
\v 3 \add But\add* Far’oh’s safety \add will bring you all shame\add*,
\q1 and Egypt’s \add security\add* \add will bring you all humiliation\add*,
\q1
\v 4 because its officials have been in Tsoan,
\q1 and its messengers have reached Hanes.
\q1
\v 5 Everyone will be ashamed because of a \add nation\add* that won’t benefit them—
\q1 not help, nor advantage, \add but\add* shame and even disgrace.
\p
\v 6 \add This\add* is a \add message\add* about the Negev \add desert’s\add* animals:
\q1 In the \add area\add* of trouble and \add danger\add*
\q1 from the lioness and the lion,
\q1 and the viper and the flying serpent,
\q1 they carry their wealth on donkeys’ shoulders
\q1 and their treasures on camels’ humps,
\q1 to a \add nation\add* that \add can’t help them\add*.
\q1
\v 7 Egypt’s ‘help’ is futile and meaningless,
\q1 so I’ve called her ‘Rahab who just sits there’.
\s1 The disobedient people
\p
\v 8 Now go \add to\add* them \add and\add* write it on a tablet—
\q1 inscribe it on a scroll
\q1 so that it’ll be there for a future day—
\q1 \add something that’ll endure\add* forever
\q1
\v 9 because this is a rebellious \add nation\add*.
\q1 \add They’re\add* lying children—unwilling to listen to Yahweh’s instructions,
\q1
\v 10 who tell \add those who see visions\add*, “Don’t see.”
\q1 And \add tell\add* the prophets, “Don’t show us ‘what’s right’—
\q1 Just flatter us and give us deceptive messages.”
\q1
\v 11 Turn off the \add road\add*.
\q1 \add Go on a different\add* path.
\q1 Keep Yisrael’s holy \add one\add* away from us.
\p
\v 12 Therefore Yisrael’s holy \add one\add* says,
\q1 “Because you’ve all rejected this message
\q1 and have trusted in oppression and \add perversion\add* and depended on it,
\q1
\v 13 then that \add disobedience\add* will become your \add downfall\add*,
\q1 →like a bulge in a high wall that will \add at some unexpected time\add*, suddenly come \add smashing down\add*.
\q1
\v 14 It’ll be like the smashing of a \add clay\add* jar—\add completely shattered\add*.
\q1 Among the fragments, a person wouldn’t be able to find a piece \add big enough\add* to \add pick up a hot coal from the fire\add*,
\q1 or to dip some water out of a cistern \add to drink\add*.”
\p
\v 15 So this is what Yisrael’s holy \add one\add* says,
\q1 “You’ll all be saved by returning and \add quietly\add* \add waiting\add*.
\q1 Your strength will \add come from\add* quietness and \add confidence\add*,
\q1 →but you all weren’t willing.
\q1
\v 16 You all said, ‘Nah, we’ll flee away on horses,’
\q1 and indeed you all will flee,
\q1 and \add you said\add*, ‘We’ll ride on swift horses,’
\q1 but those who chase after you all will prove to be swifter.
\q1
\v 17 A thousand \add will flee\add* from the threat of \add just\add* one.
\q1 You’ll all flee from the threat of five \add of the enemy\add*
\q1 until you’re left like \add a lone\add* flagstaff on the top of a mountain
\q1 or like a banner \add poked into\add* a hill.”
\s1 Yahweh will bless his people
\p
\v 18 And yet Yahweh is waiting to show favour to you all,
\q1 so he \add takes action\add* to show you mercy
\q1 because Yahweh is a god of justice.
\q1 Those who wait for him \add to rescue them\add* will be blessed,
\q1
\v 19 because people will live in Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*—in Yerushalem.
\q1 You certainly won’t weep anymore because at the sound of your crying out, he’ll show favour to you.
\q1 As soon as he hears, he’ll answer you.
\q1
\v 20 My master will give you distress for your \add food\add*
\q1 and oppression for your water,
\q1 and your teacher will no longer hide himself,
\q1 \add so\add* you’ll see \add him\add* will your own eyes.
\q1
\v 21 Your ears will hear a \add command\add* coming from behind you saying,
\q1 ‘That’s \add the right way to go\add*,’
\q1 \add so you’ll be guided whether\add* you go to the right or to the left.
\q1
\v 22 Then you all will desecrate your silver-plated idols
\q1 and your gold-sheathed images.
\q1 You’ll throw them away like a menstrual rag
\q1 and you’ll say, ‘\add You piece of\add* filth!’
\q1
\v 23 Then he’ll give you rain for the seed that you’ve planted in the ground,
\q1 →and the soil will produce \add plenty of\add* food,
\q1 and your livestocks will graze in wide pastures \add at that time\add*.
\q1
\v 24 The bulls and the male donkeys that till the ground
\q1 →will eat \add human-quality grain that’s been properly\add* winnowed.
\q1
\v 25 On every high mountain and every \add substantial\add* hill,
\q1 there’ll be streams \add flowing\add* with water,
\q1 \add at the time\add* of much slaughter when fortified towers \add are defeated\add*.
\q1
\v 26 The light from the moon will be like the light from the sun,
\q1 and the sun’s light will be seven times brighter
\q1 at the time when Yahweh bandages up his people’s fracture
\q1 and when he heals their \add severe\add* wound.
\s1 Yahweh’s judgement for Assyria
\p
\v 27 Look, Yahweh is coming from far away.
\q1 He’s \add very angry\add* and \add his weight ascends\add*.
\q1 His lips are full of indignation
\q1 and his tongue is like a consuming fire.
\q1
\v 28 His breath is like a \add rushing river\add* that comes up to the neck,
\q1 to sift the nations in a sieve \add that separates out\add* worthlessness,
\q1 and \add with\add* a bridle in the people’s jaws to lead them astray.
\q1
\v 29 You’ll all have \add your own\add* song like you would at a \add religious\add* festival,
\q1 and \add be happy inside\add* like when someone walks to Yahweh’s mountain with \add their\add* flute—
\q1 \add going\add* to Yisrael’s rock \add that gives protection\add*.
\p
\v 30 Then Yahweh will make his majestic voice heard
\q1 and lowering his arm, he’ll reveal his raging anger and the consuming flame,
\q1 \add as well as\add* a windstorm, a rainstorm, and a hailstorm,
\q1
\v 31 because Yahweh’s voice will shatter Ashshur \add (Assyria)\add*—
\q1 he’ll strike them with a rod.
\q1
\v 32 With every stroke from the \add punishing\add* rod that he puts \add across\add* them,
\q1 there’ll be tambourines and harps as he fights them in battle—brandishing \add his arm\add*,
\q1
\v 33 because a cremation place was arranged \add long ago\add*.
\q1 Indeed, it’s been prepared for the \add Assyrian\add* king.
\q1 Its funeral pyre is deep and wide with the firewood piled high.
\q1 Yahweh’s breath will ignite it like a stream of burning sulphur.
\c 31
\s1 Yahweh’s protection of Yerushalem
\p
\v 1 Those who go down to Egypt for help \add won’t end well\add*.
\q1 They depend on horses and rely on chariots that are many,
\q1 and on cavalry that are very numerous,
\q1 \add but\add* they don’t look \add towards\add* Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*,
\q1 and they don’t \add request help\add* from Yahweh.
\q1
\v 2 Yahweh is also wise and he brought calamity.
\q1 He hasn’t \add changed his mind since\add* his messages
\q1 and he’ll \add take action\add* against the place of evil-doers
\q1 and against those who do wicked \add things\add*.
\q1
\v 3 Egypt is human and not a god.
\q1 Their horses are \add physical and not spiritual\add*
\q1 and Yahweh will stretch out his hand and the ones \add trying\add* to help will stumble,
\q1 and the ones being helped will \add be defeated\add*,
\q1 →and all of them will \add die\add* together.
\q1
\p
\v 4 Because this is what Yahweh has told me,
\q1 “As a lion growls and the young lion \add growls\add* over its prey,
\q1 even if a \add large group\add* of shepherds \add shout at it\add*,
\q1 →it’s not \add put off\add* by their \add voices\add*
\q1 and it doesn’t cringe \add because of the commotion they make\add*,
\q1 →so too Commander-in-chief Yahweh will descend to go to war on Mt. Zion and its hill.
\q1
\v 5 Just like birds do, Commander-in-chief Yahweh will protect Yerushalem.
\q1 He’ll defend and rescue it—passing over it and saving it.”
\p
\v 6 \add You Yisraeli\add* people, return to the \add one\add* that you’ve \add seriously rebelled against\add*,
\v 7 because \add at that time\add*, \add everyone\add* will reject their gold and silver idols that you’ve all made with your \add disobedient\add* hands.
\q1
\v 8 Then Assyria will fall from a sword (but not a human one),
\q1 and a sword (not a human one) will destroy it.
\q1 It will flee away from \add that\add* sword,
\q1 and its young men will become forced labour.
\q1
\v 9 Their \add security\add* will pass away from terror,
\q1 and their officers will be dismayed from \add seeing the\add* banner \add flying\add*.
\q1 That’s the declaration from Yahweh who has fire in Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*
\q1 and a furnace in Yerushalem.
\c 32
\s1 Predicting an honest government
\p
\v 1 Listen, a king will reign \add with fairness\add*,
\q1 and officials will rule with justice.
\q1
\v 2 Each of them will be like a hiding place from the wind
\q1 and a shelter in a rainstorm.
\q1 They’ll be like streams in the desert,
\q1 \add and\add* like the shade from a large rock in an \add arid\add* land.
\q1
\v 3 Then won’t the eyes of those who see, look,
\q1 and the ears of those who hear, pay attention?
\q1
\v 4 Then the heart of the hasty will understand knowledge,
\q1 and the tongue of stutterers will \add speak fluently and clearly\add*.
\q1
\v 5 The fool won’t be called ‘noble’ any more,
\q1 and scoundrels \add will no longer be respected\add*,
\q1
\v 6 because the fool speaks foolishness
\q1 and his heart \add plans disobedience\add* for doing ungodly \add things\add*
\q1 and by speaking error about Yahweh.
\q1 He keeps those empty who have a hungry appetite,
\q1 and he deprives those who are thirsty.
\q1
\v 7 As for the scoundrel, evil is his weapon.
\q1 He plans to ruin those \add already\add* suffering with false \add stories\add*,
\q1 and speaks \add against\add* justice for the needy.
\q1
\v 8 \add In contrast,\add* the honourable person plans to do honourable \add things\add*,
\q1 and they will stand on \add those\add* noble \add deeds\add*.
\s1 Yerushalem’s women in despair
\p
\v 9 \add Take action, you\add* carefree women.
\q1 Listen to my voice \add you\add* confident daughters.
\q1 \add Pay attention to what I have to say\add*.
\q1
\v 10 \add In just over\add* a year \add you\add* confident \add women\add* will be agitated
\q1 because the grape harvest will fail and the \add fruit\add* gathering \add won’t happen\add*.
\q1
\v 11 Tremble \add you\add* carefree \add women\add*.
\q1 Be agitated \add you\add* confident \add women\add*.
\q1 Strip yourselves bare then put \add sackcloth\add* around your \add waists\add*.
\q1
\v 12 Beat your breasts \add with grief\add* over the pleasant fields
\q1 \add and\add* over the fruitful grapevines.
\q1
\v 13 My people’s land has thorns and thistles growing up over it—
\q1 \add even\add* in all the happy homes in the cheery town,
\q1
\v 14 because the palace will be abandoned.
\q1 The busy city will be deserted.
\q1 The hill and the watchtower \add will forever be like caves\add*—
\q1 a delight for the wild donkeys and a pasture for the flocks
\q1
\v 15 until the spirit is poured \add down\add* on us from up high,
\q1 and the wilderness becomes an orchard,
\q1 and the \add orchard\add* is considered as a forest.\x + \xo 32:15 \xt 29:17\x*
\q1
\v 16 Then justice will live in the wilderness,
\q1 and righteousness will stay in the orchard.
\q1
\v 17 The \add result of their doing what’s right\add* will be peace,
\q1 and the service of righteousness will be quietness and permanent security.
\q1
\v 18 Then my people will live \add peacefully\add*,
\q1 and in secure \add homes\add* and undisturbed resting places.
\q1
\v 19 It will hail when the forest comes down,
\q1 and the city will be \add completely levelled\add*.
\q1
\v 20 You all who sow \add wherever there’s water\add*, will be blessed—
\q1 you all who untie your cow and donkey \add to give them free range\add*.
\c 33
\s1 Yahweh pushes Assyria away
\p
\v 1 The destroyer \add won’t end well\add*, \add but\add* you haven’t been destroyed.
\q1 The one who acts treacherously hasn’t been dealt with treacherously.
\q1 When you finish destroying, \add that’s when\add* you’ll be destroyed.
\q1 When you’ve stopped dealing treacherously, \add that’s when people\add* will deal treacherously with you.
\p
\v 2 Yahweh, show your favour to us because we’ve waited for your \add help\add*.
\q1 Be \add our strength each\add* morning as well as our \add rescuer when trouble comes\add*.
\q1
\v 3 The peoples flee \add when they hear the commotion\add*.
\q1 When you \add took action\add*, the nations were scattered.
\q1
\v 4 You all gather the plunder like locusts—
\q1 like locusts swarming in over it.
\p
\v 5 Yahweh is \add praised\add* because he lives in a high \add place\add*.
\q1 He will \add rule\add* Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* \add by doing what’s both right and fair\add*.
\q1
\v 6 \add He will be your constant source of stability\add*—
\q1 \add a large supply of security\add*, wisdom, and knowledge.
\q1 \add Respect and honour\add* for Yahweh will be its treasure.
\p
\v 7 Look, their \add warriors\add* have cried outside—
\q1 the messengers of peace weep bitterly.
\q1
\v 8 The highways are deserted—
\q1 no one is going past on the paths.
\q1 Agreements are broken, \add people avoid cities\add*, no one values people.
\q1
\v 9 The land has dried up and \add become unproductive\add*.
\q1 Lebanon is ashamed \add and\add* has withered.
\q1 The Sharon \add plain\add* is like the desert,
\q1 and Bashan and Karmel are \add losing their leaves\add*.
\s1 Yahweh warns his enemies
\p
\v 10 “Now I’ll \add take action\add*” says Yahweh.
\q1 “Now I’ll \add be praised\add*.
\q1 Now I’ll be elevated.
\q1
\v 11 You’ll all conceive chaff \add and\add* give birth to stubble.
\q1 Your breath is a fire that will devour you all.
\q1
\v 12 The people will be burnt \add down into ashes\add*,
\q1 \add like\add* thorn bushes cut down and burnt \add in a heap\add*.
\q1
\v 13 \add You who are\add* far away, listen to what I’ve done.
\q1 ^and you all who are nearby, \add feel\add* my strength.”
\p
\v 14 The sinners in Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* are very afraid—
\q1 trembling has seized the godless.
\q1 “\add How\add* can we stay \add in this place\add* with a devouring fire?
\q1 \add Which of us can live with continual burning\add*?”
\q1
\v 15 \add The one who\add* \add does what’s right\add*,
\q1 and \add is honest in what they say\add*,
\q1 who rejects dishonest gain from extortion,
\q1 and who \add avoids shaking hands on a deal involving a bribe\add*,
\q1 who \add refuses to listen\add* to \add ideas of\add* \add murder\add*,
\q1 and who \add won’t let\add* his eyes look into evil \add schemes\add*,
\q1
\v 16 \add that person\add* will live in high \add places\add*—
\q1 the mountain fortress will be their refuge.
\q1 They’ll have a reliable source of food and water.
\s1 The ruling king
\p
\v 17 Your eyes will see the king in his beauty.
\q1 They’ll see a distant land.
\q1
\v 18 Your heart will \add recall the\add* terror.
\q1 “Where’s the \add taxation\add* \add accountant\add*? Where’s the one doing the weighing?
\q1 Where’s the one who counted the towers?”
\q1
\v 19 You’ll no longer see \add those fierce\add* people
\q1 \add whose language is too confusing to comprehend\add*
\q1 \add and\add* \add whose sounds are too foreign to understand\add*.
\q1
\v 20 Look at Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*, the town of our \add festivals\add*.
\q1 Your eyes will see Yerushalem—a place to live undisturbed.
\q1 No tents will be packed up and no tent pegs will ever be pulled out,
\q1 and none of its ropes will be \add snapped\add*.
\q1
\v 21 Yahweh the majestic \add one\add* will be there with us—
\q1 a place with rivers and wide canals.
\q1 No ship that’s rowed will be able to go over it,
\q1 and no \add huge sailing\add* ships will pass along it.
\q1
\v 22 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh is our judge—\add he’s\add* our commander.
\q1 Yahweh is our king—he’ll rescue us.
\q1
\v 23 Your ropes are coming undone—they can’t secure the base of the mast.
\q1 They can’t spread the sail out.
\q1 Then the large booty onboard will be divided as plunder—
\q1 even lame people will take some spoil.
\q1
\v 24 None of the residents will say that they’re sick—
\q1 the people who live there will be forgiven \add for their disobedience\add*.
\c 34
\s1 Yahweh punishes his enemies
\p
\v 1 Come close \add you\add* nations to listen.
\q1 and \add you\add* peoples pay attention.
\q1 The earth and everything that fills it must listen—
\q1 the world and everything that it’s produced.
\q1
\v 2 Yahweh is very angry at all the nations
\q1 and furious at all their armies.
\q1 He’ll completely destroy them—
\q1 he’ll hand them over to be slaughtered.
\q1
\v 3 Then their slain will be tossed out
\q1 and the hills will soak up their blood,
\q1 and their corpses will release a stench.
\q1
\v 4 All the stars in the sky will rot away,
\q1 and the skies will be rolled up like a scroll.
\q1 All their objects will wither like leaves falling off a grapevine,
\q1 and like withered fruit \add dropping\add* off a fig tree.\x + \xo 34:4: \xt Mat 24:29; Mrk 13:25; Luk 21:26; Rev 6:13-14.\x*
\p
\v 5 \add Once\add* my sword will have drunk its fill in the skies/heavens,
\q1 look, it will descend on Edom and on the people who \add will receive\add* total destruction as my judgement.\x + \xo 34:5-17: \xt Isa 63:1-6; Jer 49:7-22; Eze 25:12-14; 35:1-15; Amos 1:11-12; Oba 1-14; Mal 1:2-5.\x*
\q1
\v 6 Yahweh’s sword is full of blood and fattened with fat
\q1 from the blood of lambs and goats, and from the fat from rams’ kidneys,
\q1 because Yahweh has a sacrifice in Botsrah,
\q1 and a great slaughter in the \add nation\add* of Edom.
\q1
\v 7 Wild bulls will go down with them,
\q1 as well as young bulls and powerful \add ones\add*.
\q1 Their land will drink its fill of blood,
\q1 and the dust will be \add smeared\add* with fat,
\q1
\v 8 because Yahweh will have his day of vengeance—
\q1 a year of retribution for Tsiyyon’s \add (Zion’s)\add* sake.
\p
\v 9 Its streams will be changed into tar,
\q1 and its dust into sulfur,
\q1 and its land will become burning pitch.
\q1
\v 10 \add It’ll burn\add* night and day and its smoke will permanently go up.
\q1 It’ll be a wasteland \add throughout\add* the generations
\q1 and no one will \add ever\add* pass through it again.\x + \xo 34:10: \xt Rev 14:11; 19:3.\x*
\q1
\v 11 \add Desert owls and hedgehogs\add* will take it over—
\q1 owls and ravens will live there.
\q1 \add Yahweh\add* will stretch the measuring line of ruin over it
\q1 and \add plumb lines\add* of \add destruction\add*.
\q1
\v 12 Its nobles \add will have nothing left to call a kingdom\add*,
\q1 and all its princes \add will become nobodies\add*.
\q1
\v 13 Thorns will grow up its fortresses.
\q1 Nettles and thornbushes will \add grow\add* on its \add high walls\add*,
\q1 and it’ll become a \add place for jackals to live in\add*—
\q1 grass for \add ostriches\add*.
\q1
\v 14 \add Wild animals\add* will meet hyenas,
\q1 and the wild goats will \add bleat\add* to \add each other\add*.
\q1 The lilith owl\f + \fr 34:14 \ft See article on ‘lilith’ at https://www.sil.org/resources/publications/entry/111035.\f* will rest there,
\q1 and find a place for itself to \add nest\add*.
\q1
\v 15 \add Owls\add* will nest and lay eggs there,
\q1 and hatch and brood \add the chicks\add* in its shade.
\q1 Indeed the \add hawks\add* will gather there with their \add mates\add*.
\p
\v 16 \add Look through\add* Yahweh’s scroll and read—not one of them will be missing.
\q1 Not one will lack its \add mate\add* because \add Yahweh\add* has commanded it,
\q1 and his spirit will gather them \add there\add*.
\q1
\v 17 He has thrown \add dice\add* for them,
\q1 and his hand divided out \add their territory\add* with a measuring line.
\q1 It’ll be theirs forever—they’ll live there \add throughout the generations\add*.
\c 35
\s1 The happiness of those saved by God
\q1
\v 1 The wilderness and the desert will \add celebrate\add*,
\q1 and the Aravah \add plain\add* will be happy and blossom like a lily.
\q1
\v 2 It will blossom \add widely\add* and be glad,
\q1 even with happiness and cheery shouting.
\q1 Lebanon’s glory will be given to it,
\q1 \add as well as\add* the splendour of Carmel and Sharon.
\q1 They will see Yahweh’s \add brightness\add*—the splendour of our god.
\b
\q1
\v 3 Strengthen the limp hands,
\q1 and steady the stumbling knees.\x + \xo 35:3: \xt Heb 12:12.\x*
\q1
\v 4 Tell those with \add anxious\add* \add hearts\add*,
\q1 “Be strong—don’t be afraid.
\q1 Listen, your god will come with vengeance—
\q1 \add paying them back for what they’ve done\add*.
\q1 →He himself will come and rescue you.”
\b
\q1
\v 5 Then the blind \add will be able to see again\add*,
\q1 and deaf \add people\add* will be able to hear.\x + \xo 35:5-6: \xt Mat 11:5; Luk 7:22.\x*
\q1
\v 6 Then the lame \add person\add* will leap like a deer
\q1 and the \add one who’s mute\add* will shout happily
\q1 because \add springs\add* will burst out in the wilderness,
\q1 and streams in the Aravah \add plain\add*.
\q1
\v 7 The parched ground will become a pool,
\q1 and the thirsty place \add will become\add* springs of water.
\q1 The place where jackals lived \add and relaxed\add*
\q1 →will \add grow grass\add*, reeds, and papyrus.
\b
\q1
\v 8 There’ll be a highway \add to travel on\add*
\q1 →and it’ll be called ‘the sacred road’.
\q1 The ‘unclean’ won’t use it
\q1 \add but it’ll be for those walking in the right direction\add*—
\q1 fools won’t \add be allowed\add* to wander onto it.
\q1
\v 9 There’ll be no lions there
\q1 and no dangerous wild animals on it.
\q1 Those \add creatures\add* won’t be found there,
\q1 \add but\add* those \add people\add* \add who’ve been bought back\add* will walk on it.
\q1
\v 10 Then the \add people\add* ransomed by Yahweh will return
\q1 and they’ll come to Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* with a cheerful shout.
\q1 \add They’ll always be happy\add* and gladness and celebration will \add overwhelm\add* them,
\q1 and sorrow and groaning will \add disappear\add*.
\c 36
\s1 Assyria threatens Yerushalem
\r (2 Kgs 18:13-27; 2 Chr. 32:1-19)
\p
\v 1 In the fourteenth year of \add the reign of\add* King Hizkiyah \add (Hezekiah)\add*, Assyria’s King Sennacherib \add attacked\add* Yehudah’s fortified cities and captured them.
\v 2 Then from Lakish \add (Lachish)\add*, the Assyrian king sent \add his top negotiator\add* to King Hezekiah in Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* with a large army. He \add stopped\add* by the aqueduct at the upper pool on the road to the field \add where women wash clothes\add*,
\v 3 and Hilkiyah’s son Elyakim, \add the palace supervisor\add*, went out to meet him, \add taking\add* Shevna the \add administrator\add*, and Asaf’s son Yoah the \add secretary\add*.
\v 4 The \add negotiator\add* instructed them, “Tell Hizkiyah that Assyria’s powerful king wants to know \add who or what you think you’re trusting in to rescue you\add*?
\v 5 Your plan and war preparations are \add only hot air\add*, so who are you relying on \add that encourages you\add* to rebel against me?
\v 6 Listen, if it’s Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*, \add that’s like\add* trusting a staff made from a splintered reed. If a man were to lean on it, it would pierce his palm—that’s what relying on Egypt’s King Far-oh is like for those who put their trust in him.
\v 7 \add But\add* if you tell me that you’re relying on your god Yahweh, hasn’t Hizkiyah removed his hilltop shrines and altars, and \add forced all\add* Yehudah to worship him in front of the altar there in Yerushalem?
\p
\v 8 “\add So\add* now, make a deal with my master, the Assyrian king. Let me give you two thousand horses if you can \add find that many\add* riders for them.
\v 9 How could you \add even\add* repel a captain who’s one of the least of my master’s servants \add since\add* you’ve been relying on Egypt for chariots and horsemen \add to rescue you\add*?
\v 10 \add Also, listen,\add* I didn’t come here to destroy this \add region\add* without Yahweh—\add it was\add* Yahweh who told me to come \add here\add* and destroy \add this nation\add*.”
\p
\v 11 Then Elyakim and Shevna and Yoah \add asked\add* the \add negotiator\add*, “Please speak Aramaic to your servants, because we understand it. Don’t speak to us \add in Hebrew\add* in the \add hearing\add* of the people who are \add up\add* on the wall.”
\p
\v 12 \add But\add* the \add negotiator\add* \add replied\add*, “\add Do you think that\add* my master sent me to \add give this message\add* \add just\add* to you and your master? \add Don’t you think that it’s also for\add* the men sitting on the wall \add who’ll have to\add* \add join you in\add* eating their \add own\add* dung and drinking their \add own\add* urine?”
\p
\v 13 Then the \add negotiator\add* stood \add and looked up\add*, and \add shouted in Hebrew\add*, “Listen to this message from the great Assyrian king.
\v 14 The king says not to let \add your king\add* Hizkiyah deceive you all, because he won’t be able to save you.
\v 15 Don’t let \add him\add* make you \add rely on\add* Yahweh by telling you all that Yahweh will rescue you, and that this city won’t be \add captured by\add* the Assyrian king.
\v 16 \add No,\add* don’t listen to Hizkiyah, because the Assyrian king says that \add if you all surrender and come out here, you’ll be allowed to continue to harvest\add* your own grapevines and fig trees, and everyone will be able to drink the water from their own wells
\v 17 until I come and take you to a land like your own \add that has\add* grain and new wine—a land with bread and vineyards.
\p
\v 18 “\add Don’t let\add* Hizkiyah mislead you all by saying that Yahweh will rescue you. Did the gods of \add any other\add* nations saved them from the Assyrian king’s \add power\add*?
\v 19 Where were Hamat and Arpad’s gods? Where were Sefarvayim’s gods? \add Did any gods\add* save Shomron \add (Samaria)\add* from my \add power\add*?
\v 20 From all those \add regions\add*, which of their gods saved them from my \add power\add*, \add so what makes you all think that\add* Yahweh will save Yerushalem from \add me\add*.”
\p
\v 21 \add But\add* \add those on the wall\add* kept silent and didn’t answer him, because King \add Hizkiyah\add* had ordered them not to respond.
\v 22 Then Elyakim (Hilkiyah’s son who was the \add palace supervisor\add*) and Shevna (the \add administrator\add*) and Yoah (the \add secretary\add*) \add returned\add* to Hizkiyah with their clothes torn \add in grief\add* and \add passed the negotiator’s\add* messages on to him.
\c 37
\s1 Hizkiyah consults Yeshayah
\r (2 Kgs 19:1-7)
\p
\v 1 \add When\add* King Hizkiyah heard \add the report\add*, he torn his clothes \add too\add*, and covered himself with sackcloth and went into Yahweh’s \add residence\add*.
\v 2 Then he sent Elyakim (the \add palace supervisor\add*) and Shevna (the \add administrator\add*) and the elders of the priests to \add go to\add* Yeshayah \add (Isaiah)\add*, the son of Amots \add (Amos)\add* the prophet,
\v 3 and they told him, “\add King\add* Hizkiyah says that \add today\add* is a day of distress and rebuke and disgrace, \add like when children go to their mother who’s about to deliver her baby\add* \add but she doesn’t have the strength to\add* give birth.
\v 4 Perhaps your god Yahweh heard the messages from \add the negotiator\add* who was sent by his master, the Assyrian king, to defy the living god. \add Perhaps\add* \add Yahweh\add* will rebuke \add him for\add* the words that Yahweh heard. \add So send\add* up a prayer for the remnant \add of us here\add*.”
\p
\v 5 \add When\add* King Hizkiyah’s servants got to Yeshayah,
\v 6 \add he\add* told them to tell their master, “Yahweh says not to be afraid because of the words that you heard when the Assyrian king’s servants insulted me.
\v 7 Listen, I’ll put a spirit in him and he’ll hear a report \add that he needs\add* to return to his own \add country\add*, and then \add I’ll cause him to be assassinated at home\add*.”
\s1 A further threat from Assyria
\r (2 Kgs 19:8-9)
\p
\v 8 Then the \add Assyrian\add* \add negotiator\add* returned \add to find\add* the Assyrian king because he’d heard that he had left Lakish, and he found him fighting against Livnah.
\v 9 Then \add the king\add* heard that \add Ethiopia’s\add* King Tirhakah \add was marching out to attack him\add*, \add so\add* he sent messengers \add back\add* to Hizkiyah \add with instructions\add*,
\v 10 “Tell Yehudah’s King Hizkiyah: don’t let your god that you trust in, deceive you by telling \add you\add* that Yerushalem won’t be \add conquered by\add* the Assyrian king.
\v 11 Listen, you’ve heard how that the Assyrian kings have destroyed all the \add other\add* \add regions\add*. \add Don’t think that\add* you’ll be saved.
\v 12 Did the gods of those \add other\add* nations save them—\add places like\add* Gozan and Haran and Retsef, and the \add people\add* of Eden who \add lived\add* in Telassar?
\v 13 \add What happened to\add* the kings of Hamat, Arpad, La’ir, Sefarvayim, Hena, and Ivvah?”
\s1 Hizkiyah’s Prayer
\p
\v 14 Hizkiyah \add accepted\add* the letter brought by the messengers and read it. Then he went into Yahweh’s \add residence\add* and spread it out in front of Yahweh
\v 15 and prayed to Yahweh, saying,
\v 16 “Commander-in-chief Yahweh, Yisrael’s god, who’s enthroned above the winged creatures. You alone are God over all of earth’s kingdoms—you made the heavens and the earth.
\v 17 Yahweh, \add please pay attention\add* and listen. Open your eyes, Yahweh, and look, and listen to everything that Sennacherib has said to defy the living god.
\v 18 Yahweh, it’s true that the Assyrian kings have destroyed all \add those\add* \add nations\add* and their \add regions\add*,
\v 19 and \add his men\add* threw their gods into the fire, because they weren’t gods \add at all\add*—\add they’re just\add* \add crafted\add* from wood and stone, \add so\add* they destroyed them.
\v 20 \add But\add* now, Yahweh our god, save us from his \add power\add* so that all of the \add world’s\add* kingdoms will know that you alone are Yahweh \add who is God\add*.
\s1 Yeshayah’s message to Hizkiyah
\r (2 Kgs 19:20-37)
\p
\v 21 Then Amots’ son Yeshayah sent this message to \add King\add* Hizkiyah: “Yisrael’s god Yahweh says that because you prayed to me about the Assyrian King Sennacherib,
\v 22 then this is what Yahweh \add pronounces\add* about him:
\q1 Tsiyyon’s \add (Zion’s)\add* virgin daughter despises you—she scorns you.
\q1 \add Yerushalem’s\add* daughter shakes her head at you.
\q1
\v 23 Who is it that you’ve defied and insulted?
\q1 Who did you raise your voice \add against\add*
\q1 and \add arrogantly challenged\add*?
\q1 \add It was\add* Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*.
\q1
\v 24 You’ve defied my master by \add sending\add* your servants,
\q1 and you’ve said that you’ve gone to the tops of the mountains with your chariots—
\q1 up to the remotest parts of Lebanon to cut down its \add tallest\add* cedars and best pines.
\q1 \add You’ve said that\add* you’ll enter the \add highest parts\add* of its forest plantation.
\q1
\v 25 It’s me who has dug and drunk water,
\q1 and dried up all of Egypt’s canals with the soles of my feet.
\p
\v 26 “Haven’t you heard that I determined it from \add long ago\add*.
\q1 I planned it since ancient times and now I’m \add making it happen\add*,
\q1 →and you’re about to make fortified cities into desolate heaps of ruins.
\q1
\v 27 Their \add powerless\add* inhabitants are dismayed and ashamed.
\q1 They \add come and go like\add* the vegetation in the countryside,
\q1 and \add like\add* how a grass roof \add doesn’t stay green for long\add*
\q1 and \add like\add* a field \add as the grain crop grows\add*.
\p
\v 28 “I know when you sit down and when you go in or out,
\q1 and \add I know\add* your raging against me.
\q1
\v 29 Because of \add that\add* raging against me,
\q1 and your arrogance \add that’s reached\add* my ears,
\q1 I’ll put my hook in your nose
\q1 and my bit in your mouth,
\q1 and I’ll \add send you home on the same road that you came here on\add*.”
\p
\v 30 \add So\add* this will be the sign for you \add Hizkiyah\add*:
\q1 This year you’ll eat wild crops,
\q1 and next year you’ll eat the self-seeded growth.
\q1 But in the third year you must sow and harvest,
\q1 and plant vineyards and eat their fruit.
\q1
\v 31 The \add people\add* of Yehudah \add who’ve remained\add* \add here\add*
\q1 will \add send their roots\add* down and their fruit \add will grow\add* up,
\q1
\v 32 because a remnant will come out of Yerushalem,
\q1 and survivors from Mt. Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*.
\q1 Commander-in-chief Yahweh will accomplish this through his zeal.
\p
\v 33 Therefore Yahweh says this about the Assyrian king:
\q1 He won’t come into this city and he won’t shoot an error here.
\q1 He won’t bring a shield near it, and he won’t \add build ramps up against it\add*.
\q1
\v 34 He’ll return by the road that he came on, and he won’t enter this city.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration
\v 35 and I’ll protect this city \add and\add* rescue it for my own sake and for the sake of my servant David.
\s1 Sennacherib’s retreat and assassination
\p
\v 36 Then Yahweh’s messenger went out and \add killed\add* 185,000 Assyrian \add soldiers\add*—\add when\add* \add the others\add* got up early \add the next\add* morning, wow, there were corpses \add all around\add*!
\v 37 Then the Assyrian King Sennacherib left and \add headed back\add* \add there\add*, and he settled down in Nineveh.
\v 38 \add One day\add* he was worshipping in the \add temple\add* of his god Nisrok, and his sons Adrammelek and Sharetser \add ran a sword through him before\add* escaping to the Ararat \add region\add*, and his son Esar-Haddon \add replaced him as king\add*.
\c 38
\s1 Hizkiyah’s sickness and recovery
\r (2 Kgs 20:1-11; 2 Chr. 32:24-26)
\p
\v 1 \add Then a time came when\add* \add King\add* Hizkiyah became \add critically ill\add*, and the prophet Yeshayah (\add Isaiah\add*, Amots’ son) went to him and told him, “Yahweh says \add that you should put all your affairs into order, because you won’t recover—your time is up\add*.”
\p
\v 2 Then Hizkiyah \add rolled over to face\add* the wall and prayed to Yahweh,
\v 3 “Oh Yahweh, please remember how I’ve \add served you faithfully and with integrity\add*, and done \add what pleases you\add*.” Then Hizkiyah \add cried and cried\add*.
\p
\v 4 \add Later,\add* Yahweh \add gave\add* Yeshayah \add this\add* message,
\v 5 “Go and tell \add the king\add* that Yahweh, the god of his father David has \add taken notice of\add* his prayer \add and\add* seen his tears. \add So he’ll give him another\add* fifteen years
\v 6 and will rescue \add both\add* him and \add Yerushalem\add* from the Assyrian king. \add Yahweh\add* will defend this city
\v 7 and this will be the sign from \add him\add* that \add he\add* will do what he’s said,
\v 8 ‘Look, I will turn the shadow on the steps \add built by King\add* Ahaz, back ten steps.’ ” So the sun’s shadow went back \add up\add* ten steps that it had gone down.
\s2 Hizkiyah’s poem of praise
\p
\v 9 Yehudah’s King Hizkiyah \add wrote this\add* \add poem\add* \add after he’d recovered\add* from his sickness:
\q1
\v 10 I said, “I’ll go through the gates \add to the grave\add* in the \add prime\add* of my life,
\q1 I’ll miss out on the remainder of my years.”
\q1
\v 11 I said, “I won’t see Yah in the land of the living.
\q1 I’ll no longer look at humankind \add but rather\add* those who’ve ceased living.”
\q1
\v 12 \add The body that I live in\add* has been pulled up and removed from \add over\add* me like a shepherd’s tent.
\q1 I’ve rolled my life up like a weaver cutting me off from the loom.
\q1 From day until night, you make an end of me—
\q1
\v 13 I lie down\f + \fr 38:13 \ft The Hebrew could be read: \fqa I cried out \ft or \fq I lie down\ft .\f* until the morning.
\q1 He breaks all my bones like a lion \add would\add*.
\q1 From day until night, you make an end of me.
\q1
\v 14 I chirp like a swallow and moan like a dove.
\q1 My eyes \add feel weak from looking upwards\add*.
\q1 I’m oppressed, my master, \add help me out\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 15 What will I say? He told me and then he \add did it\add*.
\q1 I’ll walk slowly \add my remaining years\add* because of my soul’s bitterness.
\b
\q1
\v 16 My master, people live by \add such things\add*,
\q1 and my spirit \add finds life in\add* all of them.
\q1 \add Please\add* restore my health and preserve my life.
\q1
\v 17 Look, \add this\add* \add severe\add* bitterness was for my welfare,
\q1 and you \add held\add* my life \add back\add* from the pit of destruction
\q1 because you threw all my sins \add back over your shoulder\add*.
\q1
\v 18 \add No,\add* the grave doesn’t thank you.
\q1 Death doesn’t praise you.
\q1 Those who go down into the pit don’t \add expect you to be faithful\add*.
\q1
\v 19 The living, \add yes only\add* the living, give thanks to you like I do today.
\q1 A father \add tells\add* \add his\add* children about your faithfulness.
\q1
\v 20 Yahweh will save me and we’ll play stringed instruments
\q1 at \add his\add* \add residence\add* \add for the rest\add* of our lives.
\p
\v 21 Then Yeshayah said, “Get them to \add apply\add* a cake of figs to the boil so he’ll \add recover\add*.”
\p
\v 22 \add Now\add* Hizkiyah \add asked\add*, “What will be the sign that I should go up to Yahweh’s \add residence\add*?”
\c 39
\s1 Hizkiyah shows off his wealth
\r (2 Kgs 20:12-19)
\p
\v 1 At that time, Babylonian King Marduk-Baladan (son of Baladan) sent \add messengers with\add* letters and a gift to \add King\add* Hizkiyah because he had heard that he’d been sick and \add then recovered\add*.
\v 2 Hizkiyah \add happily welcomed\add* them, and showed them his treasure house—the gold and silver and spices and \add high-quality\add* oil, as well as his armoury and \add other\add* storehouses. Hizkiyah showed them everything in his \add palace\add* and all over his \add kingdom\add*.
\p
\v 3 \add Afterwards,\add* the prophet Yeshayah went to King Hizkiyah and asked him where those men had come from and what they had said.
\p “They came from the distant \add region\add* of Babylon,” Hizkiyah \add replied\add*.
\p
\v 4 “What did they see in your palace?” Yeshayah asked.
\p “They’ve seen everything that’s in my \add palace\add*,” Hizkiyah \add answered\add*. “There’s \add none of my treasures that I didn’t\add* show them.”
\p
\v 5 Then Yeshayah told Hizkiyah, “Listen to \add this\add* message from Commander-in-chief Yahweh:
\v 6 The \add time is definitely\add* coming when everything in your \add palace\add* will be carried away to Babylon—everything that your ancestors \add collected\add* \add in the past\add* until \add now\add*. Yahweh says that nothing will be left.
\v 7 \add In addition,\add* some of your descendants, \add your own flesh and blood\add*, will be taken away and \add be castrated\add* \add so as to become servants\add* in the Babylonian king’s palace.”
\p
\v 8 “Yahweh’s message that you’ve \add passed on\add* is \add appropriate\add*,” Hizkiyah told Yeshayah, “because \add at least\add* there’ll be peace and stability \add during my time\add*.”
\c 40
\s1 Yahweh will comfort his people
\p
\v 1 “\add Encourage\add* my people,” says your god. “\add Encourage\add* \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 2 Speak to Yerushalem’s heart and tell her that her \add period of\add* service is ended,
\q1 because \add the punishment for\add* her \add disobedience\add* has been accepted.
\q1 She’s received double \add punishment\add* from Yahweh for all her sins.
\b
\q1
\v 3 A voice calls out in the wilderness\f + \fr 40:3 \ft It’s unclear from the Hebrew if the \+bdit voice\+bdit* is in the wilderness, or if the \+bdit path\+bdit* is in the wilderness.\f* to clear the path for Yahweh.\x + \xo 40:3: \xt Mat 3:3; Mrk 1:3; Yhn 1:23.\x*
\q1 Make a straight road in the Aravah \add plain\add* for our god.
\q1
\v 4 Every valley will be \add filled in\add* and every mountain and hill will be \add flattened\add*,
\q1 and \add so\add* the \add slopes\add* will be \add levelled\add* and the rough places \add smoothed out\add*,
\q1
\v 5 then Yahweh’s \add splendour\add* will be revealed and all \add people\add* will see it \add simultaneously\add*,
\q1 because \add that’s what\add* Yahweh \add has declared\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 6 A voice says, ‘\add Call out\add*!’ and I \add ask\add*, ‘What should I \add call out\add*?’\x + \xo 40:6-8: \xt Jam 1:10-11; 1Pe 1:24-25.\x*
\q1 \add Say that\add* all \add people are like\add* grass—
\q1 all their ‘loyal commitment’ \add is as temporary\add* as a flower in the countryside.
\q1
\v 7 The grass dries up \add and\add* the flower wilts
\q1 when Yahweh’s breath blows over it.
\q1 Surely humankind is \add like\add* grass.
\q1
\v 8 The grass dries up, the flower wilts,
\q1 \add but\add* the \add decree\add* from our god will stand forever.
\b
\q1
\v 9 Go up onto a high \add hill\add* \add you\add* bearer of news for Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*.
\q1 Raise your voice \add you\add* bringer of news to Yerushalem—\add shout loudly\add* and don’t be afraid.
\q1 Tell Yehudah’s cities that their god is here.
\b
\q1
\v 10 Look, my master Yahweh will be coming \add with strength\add*,\x + \xo 40:10: \xt Isa 62:11; Rev 22:12.\x*
\q1 and he will be ruling \add with power\add*.
\q1 Look, \add he’s bringing his reward\add*
\q1 and his wages are \add there\add* \add in front of him\add*.
\q1
\v 11 He will tend his flock like a shepherd \add does\add*.\x + \xo 40:11: \xt Eze 34:15; Yhn 10:11.\x*
\q1 He will \add hold\add* the lambs \add to his chest\add*.
\q1 He will lead along the ewes \add who’ve just had lambs\add*.
\s1 Not/None like of Master of Yisrael
\q1
\v 12 Who has measured the \add oceans\add* in their palm,
\q1 and has marked off the sky with their handspan?
\q1 \add Who can\add* count the dust grains on the earth,
\q1 and has weighed the mountains with scales and the hills with balances?
\q1
\v 13 Who has \add told\add* Yahweh’s spirit \add what to do\add*,\x + \xo 40:13: \xt Rom 11:34; 1Cor 2:16.\x*
\q1 and has any person \add given him good advice\add*?
\q1
\v 14 Who did he \add ask for advice\add*?
\q1 Who \add informed him about something\add*?
\q1 Who taught him \add how to judge fairly\add*,
\q1 and taught him knowledge and \add helped him to understand something\add*?
\b
\q1
\v 15 Listen, the nations are like a drop in a bucket,
\q1 and are \add as insignificant\add* as dust on the scales.
\q1 He lifts the islands as if they \add just specks\add*.
\q1
\v 16 It’s not enough to \add set fire to\add* Lebanon,
\q1 and it doesn’t have enough animals to be an adequate burnt offering.
\q1
\v 17 All the nations \add together\add* are \add still\add* nothing to him.
\q1 He \add considers their combined power\add* as \add useless and worthless\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 18 Who could you compare God with?\x + \xo 40:18-19: \xt Acts 17:29.\x*
\q1 What \add is there that you all could say is anything\add* like him?
\q1
\v 19 An idol that was cast by a craftsman,
\q1 overlaid with gold by a goldsmith,
\q1 and then \add decorated\add* with silver chains?
\q1
\v 20 The poorer \add person\add* chooses a contribution of wood that won’t rot.
\q1 They choose a skillful craftsman to make an idol that won’t \add topple over\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 21 Don’t you all know? Haven’t you heard?
\q1 Didn’t anyone tell you all from the beginning?
\q1 Don’t you all understand the earth’s foundations?
\q1
\v 22 \add He’s\add* the \add one who\add* sits above the circle of the earth,
\q1 and its inhabitants are like grasshoppers.
\q1 \add He’s\add* the \add one who\add* stretches the skies out like a curtain
\q1 and spreads them out like a tent to live in.
\b
\q1
\v 23 He \add decides which officials will come\add* to nothing.
\q1 He makes the \add world’s\add* judges \add irrelevant\add*.
\q1
\v 24 Indeed, they’re hardly planted, yes, hardly sown.
\q1 Indeed, their stem has barely taken root in the earth,
\q1 but he also blows upon them and they wither,
\q1 and the wind carries them away like straw.
\b
\q1
\v 25 “Who \add else\add* is like me?” \add asks\add* the holy \add one\add*.
\q1 “Who \add else\add* could be equal to me?”
\b
\q1
\v 26 Look up and see \add the stars\add*.
\q1 Who created them?
\q1 \add Yahweh\add* knows their number as he brings them out.
\q1 He calls them all by name.
\q1 Because of his great strength and mighty power
\q2 not \add a single one\add* is missing.
\b
\q1
\v 27 Why do you talk, Yakob?
\q1 And why do you speak, Yisrael?
\q1 \add Saying,\add* ‘My path is hidden from Yahweh,
\q2 and my \add rights\add* disappear.’
\q1
\v 28 Don’t you know?
\q1 Haven’t you heard?
\q1 The eternal God Yahweh is the creator of \add one end of the earth to the other\add*.
\q1 He doesn’t get tired
\q1 and he won’t become weary.
\q1 You won’t find a limit to his understanding.
\q1
\v 29 He gives energy to those who are weary,
\q1 and increases the strength of those who are weak.
\q1
\v 30 \add Even\add* young people get tired and weary,
\q1 and young men can stumble \add clumsily\add*,
\q1
\v 31 \add but\add* those who \add trust\add* Yahweh will renew their strength.
\q1 They will rise up with wings like eagles.
\q1 They will run and not get tired.
\q1 They will walk and not become weary.
\c 41
\s1 Yahweh will help Yisrael
\p
\v 1 \add Stay\add* silent \add in front of\add* me, \add you\add* islands,
\q1 and let the peoples renew their strength.
\q1 Let them approach then let them speak.
\q1 Let’s gather together for judgement.
\q1
\v 2 Who has stirred up \add punishment\add* from the east?
\q1 It meets with his feet.
\q1 He destroys nations \add in front of\add* him.
\q1 He causes kings to rule.
\q1 He makes them like dust with his sword—
\q1 like chaff driven by his bow.
\q1
\v 3 He chases after them—going forward in peace.
\q1 He comes on a path without \add using\add* his feet.
\q1
\v 4 Who has done it and has accomplished it—
\q1 calling the generations out from the beginning?
\q1 I Yahweh, am the first and the last. I am he.
\b
\q1
\v 5 The islands have seen and are afraid.
\q1 The \add whole world\add* trembles.
\q1 They approach and come.
\q1
\v 6 Everyone helps out their neighbours,
\q1 and tells \add each other\add* to be strong.
\q1
\v 7 The craftsman encourages the goldsmith who smooths with a hammer.
\q1 The \add one\add* who strikes the anvil says that the welding is good
\q1 and the strengthen it with nails so it won’t \add topple over\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 8 But you, my servant Yisrael,
\q1 Yakob \add (Jacob)\add* who I’ve chosen,
\q1 the offspring of my friend Avraham,
\q1
\v 9 I pulled you back from the ends of the earth,
\q1 calling you from its most distant corners,
\q1 and I told you, ‘You’re my servant.’
\q1 I’ve chosen you and won’t reject you.
\q1
\v 10 Don’t be afraid, because I’m with you.
\q1 Don’t be anxious, because I’m your God.
\q1 I’ll strengthen you, indeed, I’ll help you.
\q1 Yes, I’ll support you with \add my strength—always doing what’s right\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 11 Listen, all those who are angry with you will be ashamed and \add disgraced\add*.
\q1 Those who contend with you will be reduced to nothing and will perish.
\q1
\v 12 You’ll search for those who contended against you, but you won’t be able to find them.
\q1 Those who battled against you will be useless and \add irrelevant\add*,
\q1
\v 13 because I, your god Yahweh, will hold \add up\add* your right hand—
\q1 the one who tells you not to be afraid \add because\add* I’ll help you.
\p
\v 14 Don’t be afraid, Yakov, \add you\add* worm—you Israeli \add people\add*.
\q1 I will help you \add declares\add* Yahweh—\add the one who rescues you\add*—
\q1 Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*.
\q1
\v 15 Listen, I’m making you into a threshing sledge—sharp and doubled-edged.
\q1 You’ll thresh mountains and crush them,
\q1 and make the hills like chaff.
\q1
\v 16 You’ll \add toss them into the air\add* and the wind will carry them away,
\q1 and a whirlwind will scatter them.
\q1 Then you’ll be happy \add about\add* Yahweh—
\q1 you’ll boast about Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 17 The poor and needy \add people\add* look for water, but there’s none.
\q1 Their tongues are dry from thirst.
\q1 I, Yahweh, will \add respond to\add* them.
\q1 I, Yisrael’s god won’t abandon them.
\q1
\v 18 I’ll \add make streams flow down\add* from \add barren hills\add*,
\q1 and will \add cause springs to appear\add* in the middle of the valleys.
\q1 I’ll make the wilderness into a pool of water,
\q1 and \add fill\add* the dry land with springs.
\q1
\v 19 I’ll \add grow\add* cedar, acacia, myrtle, and olive trees in the wilderness.
\q1 I’ll \add plant\add* cypress, elm, and boxwood trees on the desert plain,
\q1
\v 20 so that \add people\add* will be able to see, to realise, and to have determination and insight together
\q1 →because Yahweh \add has personally\add* done this—Yisrael’s holy \add one\add* has created it.
\s1 Yahweh’s challenge to idols
\p
\v 21 “\add Bring\add* your case \add to me\add*,” says Yahweh.
\q1 “\add Present\add* your arguments,” says Yakov’s king.
\q1
\v 22 Let them bring them out and tell us what will happen.
\q1 What happened \add before that\add*?
\q1 Tell us so we can \add ponder them\add* and so we can know \add what’s been done\add*
\q1 and then tell us \add what’s still\add* coming.
\q1
\v 23 Tell the \add signs of the future\add* so that we can know if you’re all gods.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* do \add something good or bad\add* so that we can be \add amazed or afraid\add* together.
\q1
\v 24 Look, you’re all nothing and your actions are worthless.
\q1 Anyone who chooses you all to worship \add is disgusting\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 25 I have stirred up \add a ruler\add* from the north,
\q1 and he’s coming from \add the east\add*.
\q1 He’ll \add put his trust in me\add*
\q1 and he’ll \add step on\add* officials like mud
\q1 and like a potter who \add works the clay with his feet\add*.
\q1
\v 26 Who told us \add that\add* from the beginning so that we’d know?
\q1 Who \add predicted it\add* so that we can \add now\add* say that they were correct?
\q1 \add Actually,\add* no one said or announced it—
\q1 \add no,\add* no one heard your messages.
\q1
\v 27 Firstly to Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*, look they’re here!
\q1 Then I sent a runner to Yerushalem \add to give them the news\add*.
\q1
\v 28 Then I looked \add at those idols\add* \add but\add* there was no \add life\add* \add there\add*.
\q1 There wasn’t any advisor among them.
\q1
\v 29 \add No,\add* all of them are a delusion—they \add accomplish\add* nothing.
\q1 Their \add cast metal\add* images \add are as empty as the wind\add*.
\c 42
\s1 Yahweh’s chosen servant
\s2 The first servant song
\q1
\v 1 Look, here’s my servant who I support—my chosen one who I’m pleased with.\x + \xo 42:1: \xt Mat 3:17; 17:5; Mrk 1:11; Luk 3:22; 9:35.\x*
\q1 I’ve put my spirit onto him. He’ll bring justice to the nations.
\q1
\v 2 He won’t cry out or lift up \add his head\add*.
\q1 and he won’t make his voice heard in the \add streets\add*.
\q1
\v 3 He won’t break a crushed reed
\q1 and nor will he extinguish a dim \add oil-lamp\add*.
\q1 He will \add faithfully\add* bring justice \add to the people\add*.
\q1
\v 4 He won’t grow dim or be crushed
\q1 before he’s established justice \add in the world\add*,
\q1 and while the islands wait for his instructions.
\b
\q1
\v 5 The god Yahweh who created the skies and stretched them out,
\q1 who \add formed\add* the earth and all its produce,
\q1 who gives breath to the people on it
\q1 and a spirit to those who walk on it, says this:
\q1
\v 6 I, Yahweh, have called you \add my servant\add* \add for a godly purpose\add*,
\q1 and I’ll take hold of your hand and watch over you.
\q1 I will make you into a \add promise for\add* the people—a light \add for\add* the nations:
\q1
\v 7 to open the eyes of the blind—
\q1 to bring prisoners out of the dungeon—
\q1 to release those who live in dark prisons.
\b
\q1
\v 8 I am Yahweh. That’s my name
\q1 and I won’t \add allow anyone else to receive the honour that only I deserve\add*,
\q1 and nor will I allow images \add to receive the praise that should come to me\add*.
\q1
\v 9 Listen, things \add said\add* before have come \add to pass\add*
\q1 and I’m about to \add reveal\add* new things—
\q1 I’ll \add let you all know about\add* them before they \add come to be\add*.
\s1 A song to praise Yahweh
\q1
\v 10 Sing a new song for Yahweh—praising him from the end of the earth.
\q1 Those who go down to the sea and \add everything\add* that fills it.
\q1 \add You\add* islands and their inhabitants.
\q1
\v 11 Let the wilderness and its cities lift up \add their voice\add*—
\q1 the villages where \add the Bedouins\add* live.
\q1 Let the inhabitants of \add Edom’s capital\add* Sela sing.
\q1 Let them shout from the mountaintops.
\q1
\v 12 Let them \add honour\add* Yahweh
\q1 and \add praise\add* him from the islands.
\q1
\v 13 Yahweh will go ahead like a warrior—
\q1 he’ll stir up zeal like a man of war.
\q1 He’ll raise a war cry—shouting \add out loudly\add*,
\q1 \add and then\add* he’ll \add defeat\add* his enemies.
\s1 Yahweh promises help
\p
\v 14 I’ve been silent \add for a long time now\add*.
\q1 I’ve been still—I’ve restrained myself.
\q1 \add Now\add* I’ll cry out like a woman giving birth.
\q1 I’ll puff and pant \add at the same time\add*.
\q1
\v 15 I’ll make the mountains and hills dry up
\q1 and all their vegetation will wither.
\q1 plus I’ll turn the rivers into islands
\q1 and dry up the pools.
\b
\q1
\v 16 I’ll lead the blind down a path that they don’t know.
\q1 I’ll guide them on roads \add that they’re not familiar with\add*.
\q1 I’ll make the dark places in front of them, light,
\q1 and the rough places into level ground.
\q1 I’ll do those things for them, and I won’t abandon them.
\q1
\v 17 Those who trust in idols will be turned back and \add totally humiliated\add*—
\q1 those who tell a \add cast metal\add* figure, ‘You’re our god.’
\s1 Yisrael’s stubborn deafness
\p
\v 18 Listen \add you\add* deaf \add people\add*,
\q1 and look \add you\add* blind \add people\add* and see.
\q1
\v 19 Who is blind other than my servant,
\q1 or deaf like my messenger who I’ll send?
\q1 Who’s blind like \add my partner\add* in \add our\add* agreement,
\q1 or blind like Yahweh’s servant.
\q1
\v 20 You see many things \add but\add* don’t \add take any notice\add*.
\q1 Your ears are open \add but\add* you don’t listen.
\p
\v 21 Yahweh was pleased to \add do what’s right\add*—
\q1 he made \add his\add* instructions \add honourable and splendid\add*.
\q1
\v 22 \add But\add* this is a people who’ve been robbed and plundered.
\q1 They’re all trapped in holes and hidden away in prisons.
\q1 They’ve become the spoil, and there’s no one \add to rescue\add* \add them\add*.
\q1 \add They’ve become\add* plunder and no one \add speaks up to help them\add* back.
\b
\q1
\v 23 Will any of you \add take any notice\add* of that?
\q1 Will anyone listen or pay attention afterwards?
\q1
\v 24 Who gave Yakov \add (Jacob)\add* to the \add robbers\add*,
\q1 and Yisrael \add (Israel)\add* to the looters?
\q1 →Wasn’t it Yahweh, the one we \add disobeyed\add*?
\q1 They weren’t willing to \add do what he wanted\add*,
\q1 and they didn’t listen to his instructions.
\q1
\v 25 Then he poured out his rage and the \add violence of war\add*.
\q1 The flames \add burnt all around\add*, yet \add Yisrael\add* didn’t \add realise\add*.
\q1 They burnt it up, \add but\add* it didn’t \add take it to\add* heart.
\c 43
\s1 Yahweh promises rescue and return
\p
\v 1 \add But\add* now Yahweh, the one who created you, Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*,
\q1 and who formed you, Yisrael \add (Yisrael)\add*, says this:
\b
\q1 Don’t be afraid, because I’ve \add paid the price to free you\add*.
\q1 I’ve called you by name—you \add belong to me\add*.
\q1
\v 2 \add When\add* you pass through the waters, I’m with you,
\q1 and through the rivers, they won’t \add carry you away\add*.
\q1 \add When\add* you walk through the fire, you won’t get scorched
\q1 and the flames won’t burn you \add up\add*
\q1
\v 3 because I’m your god, Yahweh—
\q1 your rescuer, Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*.
\q1 I’ve given Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add* as your ransom—
\q1 Ethiopia \add (Heb. Kush)\add* and Seva in your place
\q1
\v 4 since you are precious in my eyes.
\q1 You are honoured and I love you,
\q1 and I’ll give humankind in your place,
\q1 and \add nations\add* in exchange for your life.
\q1
\v 5 Don’t be afraid, because I’m with you.
\q1 I’ll bring your \add descendants\add* from the east,
\q1 and I’ll gather you in from the west.
\q1
\v 6 I’ll tell the north \add to hand you over\add*,
\q1 and \add tell\add* the south not to hold \add you\add* back.
\q1 Bring my sons \add back\add* from distant \add lands\add*,
\q1 and bring my daughters from the ends of the earth—
\q1
\v 7 \add yes,\add* all those who \add belong to me\add*
\q1 and who I’ve created \add as my showpiece\add*—
\q1 those who I formed \add when\add* I made them.
\s1 The calling of God of Yisrael as witness
\p
\v 8 Bring out the people with eyes who \add still seem\add* blind,
\q1 and those who have ears \add but\add* \add still seem\add* deaf.
\q1
\v 9 All the nations have gathered together,
\q1 and the peoples assemble.
\q1 Which of them could have \add predicted this\add*?
\q1 They announce \add things that have happened in the past\add*!
\q1 Let them appoint their \add own\add* witnesses so they can be justified.
\q1 Let them hear and then let them say that it’s true.
\b
\q1
\v 10 \add But\add* Yahweh declares that you all are \em my\em* witnesses
\q1 and my servant who I’ve chosen
\q1 so that you all can know and believe me
\q2 and understand that I am \add God\add*.
\q1 There’s no other god that was formed before me,
\q1 ^and none will be format after me.
\b
\q1
\v 11 I (\add and no one else\add*) am Yahweh.
\q1 and other than me, there’s \add no one else who can save you\add*.
\q1
\v 12 I have declared \add that I would save\add* and I have saved,
\q1 and I have proclaimed \add that I have done it\add*,
\q1 and you all are my witnesses that I am God.
\q1 That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\q1
\v 13 From \add the first\add* day, I am he,
\q1 and no one \add can oppose my power\add*.
\q1 I \add take action\add* and who could reverse it?
\s1 The punishment of Babylon
\p
\v 14 Yahweh, \add the one who paid to set you all free\add*, Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*, says this:
\q1 For your sake, I’ve sent \add an army\add* to Babylon,
\q1 and I’ll bring all of them down \add as fugitives\add* in boats,
\q1 and all \add those\add* Chaldeans in the ships \add that they usually cheer about\add*.
\q1
\v 15 I am Yahweh, your holy \add one\add*
\q1 creator of Yisrael, your king.
\b
\p
\v 16 \add I am\add* Yahweh,
\q1 the \add one\add* who made a path through the sea
\q1 and a road through the \add surging\add* waters.
\q1
\v 17 \add I enticed\add* the chariots and horses out,
\q1 together with a strong army,
\q1 They fell down together and didn’t rise \add again\add*.
\q1 They were extinguished like \add how\add* a wick is quenched.
\p
\v 18 \add Yahweh says\add*,
\q1 Don’t \add meditate on what happened previously\add*,
\q1 and don’t \add keep thinking about past history\add*.
\q1
\v 19 Listen, I’m going to do \add something\add* new.
\q1 It’s springing up—haven’t you \add noticed\add* it?
\q1 \add Yes,\add* I’ll make a road in the wilderness—
\q1 streams in \add that\add* desolate place.
\q1
\v 20 The animals in the countryside will honour me—
\q1 the jackals and the ostriches
\q1 because I’ve put water in the wilderness,
\q1 streams in the desolate place
\q1 to \add provide\add* water for my chosen people.
\q1
\v 21 I formed that \add nation\add* for myself.
\q1 They will \add discuss\add* \add their\add* praise for me.
\s1 Yisrael’s sin
\p
\v 22 \add But\add* you didn’t call to me \add for help\add*, Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*,
\q1 because you’ve grown tired of me, Yisrael \add (Israel)\add*.
\q1
\v 23 You haven’t brought sheep to me as your burnt offerings,
\q1 and you haven’t honoured me with your sacrifices.
\q1 I haven’t burdened you with \add grain\add* offerings,
\q1 and I haven’t made you weary \add by demanding incense\add*.
\q1
\v 24 You didn’t \add spend any money to buy\add* fragrant reeds for me,
\q1 and you haven’t satisfied me with the fat from your sacrifices.
\q1 Nevertheless you’ve burdened me with your \add disobedience\add*—
\q1 you’ve tired me out with your \add wickedness\add*.
\q1
\v 25 I’m \add the only one\add* who wipes your offenses out for my own sake,
\q1 and then I won’t remember your sins any more.
\b
\q1
\v 26 \add Remind\add* me, let’s \add plead the case\add* together.
\q1 You retell it \add all\add* so that you can be \add declared innocent\add*.
\q1
\v 27 Your \add founding\add* father sinned,
\q1 and your spokesmen have disobeyed me,
\q1
\v 28 \add so\add* I’ll defile your sacred officials,
\q1 and \add send\add* destruction to Yakov,
\q1 and insults to Yisrael.
\c 44
\s1 Yahweh’s chosen people
\q1
\v 1 Now listen Yakov \add (Jacob)\add* my servant,
\q1 and Yisrael \add (Israel)\add* who I’ve chosen.
\q1
\v 2 The one who made you and formed you in the womb,
\q1 Yahweh says this:
\q1 Don’t be afraid, Yakov my servant,
\q1 and \add Yisrael\add* who I’ve chosen,
\p
\v 3 because I’ll pour water out onto the thirsty \add ground\add*
\q1 and streams on the dry ground.
\q1 I’ll pour my spirit out onto your offspring
\q1 and my blessing onto your descendants.
\q1
\v 4 They’ll spring up among the grasses
\q1 like poplars \add beside flowing streams\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 5 This one will say that they’re \add in favour\add* of Yahweh,
\q1 and \add that\add* one will out Yakob’s name out.
\q1 \add Another one\add* will write ‘Belonging to Yahweh’ on their hand,
\q1 and \add others\add* will use the title ‘From Yisrael’.
\p
\v 6 Yisrael’s king and the \add one who bought their freedom\add*,
\q1 Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this:
\q1 I’m the first and the last,\x + \xo 44:6: \xt Isa 48:12; Rev 1:17; 22:13.\x*
\q1 and there’s no other god—just me.
\q1
\v 7 \add Yes,\add* who’s like me? Let him proclaim it,
\q1 and let him declare it.
\q1 Let him recount to me \add the historical sequence of\add* how this \add nation\add* was established in the past,
\q1 and let them declare \add what’s about to happen\add*.
\q1
\v 8 Don’t dread \add the future\add*
\q1 and don’t be afraid.
\q1 Didn’t I already declare \add it\add* to you
\q1 and announce \add what would happen\add*, and you all are my witnesses?
\q1 Is there some other god\f + \fr 44:8 \ft This is the only place where Yeshayah uses Eloah (singular) for God instead of Elohim (plural).\f* than me?
\q1 There’s no other ‘rock’ that I know of.
\s1 The absurdity of crafting an idol
\p
\v 9 All those who form idols are \add losers\add*
\q1 and their expectations won’t be realised.
\q1 Their witnesses can’t see and they don’t know \add anything\add*,
\q1 so they’ll be ashamed.
\q1
\v 10 Who would form a god
\q1 or an idol that never \add helps\add* them?
\q1
\v 11 All their associates will be \add put to shame\add*—
\q1 craftsmen are \add just\add* human beings.
\q1 Let all of them gather together \add and\add* \add take their stand\add*.
\q1 Let them dread \add the consequences\add* and be ashamed together.
\p
\v 12 The blacksmith takes a tool and works on the iron over the coals.
\q1 He hammers it with his strong arm to form it \add into shape\add*.
\q1 \add But then\add* he gets hungry and \add feels weaker\add*.
\q1 \add If\add* he doesn’t drink water, he’ll \add feel exhausted\add*.
\p
\v 13 The \add carpenter measures a piece of\add* wood.
\q1 He outlines it with a marker and works it with his \add chisels\add*.
\q1 He outlines it with a compass and makes it like the figure of a man—
\q1 like a \add good-looking\add* man \add who might\add* live in a house.
\q1
\v 14 He cuts down \add cedar trees\add*
\q1 or \add selects\add* a cypress or an oak.
\q1 He \add lets it grow strong\add* among the trees in the forest.
\q1 He plants a fir tree and the rain makes it grow.
\q1
\v 15 Then \add the wood\add* is used by humankind to burn.
\q1 \add The carpenter\add* uses some of the wood to warm himself,
\q1 \add Yes,\add* he kindles a fire and bakes bread \add on it\add*.
\q1 He also makes a god out of it and bows down to it.
\q1 He makes \add the wood\add* into an idol and kneels in front of it.
\q1
\v 16 He burns half of \add the wood\add* for the fire,
\q1 and roasts meat on \add that\add* half—he eats the meat and is satisfied.
\q1 He also warms himself and says ‘Aha, I’m warm,’ as he looks at the fire.
\q1
\v 17 He uses the rest of the wood to make a god.
\q1 He makes an idol and kneels in front of it.
\q1 He bows down and prays to it
\q1 →and says, ‘Rescue me, because you’re my god.’
\p
\v 18 \add Those people\add* don’t know and don’t understand
\q1 because their eyes are plastered over so they can’t see
\q1 \add and\add* their minds \add are prevented\add* from having insight.
\q1
\v 19 No one \add gives much thought to their actions\add*.
\q1 \add They don’t apply\add* knowledge and understanding, to say,
\q1 ‘I burnt half of \add the wood\add* in the fire and baked bread on the coals.
\q1 I roasted meat on it and ate it.
\q1 Then I’ll take the remainder to make \add a detestable idol\add*.
\q1 I’ll bow down to a \add piece of wood\add* from a tree.’
\p
\v 20 He eats \add thanks to those ashes\add*.
\q1 He’s deceived and been led astray.
\q1 He doesn’t escape \add from his own situation\add* and say,
\q1 ‘I’m \add holding\add* a lie in my right hand.’
\p
\v 21 Remember that, Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*,
\q1 and Yisrael \add (Israel)\add* because you’re my servant.
\q1 I formed you—you’re my servant Yisrael—I won’t forget about you.
\q1
\v 22 I’ve blotted out your \add disobedience\add* like a cloud.
\q1 and your sins like a \add fog\add*.
\q1 Return to me because I \add paid the price for your freedom\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 23 Shout happily \add you\add* skies because Yahweh has taken action.
\q1 Shout triumphantly \add you\add* depths of the earth.
\q1 Sing loudly \add you\add* mountains and forests and all \add you\add* trees
\q1 because Yahweh has \add paid the price for Yakov’s freedom\add*
\q1 and will \add be honoured\add* by Yisrael.
\p
\v 24 Yahweh, \add the one who paid for your freedom\add*
\q1 and the one who formed you in the womb, says this:
\q1 I am Yahweh who made everything,
\q1 who alone stretched out the skies \add and\add* formed the earth.
\q1 Who \add was it who helped\add* me?
\q1
\v 25 \add Who else\add* frustrates the sign of empty-talkers,
\q1 and makes diviners look foolish?\x + \xo 44:25: \xt 1Cor 1:20.\x*
\q1 \add Who else\add* turns wise \add people\add* back
\q1 and makes their knowledge \add seem\add* foolish?
\q1
\v 26 \add Who else\add* confirms the words of his \add prophet\add*,
\q1 and fulfills the advice of his messengers
\q1 who say that Yerushalem will be inhabited,
\q1 and that Yehudah’s towns will be rebuilt,
\q1 and \add the country’s\add* ruins will be \add rebuilt\add*?
\q1
\v 27 \add Who else\add* tells the deep sea to dry out,
\q1 and makes your rivers dry up?
\q1
\v 28 \add Who else\add* calls \add King\add* Cyrus \add (Heb. Koresh)\add* ‘my shepherd’,\x + \xo 44:28: \xt 2Ch 36:23; Ezr 1:2.\x*
\q1 and says that he’ll do everything I want?
\q1 \add Who else\add* says that Yerushalem will be rebuilt,
\q1 and that the temple foundations will be \add restored\add*.
\c 45
\s1 Yahweh send Cyrus
\p
\v 1 Yahweh has appointed Cyrus \add (Heb. Koresh)\add* \add and\add* \add given him power\add*
\q1 to subdue \add other\add* nations and \add defeat\add* kings—
\q1 to open doors \add ahead of\add* him,
\q1 and no gates will shut \add him out\add*.
\q1 \add Now\add* \add Yahweh\add* says this:
\q1
\v 2 I’ll go \add ahead of you\add* \add Cyrus\add* and level the mountains.
\q1 I’ll break down bronze doors and cut through iron bars,
\q1
\v 3 and I’ll give you the treasures \add that are hidden away\add*
\q1 and the riches \add stored\add* in secret places
\q1 so that you’ll know that it’s me, Yahweh, Yisrael’s god, who calls you by name.
\q1
\v 4 For the sake of my servant Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*
\q1 and Yisrael \add (Israel)\add* my chosen \add one\add*,
\q1 I’ve summoned you by name.
\q1 Although you don’t know me, I’ll give you a title \add of honour\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 5 I am Yahweh and there’s no one else.
\q1 Apart from me, there’s no \add other\add* God.
\q1 Even though you don’t know me,
\q2 I will strengthen you
\q1
\v 6 so that from the east to the west they’ll know
\q2 that there’s nothing apart from me.
\q1 I’m Yahweh, and there’s no other \add God\add*.
\q1
\v 7 I formed the light and created the darkness.
\q1 I bring peace and prosperity, and I cause disasters.
\q1 It’s me, Yahweh, who does all those things.
\q1
\v 8 Rain down from above \add you\add* skies,
\q1 and let the clouds \add pour down godliness\add*.
\q1 Let the earth open up and let salvation grow \add on the trees\add*
\q1 and \add at the same time,\add* let righteousness sprout up.
\q1 I, Yahweh, have created it.
\s1 Don’t argue with Yahweh
\q1
\v 9 The \add person\add* who argues against their \add creator\add* \add won’t end well\add*.
\q1 \add They’re like\add* a piece of broken pottery \add lying among all the other pieces\add* on the ground.
\q1 Does the clay \add ask\add* \add the potter\add* what he’s making,\x + \xo 45:9: \xt Isa 29:16; Rom 9:20.\x*
\q1 \add or\add* \add ask why he didn’t do a very good job making what he did\add*?
\q1
\v 10 Anyone who \add asks\add* a father what he’s fathering \add won’t end well\add*,
\q1 and \add nor will anyone who asks\add* a woman what she’s in labour for.
\q1
\v 11 Yahweh, Yisrael’s holy \add one\add* and the one who formed it, \add asks\add* this:
\q1 ‘\add Concerning\add* the things to come, do you question me about my children?
\q1 And will you all tell me \add what actions that I should take\add*?’
\q1
\v 12 I made the earth and created humankind on it.
\q1 My own hands stretched the skies out,
\q1 and I ordered all \add the heavenly bodies\add* \add into place\add*.
\q1
\v 13 I stirred \add Cyrus\add* up \add to do what’s right\add*,
\q1 and I’ll smooth out his paths \add ahead of him\add*.
\q1 He’ll be the one to build my city, and he’ll release my exiles—
\q1 not for a ransom or for a bribe.
\m Commander-in-chief Yahweh says that.
\p
\v 14 Yahweh says this:
\q1 Egypt’s produce and Ethiopia’s profit and those tall people from Sava
\q1 will \add all\add* be turned over to you and they’ll belong to you.
\q1 They’ll walk behind you and will be handed over in chains.
\q1 They’ll bow down to you and \add state\add*,
\q1 ‘Surely God is with you—he’s the only god—there’s no other.’
\q1
\v 15 You are certainly a god who hides himself,
\q1 \add you\add* god \add who rescues\add* Yisrael.
\q1
\v 16 Those who craft idols will be humiliated—
\q1 all of them will be put to shame together.
\q1 Those who craft idols will be \add publicly disgraced\add*.
\q1
\v 17 Yisrael has been rescued by Yahweh—\add freed forever\add*.
\q1 You all won’t be humiliated or put to shame ever again.
\b
\q1
\v 18 Yahweh who created the skies, is God.
\q1 He formed the earth and established it.
\q1 He didn’t create it as a wasteland,
\q1 ^but rather, he formed it to be lived in.
\q1 \add Yahweh\add* says this:
\q1
\v 19 I didn’t speak in secrecy in a place where \add it’s all dark\add*.
\q1 It wasn’t in vain that I told Yakov’s \add descendants\add* to search for me.
\q1 I am Yahweh who says \add what is right\add* and declares \add what is proper\add*.
\s1 Yahweh and false gods
\p
\v 20 Gather together and come.
\q1 \add Assemble\add* together \add you\add* fugitives from the nations.
\q1 Those who carry their \add wooden\add* idols don’t know \add what’s going on\add*—
\q1 those who pray to a god that can’t \add help\add* them.
\q1
\v 21 Declare and approach. Let them also get advice together.
\q1 Who predicted that in the past and then declared it?
\q1 Wasn’t it me, Yahweh?
\q1 There’s no god other than me—
\q1 a god \add who does what is right\add* and \add who rescues\add* \add his people\add*.
\q1 There’s no other \add rescuer\add* except me.
\b
\q1
\v 22 Turn to me and be saved, all \add you\add* at the ends of the earth,
\q1 because I’m God and there isn’t any other.
\q1
\v 23 I’ve \add solemnly promised\add* \add that\add*—
\q1 \add I only say what’s right\add* and \add I don’t change my mind\add*,
\q1 because every knee will bow to me.\x + \xo 45:23: \xt Rom 14:11; Php 2:10-11.\x*
\q1 Every tongue will promise \add allegiance to me\add*.
\b
\p
\v 24 They’ll say that righteousness and strength are only in Yahweh.
\q1 All those who were angry at him will come to him \add in their shame\add*.
\q1
\v 25 Yisrael’s descendants will be \add declared innocent by\add* Yahweh,
\q1 and they’ll boast \add about what he’s done for them\add*.
\c 46
\s1 The false gods there in Babylon
\p
\v 1 \add The Babylonian gods\add* Bel bows down and Nevo stoops low.
\q1 Their idols need to be carried by animals and are burdens for tired cattle.
\q2
\v 2 Together \add those gods\add* bend low, kneeling down.
\q1 They’re not able to rescue the load
\q1 and they themselves have \add been taken\add* into captivity.
\b
\q1
\v 3 Listen to me \add you\add* \add descendants\add* of Yakov,
\q1 and all the remnant of Yisrael’s \add families\add*—
\q1 carried since \add birth\add*,
\q1 \add supported\add* since the womb.
\q1
\v 4 \add I’ll be there even when you age\add*,
\q1 and I’ll carry \add you\add* \add when your hair goes grey\add*.
\q1 I made \add you\add* and I’ll \add support\add* \add you\add*,
\q1 and I’ll carry \add you\add* and rescue \add you\add*.
\p
\v 5 Who can you liken me to or \add say that I’m the same as\add*,
\q1 or compare me to and \add say that\add* we’re alike?
\q1
\v 6 Those who pour gold out from a bag
\q1 and weigh \add their\add* silver on a scale,
\q1 hire a metalsmith to make it into a god.
\q1 They \add kneel in front of it and worship it\add*.
\q1
\v 7 They lift it up and carry it on their shoulders,
\q1 and then they put it down in its place.
\q1 It stands \add there\add* and never leaves.
\q1 \add They\add* call out to it \add for help\add* but it doesn’t answer—
\q1 it won’t rescue \add them\add* from \add their\add* troubles.
\b
\q1
\v 8 Remember that and pluck up courage.
\q1 \add You\add* rebels, \add take it to\add* heart.
\q1
\v 9 Think about what happened long ago
\q1 because I’m God and there’s no other,
\q1 \add I’m\add* God and there’s no one like me.
\q1
\v 10 From the beginning, I declare the end.
\q1 From ancient times, I \add announce\add* what’s still to come.
\q1 I declare that my plan will come to be,
\q2 and all my intentions will be accomplished.
\q1
\v 11 Summoning a bird of prey from the east,
\q1 from a distant \add country\add*—the man to \add carry out my plan\add*.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* I’ve spoken and I’ll \add make it happen\add*.
\q1 I’ve planned, and I’ll also accomplish it.
\b
\q1
\v 12 Listen to me \add you stubborn\add* \add people\add*—
\q1 \add you who\add* are so far from \add doing what’s right\add*.
\q1
\v 13 I’ve brought my righteousness near—it’s not far away,
\q1 and my salvation won’t delay.
\q1 I’ll \add rescue\add* Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*
\q1 \add and display\add* my splendour to Yisrael \add (Israel)\add*.
\c 47
\s1 Babylon’s coming judgement
\p
\v 1 Come down and sit in the dust \add you\add* virgin daughter of Babylon.
\q1 Sit on the ground without a throne \add you\add* daughter of the Chaldeans,\x + \xo 47:1-15: \xt Isa 13:1–14:23; Jer 50:1; 51:64.\x*
\q1 because people won’t call you tender and delicate any more.
\q1
\v 2 \add Turn those\add* millstones and grind flour.
\q1 Remove your veil and strip off your skirt.
\q1 Uncover your legs to \add wade through\add* rivers.
\q1
\v 3 Your nakedness will be \add exposed\add*.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* your shame will be visible.
\q1 I’ll take vengeance and won’t \add spare\add* anyone.
\b
\q1
\v 4 Commander-in-chief Yahweh is the name of \add the one who bought our freedom\add*—
\q1 Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*.
\p
\v 5 Sit in silence and go in darkness \add you\add* daughter of the Chaldeans,
\q1 because you’ll no longer be called ‘the queen of kingdoms’.
\q1
\v 6 I was angry with my people—
\q1 I defiled my inheritance and \add handed them over to you\add*.
\q1 You \add showed\add* them no compassion—
\q1 \add even\add* the old \add had a heavy burden placed on them\add*.
\q1
\v 7 You said that you’d be queen forever,
\q1 but you didn’t \add give it enough thought\add*—
\q1 you didn’t \add consider\add* its outcome.
\q1
\v 8 Now listen to this \add you\add* over-indulged \add woman\add* who lives in security,
\q1 saying in her heart, ‘\add No one else is important except me\add*.\x + \xo 47:8-9: \xt Rev 18:7-8.\x*
\q1 \add I’ll never be a widow or lose my children\add*.’
\q1
\v 9 \add But\add* both of these things will \add suddenly happen\add* to you:
\q1 Bereavement and childless \add will hit\add* in one day.
\q1 They’ll come on you with completeness \add despite\add* your plentiful sorceries
\q1 \add and\add* the power of your multiple spells.
\b
\q1
\v 10 You trusted in your wickedness and \add thought\add* no one \add would notice\add* you.
\q1 Your wisdom and knowledge has led you astray
\q1 and you \add told yourself that no one else was important except you\add*.
\q1
\v 11 Calamity will \add hit\add* you and you won’t be able to charm it away.
\q1 Disaster will fall on you and you won’t be able to \add avoid\add* it—
\q1 disaster like you’ve never known before will come on you suddenly.
\q1
\v 12 \add Keep trusting\add* your spells and your plentiful sorceries
\q1 that you’ve worked \add hard\add* at since your youth.
\q1 Perhaps you’ll \add be successful\add*—maybe \add scaring\add* \add disaster away\add*.
\q1
\v 13 You’ve become tired of \add listening to so much advice\add*.
\q1 Please let them stand up and save you—
\q1 those \add ones\add* who \add chart\add* the skies and \add divine from\add* moons
\q1 to \add discover\add* \add what’s going to happen to\add* you.
\b
\q1
\v 14 Look, they’ve become like straw that get burnt in a fire.
\q1 They can’t rescue themselves from the flames.
\q1 There’ll be no coals to warm them—\add no\add* fire to sit by.
\q1
\v 15 That’s what those you worked with have become—those traders from your youth.
\q1 Everyone has wandered in their own \add direction\add*—there’s no rescuer.
\c 48
\s1 Yahweh knows and controls the future
\q1
\v 1 Listen to this \add you\add* \add descendants\add* of Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*,
\q1 who are called by the name Yisrael \add (Israel)\add* and \add descended from\add* Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*.
\q1 \add You\add* \add make promises using\add* Yahweh’s name,
\q1 and \add mention\add* Yisrael’s god,
\q1 \add but\add* it’s not \add done\add* \add honestly or sincerely\add*
\q1
\v 2 \add even though they state\add* that they’re from the sacred city,
\q1 and that they’re supported by Yisrael’s god, named commander-in-chief Yahweh.
\p
\v 3 \add Long ago I predicted and explained what would happen\add*,
\q1 →then suddenly, I \add took action\add* and they \add happened\add*
\q1
\v 4 because I knew that you were stubborn.
\q1 Your neck muscles are \add like\add* iron
\q1 and your forehead is \add like\add* bronze,
\q1
\v 5 \add so\add* I \add announced those things in advance\add*.
\q1 Before \add they happened\add*, I \add informed\add* you
\q1 \add so that you couldn’t\add* say that your idol did them,
\q1 \add or\add* \add say that\add* your carved idols and cast figures ordered them \add to happen\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 6 You’ve heard—\add now\add* \add investigate\add* all of it.
\q1 \add Won’t you admit that what I tell you\add* \add is true\add*?
\q1 \add Now\add* I’ll tell you new things,
\q1 and secret things that you didn’t \add previously\add* know.
\q1
\v 7 \add They’re activated now—not in the past\add*,
\q1 and you hadn’t heard of them \add happening\add* before today
\q1 otherwise you might say \add that you expected\add* them.
\b
\q1
\v 8 \add No,\add* you hadn’t heard and you didn’t know
\q1 because from \add way back\add*, \add you never wanted to hear\add*.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* I knew that you act very treacherously
\q1 and \add even\add* from the womb you’ve been called a rebel.
\b
\q1
\v 9 For the sake of my \add reputation\add*, I’ll \add hold back\add* my anger,
\q1 and \add so that I’m praised\add*, I’ll restrain myself from \add destroying\add* you.
\q1
\v 10 Look, I’ve refined you, but not like silver—
\q1 I’ve tested you in the furnace of affliction.
\q1
\v 11 \add But\add* for my own sake I’ll \add take action\add*,
\q1 because how \add could I allow my reputation to be damaged\add*?
\q1 I won’t \add allow others to take the honour that’s due to me\add*.
\s1 The chosen by God destroy of Babylon
\q1
\v 12 Listen to me Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*,
\q1 and Yisrael \add (Israel)\add* who I called.
\q1 I am he, the first, \add and\add* also the last.\x + \xo 48:12: \xt Isa 44:6; Rev 1:17; 22:13.\x*
\q1
\v 13 \add Yes,\add* my hand founded the earth,
\q1 and my right hand stretched out the skies.
\q1 I call to them, \add then\add* they stand together.
\b
\q1
\v 14 Gather together all of you and listen.
\q1 \add Which\add* of \add those idols\add* has announced these things?
\q1 Yahweh’s \add dearest ally\add* will implement \add Yahweh’s\add* desire on Babylon
\q1 and \add apply his power to\add* \add those\add* Chaldeans.
\q1
\v 15 I’ve spoken. I’ve summoned him.
\q1 I’ve brought him, and he will \add succeed in his mission\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 16 Come close to me and listen to this:
\q1 From the beginning, I haven’t spoken in secrecy.
\q1 I was there when those things happened.
\q1 My master Yahweh has sent me and his spirit.
\p
\v 17 Yahweh, Yisrael’s holy \add one\add* \add and\add* \add the one who paid the price for your freedom\add*, says this:
\q1 I am your god, Yahweh, who teaches you to prosper—
\q1 who leads you in the path that you should \add follow\add*.
\q1
\v 18 If you had paid attention to my instructions
\q1 then you would have had peace like a river
\q1 and your righteousness like waves in the ocean.
\q1
\v 19 Your \add descendants\add* would have been \add as numerous\add* as the sand,
\q1 and the offspring from your womb like its grains.
\q1 It wouldn’t have been \add destroyed\add*
\q1 and had its name \add removed from my presence\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 20 Go away from Babylon.\x + \xo 48:20: \xt Rev 18:4.\x*
\q1 Flee from \add those\add* Chaldeans.
\q1 Proclaim this with a happy song.
\q1 Send it out to the \add ends\add* of the earth to say:
\q1 Yahweh has \add paid the price to free\add* his servant Yakov.
\q1
\v 21 They weren’t thirsty when he led them through the \add wildernesses\add*.
\q1 He made water flow out of a rock for them—
\q1 he split open the rock and the water gushed out.
\b
\q1
\v 22 There’s no peace for the \add wicked\add* says Yahweh.\x + \xo 48:22: \xt Isa 57:21.\x*
\c 49
\s1 Yahweh’s servant
\s2 The second servant song
\q1
\v 1 Listen to me \add you\add* islands,\x + \xo 49:1: \xt Jer 1:5.\x*
\q1 and pay attention \add you\add* distant peoples.
\q1 Yahweh called me \add from before I was born\add*—
\q1 he \add knew\add* my name when I was still inside my mother.
\q1
\v 2 He made my mouth like a sharp sword \add that\add* he hid in the shadow of his hand.\x + \xo 49:2: \xt Heb 4:12; Rev 1:16.\x*
\q1 He made me into a polished arrow \add that\add* he hid in his quiver.
\q1
\v 3 Then he told me, ‘Yisrael, you’re my servant,
\q1 and I’ll \add be honoured by others because\add* of you.’
\b
\q1
\v 4 I \add replied\add*, ‘I’ve worked with \add no results\add*
\q1 and used my strength for nothing \add at all\add*.
\q1 Nevertheless, my justice is with Yahweh,
\q1 and my wages are with my god.’
\b
\q1
\v 5 Now Yahweh \add has spoken\add*—
\q1 the \add one\add* who formed me from the womb as his servant—
\q1 to restore Yakov to himself,
\q1 and gather Yisrael to him.
\q1 I’ll be honoured in Yahweh’s eyes,
\q1 and my god has been my strength.
\b
\q1
\v 6 \add Also\add* he says,\x + \xo 49:6: a \xt Isa 42:6; Luk 2:32; Acts 26:23; \xo b \xt Acts 13:47.\x*
\q1 ‘It’s too insignificant for you to be my servant to raise up Yakov’s tribes
\q1 and to bring back those from Yisrael who’ve been preserved.
\q1 I’ll make you into a light for the nations—
\q1 to be \add the one who\add* takes salvation to the \add ends\add* of the earth for me.’
\b
\q1
\v 7 Yahweh, Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*,
\q1 the \add one who paid the price for their freedom\add*
\q1 says to the one whose life is despised,
\q1 the one who’s hated by the nations—a slave of rulers:
\q1 ‘Kings will see and \add stand up\add*,
\q1 and princes will bow down
\q1 on account of Yahweh who is faithful—Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*
\q1 because he has chosen you.’
\s1 Yisrael’s restoration
\q1
\v 8 Yahweh says this:
\q1 I will answer you in a time of favour,
\q1 and I will help you on a day of salvation\x + \xo 49:8: \xt 2Cor 6:2.\x*
\q1 and protect you and \add appoint you to be an agreement\add* for the people,
\q1 to rebuild the land \add so that desolate place can be redistributed as inheritances\add*.
\q1
\v 9 \add You’ll\add* tell the prisoners to come out
\q1 and those in darkness to show themselves.
\q1 They’ll graze \add along\add* roads,
\q1 and over all the pasture on bare hills.
\q1
\v 10 They won’t be hungry or thirsty,\x + \xo 49:10: \xt Rev 7:16-17.\x*
\q1 and the burning heat of the sun won’t \add beat down\add* on them,
\q1 because they’ll be guided by \add one\add* who has compassion on them
\q1 and he’ll lead them to springs of water.
\b
\q1
\v 11 I’ll make all my mountains into a road,
\q1 and \add I’ll fill all the low spots\add* on my highways.
\q1
\v 12 Look, they’ll come from \add far away\add*,
\q1 and look, some from the north and from the west, and from Sinim.
\b
\q1
\v 13 Shout happily \add you\add* sky and be cheerful \add you\add* earth
\q1 and shout with joy \add you\add* mountains
\q1 because Yahweh has comforted his people
\q1 and has compassion on \add them when they’re suffering\add*.
\p
\v 14 \add But\add* Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* said, ‘Yahweh has abandoned me,
\q1 and my master has forgotten me.’
\p
\v 15 Would a woman forget her \add young baby\add*
\q1 \add or\add* have no compassion on the child \add that she’s given birth to\add*?
\q1 \add Even if she could\add* forget, I won’t forget you.
\q1
\v 16 Look, I’ve written \add your name\add* on my palms.
\q1 \add I’m always thinking about\add* your \add city\add* walls.
\b
\q1
\v 17 Your children are hurrying.
\q1 Those who destroyed and ravaged you, are going away from you.
\q1
\v 18 \add Look up and see all around you\add*,
\q1 they’re all gathering together—coming towards you.
\q1 Yahweh declares, As surely as I live,
\q1 you’ll ‘put them all on’ like jewelry,
\q1 and you’ll tie them on like a bride.
\q1
\v 19 \add Look up\add* because your ruined and desolate places,
\q1 and your devastated land,
\q1 will be too cramped for the \add coming\add* inhabitants,
\q1 and those who swallowed you up will be far away.
\q1
\v 20 Yet \add your descendants\add* \add who were born in captivity\add* will say in your ears,
\q1 ‘This place is too cramped for us.
\q1 \add Move over to make room for us to live\add* \add here\add*.’
\q1
\v 21 Then you’ll think to yourself, ‘Who fathered these \add children\add*?
\q1 I was bereaved and barren—taken into exile and thrown away. Who raised these \add children\add*?
\q1 I was left alone, \add so\add* where did these children \add come from\add*?’
\b
\q1
\v 22 My master Yahweh says this:
\q1 Look, I’ll lift my hand up to the nations,
\q1 and raise my banner to the peoples.
\q1 They’ll bring your sons on their laps,
\q1 and they’ll carry your daughters on their shoulders.
\q1
\v 23 Kings will become your \add children’s tutors\add*,
\q1 and their noble ladies will become your wet nurses.
\q1 They’ll bow down to you with their faces to the ground
\q1 and lick the dust from your feet.
\q1 →Then you’ll know that I am Yahweh—those who \add patiently rely on my assistance\add* won’t be humiliated.
\b
\q1
\v 24 Can the booty be snatched from a warrior,
\q1 or can captives escape from a tyrant.\f + \fr 49:24 \ft Using the reading from the Qumran scroll here.\f*
\q1
\v 25 But Yahweh says this:
\q1 Even the warrior’s captives will be taken \add from him\add*,
\q1 and the spoils will be \add recovered\add* from a tyrant,
\q1 →and I’ll oppose your opponent and rescue your children.
\q1
\v 26 I’ll cause those who mistreated you to eat their own flesh,
\q1 and they’ll get drunk on the wine of their own blood.
\q1 Then \add everybody\add* will know that I am your rescuer, Yahweh,
\q1 and Yakov’s powerful \add one\add* who \add paid the price for your freedom\add*.
\c 50
\p
\v 1 Yahweh says this:
\q1 Where’s the divorce \add papers\add* for your mother who I sent away?
\q1 Which of my creditors did I sell you all to,
\q1 because you were all sold because of your \add disobedience\add*?
\q1 And your mother was sent away because of your \add rebellion\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 2 Why did I come when there wasn’t anyone \add there\add*?
\q1 \add Why\add* did I call when no one answered?
\q1 \add Was I unable to pay\add* the ransom?
\q1 Didn’t I have enough strength to rescue \add you\add*?
\q1 Look, when I scold the ocean, it dries up.
\q1 I can turn rivers into a wilderness—
\q1 →its fish will stink because they’ll die of thirst because there’s no water.
\q1
\v 3 I clothe the skies with darkness,
\q1 and I place sackcloth as their covering.
\s1 Yahweh’s obedient servant
\s2 The third servant song
\q1
\v 4 My master Yahweh, has given me a tongue \add that keeps learning\add*—
\q1 knowing how to help the weary with a message.
\q1 He wakes me in the morning—
\q1 wakes me up to listen \add to his teaching\add*.
\q1
\v 5 My master Yahweh, has opened my \add ears\add*.
\q1 I haven’t been rebellious
\q1 \add and\add* I haven’t turned back \add from what I was asked\add*.
\q1
\v 6 I gave my back to those who struck me,\x + \xo 50:6: \xt Mat 26:67; Mrk 14:65.\x*
\q1 and my cheeks to those who made them bare.
\q1 I didn’t hide my face from insults and \add getting spat on\add*
\q1
\v 7 \add but\add* my master Yahweh will help me.
\q1 Therefore I’m not humiliated,
\q1 so I’ve made my face \add look determined\add* like flint
\q1 because I know that I won’t be ashamed.
\q1
\v 8 The \add one who’ll declare me innocent\add* is close by.\x + \xo 50:8-9: \xt Rom 8:33-34.\x*
\q1 Who will \add bring charges against me\add*? Let’s stand \add in court\add* together.
\q1 Who is \add my accuser\add*? Let him approach me.
\q1
\v 9 Listen, my master Yahweh will help me.
\q1 Who is it who condemns me as guilty?
\q1 They’ll all wear out like clothes—the moths will eat them.
\b
\q1
\v 10 \add How many of you strive to obey\add* Yahweh,
\q1 listening to his servant’s \add words\add*?
\q1 Who \add among you all\add* walks in \add deep darkness\add* without \add light\add*?
\q1 \add Learn to\add* trust Yahweh and to depend on \add your\add* god.
\q1
\v 11 Look, all of you who kindle fires and \add carry flaming torches\add*.
\q1 Walk in the light from your fire and from the kindling that you’re all burning.
\q1 That is what you’ll receive from my hand.
\q1 You’ll all lie down in pain.
\c 51
\s1 Comforting words for Yerushalem
\p
\v 1 Listen to me, all of you who \add strive to do what’s right\add*—
\q1 you who \add want to follow Yahweh’s instructions\add*.
\q1 Look at the rock that you where chiselled from,
\q1 and at the mouth of the cistern that you were quarried out of.
\q1
\v 2 Look at your \add ancestor\add*, Avraham,
\q1 and Sarah who bore you all,
\q1 because I called him as one \add person\add*,
\q1 →then I blessed him and made him many,
\q1
\v 3 because Yahweh will comfort Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*.
\q1 He will comfort all its ruined places,
\q1 and make her wilderness like Eden
\q1 and her desert plains like Yahweh’s garden.
\q1 Joy and happiness will \add come from\add* there—
\q1 thanksgiving and the \add sounds\add* of music.
\b
\q1
\v 4 Pay attention to me, my people.
\q1 and \add you\add* my nation, \add listen carefully\add*,
\q1 because \add I will send out my instructions\add*,
\q1 and in an instant, I’ll make my justice as a light for the nations.
\q1
\v 5 \add I’m ready to declare you as innocent\add*.
\q1 My salvation will go out.
\q1 My arms \add will bring justice\add* to the peoples.
\q1 The islands wait eagerly—waiting for my arm.
\q1
\v 6 \add Look upwards to the skies\add*
\q1 ^and \add down\add* to the earth below,
\q1 because the skies will be dispersed like smoke,
\q1 and the earth will wear out like \add a piece of clothing\add*
\q1 and its inhabitants will die like gnats.
\q1 \add However, when I save you, you’ll be free\add* forever,
\q1 and \add I’ll only ever do what is right\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 7 Listen to me, all of you who know \add what is right\add*—
\q1 people with my instructions \add always\add* in their \add thoughts\add*.
\q1 Don’t \add be afraid of getting insulted by people\add*,
\q1 and don’t be dismayed by their abuse,
\q1
\v 8 because \add moths\add* will eat them like a \add piece of clothing\add*,
\q1 and \add their\add* larva will devour them like \add they do with\add* wool.
\q1 However, \add I will only ever do what is right\add*,
\q1 and \add when I save you, you’ll be free throughout the generations\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 9 Wake up, wake up! Yahweh, \add strengthen yourself\add*!
\q1 Wake up like \add back\add* in the old days—
\q1 the generations \add from long ago\add*.
\q1 Wasn’t it you who pierced the sea monster Rahab and cut it into pieces?
\q1
\v 10 Wasn’t it you who dried up the ocean—those large, deep waters—
\q1 \add the one\add* who made the deep seas into a way for those \add who’ve been set free\add* to pass over?
\q1
\v 11 Then those who Yahweh \add has paid the price for their freedom\add*, will return,
\q1 and go to Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* with happy shouts,
\q1 and with happiness \add always showing on their faces\add*.
\q1 Gladness and joy will overtake them—
\q1 sorrow and mourning will \add disappear\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 12 \add It’s me who’s the one who\add* comforts you all.
\q1 Why would you be afraid of \add other\add* humans \add who are just mortal\add*,
\q1 or \add other\add* \add descendants of humankind who are a temporary as\add* grass.
\q1
\v 13 Then you’ve forgotten Yahweh who made you
\q1 and who stretched out the skies and \add made the earth’s foundations\add*.
\q1 You’ve been in dread the entire day \add as your angry oppressor approaches ready to destroy\add* \add you\add*.
\q1 \add But\add* where is the oppressor’s anger \add now\add*?
\q1
\v 14 The one who stoops over will be quickly released.
\q1 He won’t die in the pit and won’t lack his food.
\b
\q1
\v 15 I am your god Yahweh who stirs up the sea
\q1 and its waves roar.
\q1 Commander-in-chief Yahweh is his name.
\q1
\v 16 I’ve \add given you my messages to proclaim\add*,
\q1 and I’ve \add protected\add* you with my hand—
\q1 planting the skies and founding the earth,
\q1 and telling Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* that you are my people.
\s1 The cup of anger removed from Yerushalem
\q1
\v 17 Rouse yourself, rouse yourself. \add Get up\add*, Yerushalem—
\q1 you who drank the cup from Yahweh’s hand \add that was filled with\add* his anger.
\q1 You drank the cup \add that makes you stagger\add*—you drained it.
\q1
\v 18 \add Despite\add* all the children that she’s borne, there’s no one to lead her,
\q1 and there’s no one to hold her hand out of all the children that she’s brought up.
\b
\q1
\v 19 Those two things have happened to you:
\q1 Who shows sympathy to you \add after\add* the devastation and destruction?
\q1 \add Who\add* comforts you \add after\add* the famine and \add war\add*?
\q1
\v 20 Your children have fainted and they lie at the \add end\add* of every street like antelope \add caught\add* in a net.
\q1 They’re full of Yahweh’s anger—the rebuke from your god,
\q1
\b
\v 21 so \add listen\add* to this \add you\add* oppressed \add one\add*,
\q1 and \add the one\add* who’s drunk, but not from wine.
\q1
\v 22 This is what your master Yahweh,
\q1 and your god who defends your people, says:
\q1 Listen, I’ve taken \add that\add* cup of suffering out of your hand—
\q1 the goblet \add containing\add* my rage. You’ll no longer have to drink it.
\q1
\v 23 \add Instead\add*, I’ll put it into your tormentors’ hand—
\q1 those who told you to bow down so they could walk over the top of you,
\q1 and made your back like the ground or the street for walking on.
\c 52
\s1 Yahweh will rescue Yerushalem
\q1
\v 1 Wake up, wake up, \add strengthen yourself\add* Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*.\x + \xo 52:1: \xt Rev 21:2-27.\x*
\q1 Put your beautiful clothes on, Yerushalem, sacred city,
\q1 because the uncircumcised and the ‘unclean’ people won’t enter you again.
\q1
\v 2 Shake yourself free from the dust.
\q1 \add Take action\add*, \add you\add* captive Yerushalem.
\q1 Release the chains from your neck, \add you\add* captive daughter of Tsiyyon
\q1
\v 3 because Yahweh says this:
\q1 You were sold for nothing
\q1 and \add you’ll gain your freedom without any payment\add*,
\q1
\v 4 because my master Yahweh says this:
\q1 My people went down to Egypt to stay there \add long ago\add*,
\q1 and then Assyria \add (Heb. Asshur)\add* has oppressed \add the nation\add* for nothing.
\p
\v 5 Now Yahweh declares:
\q1 My people were taken for \add no reason\add*.
\q1 His rulers mock him\x + \xo 52:5: \xt Rom 2:24.\x*
\q1 and my name is continually slandered \add throughout\add* the day.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 6 Therefore my people will know my name because on that day
\q1 it will be me speaking and saying, ‘Here I am.’
\q1
\v 7 How delightful is the one who brings good news across the mountains announcing peace—\x + \xo 52:7: \xt Nah 1:15; Acts 10:36; Rom 10:15; Eph 6:15.\x*
\q1 bringing good news that announces \add a coming rescuer\add*,
\q1 \add and\add* telling Tsiyyon that their god reigns.
\q1
\v 8 Your watchmen will \add all\add* \add call out loudly at the same time\add*.
\q1 They’ll \add all\add* \add shout happily because each of them\add* will see that Yahweh has returned to Tsiyyon.
\b
\q1
\v 9 \add Start shouting out happily\add* \add you\add* \add ruined\add* places in Yerushalem
\q1 because Yahweh has \add encouraged\add* his people—he’s \add paid the price for Yerushalem’s freedom\add*.
\q1
\v 10 In \add front of\add* all the nations, Yahweh has \add revealed that he’s holy and powerful\add*,
\q1 and \add even\add* the ends of the earth will see that our god \add rescues his people\add*.
\q1
\v 11 Get out, get out, leave that place! Don’t touch anything that’s ‘unclean’.\x + \xo 52:11: \xt 2Cor 6:17.\x*
\q1 Get out from among it. Purify yourselves, \add all of you who carry Yahweh within you\add*,
\q1
\v 12 because you won’t leave out in a rush.
\q1 You all won’t have to flee \add hurriedly\add*
\q1 because Yahweh will \add go ahead of you all\add*,
\q1 and Yisrael’s god \add will bring up the rear\add*.
\s1 The suffering servant
\s2 The fourth servant song
\p
\v 13 Listen, my servant will prosper—
\q1 he’ll be \add promoted and highly honoured\add*.
\q1
\v 14 Many people were horrified at you—his appearance was so disfigured
\q1 and his body \add was so disfigured\add* \add that he no longer looked like a man\add*.
\q1
\v 15 So he’ll startle many nations.
\q1 Kings will shut their mouths because even if they hadn’t been told about it,
\q1 they’ll see and understand what they hadn’t heard about.\x + \xo 52:15: \xt Rom 15:21.\x*
\c 53
\p
\v 1 Who has believed our message,\x + \xo 53:1: \xt Rom 10:16; Yhn 12:38.\x*
\q1 and who has Yahweh’s \add power\add* been revealed to?
\q1
\v 2 He grew in front of him like a young plant,
\q1 and like a root out of the dry ground.
\q1 He had no \add fancy\add* form or splendour to look at,
\q1 and his appearance \add didn’t attract us to him\add*.
\q1
\v 3 He was despised and rejected by people—
\q1 a man \add with a lot of\add* pain and familiar with sickness
\q1 like someone that \add most people would look away from\add*
\q1 and despise him, \add rather than to\add* esteem him.
\b
\q1
\v 4 \add Despite that\add*, he’s borne our sicknesses
\q1 and carried our pains.
\q1 We \add thought\add* that he’d been struck down by God—
\q1 attacked and made to suffer.\x + \xo 53:4: \xt Mat 8:17.\x*
\q1
\v 5 \add But\add* he was pierced for our disobedience,
\q1 and crushed for our wicked actions.
\q1 The punishment that \add gave us\add* peace was on him,
\q1 and we were healed \add thanks\add* to his wounds.\x + \xo 53:5: \xt 1Pe 2:24.\x*
\q1
\v 6 We’ve all strayed away like sheep—
\q1 \add everyone’s gone in their own direction\add*
\q1 and Yahweh has placed all our disobedience onto him.\x + \xo 53:6: \xt 1Pe 2:25.\x*
\b
\q1
\v 7 He was oppressed and tormented
\q1 \add but\add* like a lamb being led away to be slaughtered, he didn’t open his mouth,
\q1 and like a sheep that’s silent in front of its shearers, he didn’t open his mouth.\x + \xo 53:7: \xt Rev 5:6.\x*
\q1
\v 8 \add After\add* oppression and judgement, he was taken away,
\q1 \add but how many of his peers even cared\add* that he was cut off from the land of the living?
\q1 He was wounded because of the disobedience of my people.
\q1
\v 9 His burial place was among the criminals,
\q1 and a rich man at his death,
\q1 although he’d committed no violent acts,
\q1 and \add had never spoken deceitfully\add*.\x + \xo 53:9: \xt 1Pe 2:22.\x*
\b
\q1
\v 10 \add But\add* Yahweh desired to crush him—
\q1 he made him sick if it would make his life a guilt offering.
\q1 He will live long and see offspring,
\q1 and Yahweh’ plans will prosper \add through his work\add*.
\q1
\v 11 Due to his internal anguish, he’ll be able to see.
\q1 He’ll be satisfied with his knowledge.
\q1 My \add obedient\add* servant will justify many,
\q1 and he will carry their disobedience.
\q1
\v 12 \add Because of that,\add* I’ll allocate a portion for him.
\q1 He’ll divide out the plunder to a powerful people
\q1 because he poured out his life \add resulting in\add* his death.
\q1 He was included with the wicked,
\q1 and he bore the disobedience of many people,
\q1 and he intervened on behalf of the disobedient.\x + \xo 53:12: \xt Luk 22:37.\x*
\c 54
\s1 Yahweh’s love for Yerushalem
\p
\v 1 Sing happily \add you\add* barren women who has never given birth.\x + \xo 54:1: \xt Gal 4:27.\x*
\q1 Break into a cheery song and \add celebrate\add*, \add you\add* who’ve never been in labour,
\q1 because the desolate woman now has more children than the married woman did says Yahweh.
\q1
\v 2 Widen your tent and stretch your tent curtains further out without restraint.
\q1 Make your tent ropes longer and \add drive your stakes in deep\add*
\q1
\v 3 because you’ll spread out \add both\add* to the right and to the left,
\q1 and your descendants will conquer nations
\q1 and \add settle\add* in cities \add that had become desolate\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 4 Don’t be afraid because you won’t be put to shame,
\q1 and don’t be discouraged because you won’t be disgraced,
\q1 because you’ll forget the shame from your youth.
\q1 You’ll no longer remember the disgrace from \add when you were made a widow\add*
\q1
\v 5 because your husband is \add the one who made you\add*—
\q1 his name is Commander-in-chief Yahweh.
\q1 Yisrael’s holy \add one\add* is your protector.
\q1 He’s called the god of the \add whole world\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 6 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh has called you back
\q1 as if you were an abandoned wife \add with a wounded\add* spirit,
\q1 or a young wife who was rejected.
\p Your god says:
\q1
\v 7 I abandoned you for a \add little while\add*,
\q1 ^but \add now\add* I’ll \add bring you back\add* with great compassion.
\q1
\v 8 I \add kept away from you for a while\add* in a flood of severe anger,
\q1 \add but\add* with \add my\add* permanent loyal commitment, I’ll have compassion on you.
\p Yahweh \add who paid the price for your freedom\add* says:
\q1
\v 9 For me, this is like Noah’s flood—
\q1 just as I promised to never again \add to cover\add* the earth,
\q1 so \add too\add* I promise not to be angry at you or to rebuke you.
\q1
\v 10 Even if the mountains disappear and the hills shake,
\q1 my loyal commitment to you won’t \add disappear\add* and my agreement for peace won’t be shaken,
\q1 says Yahweh, the one who has compassion for you.
\s1 The new Yerushalem
\p
\v 11 You \add city\add* which is suffering \add like being battered in a\add* storm
\q1 \add with no one to comfort you\add*,
\q1 listen, I’ll \add rebuild you with\add* turquoise stones,
\q1 and place sapphires in your foundations.
\q1
\v 12 I’ll make your towers out of rubies
\q1 and your gates from beryl stones,
\q1 and all your \add walls\add* from \add other precious\add* stones.
\b
\q1
\v 13 All your children will be followers of Yahweh,
\q1 and \add they’ll\add* \add experience extended\add* peace.
\b
\q1
\v 14 You’ll be established \add with justice\add*—far away from oppression.
\q1 You won’t be afraid of \add acts of\add* terror because it won’t approach you.
\b
\q1
\v 15 Listen, no one will attack you \add that I haven’t sent\add*.
\q1 Anyone stirring up trouble against you will fail.
\b
\q1
\v 16 Look, I created the craftsman who fans the charcoal fire,
\q1 and produces weapons as his work,
\q1 and it’s me who created a destroyer to \add cause destruction\add*.
\q1
\v 17 No weapon that’s made to be used against you will succeed,
\q1 and those who \add speak out accusations against you\add* will be condemned as guilty.
\q1 That’s the inheritance of Yahweh’s servants,
\q1 and \add I, Yahweh, will pronounce them as innocent\add*.
\c 55
\s1 Come and freely find Yahweh
\p
\v 1 Hey, \add you\add* who are thirsty, go to the waters,
\q1 and \add you\add* who have no money, go and buy grain and eat.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* come and buy grain without money,
\q1 and wine and milk with no price on them.
\q1
\v 2 \add Why pay money\add* for what’s not food,
\q1 and work hard for what doesn’t satisfy?
\q1 Listen carefully to me and eat good \add things\add*
\q1 and enjoy \add rich foods\add*.
\q1
\v 3 \add Pay attention\add* and come to me.
\q1 Listen so you all can live,
\q1 and I’ll make a permanent agreement with you all—
\q1 the reliable, loyal commitment \add shown to\add* David.
\q1
\v 4 Listen, I’ve made him a witness to the nations—
\q1 a leader and commander of the people \add groups\add*.
\q1
\v 5 Look, you’ll call a nation that you didn’t know,
\q1 and that nation that didn’t know you \add either\add*, will run to you
\q1 because of your god Yahweh,
\q1 and \add because\add* Yisrael’s holy \add one\add* has \add caused you to be honoured\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 6 Search for Yahweh while he lets himself be found.
\q1 Call out to Yahweh \add for help\add* while he’s near.
\q1
\v 7 Let the wicked \add person\add* abandon their \add behaviour\add*,
\q1 and the evil \add person\add* \add abandon\add* their \add plans\add*.
\q1 Then let them return to Yahweh so that he can have compassion for him,
\q1 and \add return\add* to our god because he’ll \add freely\add* forgive \add them\add*.
\p
\v 8 \add Yes,\add* my thoughts aren’t \add like\add* your thoughts,
\q1 and your ways aren’t \add like\add* my ways.
\m \add That’s what Yahweh declares\add*.
\q1
\v 9 \add Yes\add*, \add just\add* as the skies are higher than the earth,
\q1 so too my ways are higher than your ways
\q1 and my thoughts \add are higher\add* than your thoughts.
\b
\q1
\v 10 Just like how the rain and snow come down from the skies
\q1 and don’t return there, but water the land
\q1 that then makes it produce and sprout,
\q1 andR nettles, seed is given to the sower and bread to the consumer,
\q1
\v 11 so too when my message leaves my mouth.
\q1 It won’t return to me empty,
\q1 but when it’s done what was desired,
\q1 and after having prospered \add in the place where\add* I sent it.
\b
\q1
\v 12 You’ll all go out cheerfully
\q1 and be led in peace.
\q1 The mountains and hills will let out a happy shout,
\q1 and all the trees in the countryside will clap their hands.
\q1
\v 13 Instead of thornbushes, cypress \add trees\add* will grow up.
\q1 Rather than nettles, myrtle \add trees\add* will \add rise\add* up,
\q1 and it’ll \add increase\add* Yahweh’s \add reputation\add*
\q1 as a permanent sign that will never be \add destroyed\add*.
\c 56
\s1 Salvation for others
\p
\v 1 Yahweh says this:
\q1 \add Promote\add* justice and do \add what is right\add*
\q1 because \add the time when I’ll save you\add* is coming soon,
\q1 and my righteousness will be revealed.
\q1
\v 2 Everyone who does that will be blessed,
\q1 and humanity’s child who takes hold of it,
\q1 who \add observes\add* the rest day—not defiling it,
\q1 and who \add stays away\add* from doing anything evil.
\b
\q1
\v 3 Don’t let the son of any foreigner who’s \add decided to follow\add* Yahweh,
\q1 say, ‘Yahweh will certainly separate me out from his people.’
\q1 And don’t let the \add castrated slave\add* say, ‘Look, I’m a withered-up tree,’
\q1
\v 4 because Yahweh says this:
\q1 To the \add castrated slaves\add* who observe my rest days
\q1 and choose \add what pleases me\add* and \add are faithful\add* to my agreement,
\q1
\v 5 I will give them a monument and a good name in my house and inside my walls
\q1 that’s better than sons and daughters.
\q1 I’ll give \add them\add* a permanent \add good\add* reputation which won’t be terminated.
\q1
\v 6 Then the children of foreigners who \add strive to follow\add* Yahweh,
\q1 to serve him and to love \add his\add* name, \add and\add* to be his servants,
\q1 who \add observe\add* the rest day without defiling it,
\q1 and who cling to my agreement,
\q1
\v 7 I’ll bring them to my sacred mountain\x + \xo 56:7: \xt Mat 21:13; Mrk 11:17; Luk 19:46.\x*
\q1 and make them happy in my \add temple where people pray\add*.
\q1 Their burnt offerings and sacrifices will be acceptable on my altar,
\q1 because my \add temple\add* will be called a prayer house for all the \add nations\add*.
\p
\v 8 My master Yahweh, who gathers Yisrael’s outcasts, says this:
\q1 I’ll gather others \add beside those already\add* gathered.
\s1 The judging of teachers of Yisrael
\p
\v 9 All you animals in the countryside, come to devour,
\q1 \add yes,\add* all you animals in the forest.
\q1
\v 10 All of its watchmen are blind—they don’t know \add what’s going on\add*.
\q1 They’re all voiceless dogs, unable to bark.
\q1 They dream about lying down—\add enjoying a nap\add*.
\q1
\v 11 The dogs have a \add fierce\add* appetite—they’re never full.
\q1 The shepherds know nothing and don’t understand.
\q1 They’ve all gone their own way and \add make money from their illegal sidelines\add*.
\q1
\v 12 Come on, take some wine and let’s drink strong drink.
\q1 Tomorrow will be just like today except we’ll have even more.
\c 57
\s1 Yisrael’s idolatry is condemned
\p
\v 1 The \add godly\add* \add people\add* die \add but no one takes it to\add* heart.
\q1 Those with loyal commitment are removed \add but\add* no one \add knows what’s going on\add*
\q1 because the \add godly\add* \add people\add* are \add pulled back\add* from facing evil.
\q1
\v 2 \add They\add* go in peace.
\q1 They’ve walked on a straightforward \add path\add*
\q1 \add and now\add* they rest on their beds.
\b
\q1
\v 3 \add But\add* come here \add you\add* children of a sorceress—
\q1 offspring of \add adulterers and prostitutes\add*.
\q1
\v 4 Who are you all making fun of?
\q1 Who are you \add speaking out against\add* and poking your tongues out against?
\q1 You’re all children of wickedness—offspring of deception
\q1
\v 5 who \add burn with lust\add* under oak \add trees\add*—\add in fact\add* under every green tree.
\q1 You all slaughter children in valleys under the clefts in the cliffs.
\q1
\v 6 You \add stand up large,\add* smooth stones from the riverbed
\q1 \add and offer them a portion\add* of your food.
\q1 You pour out \add wine as\add* a drink offering and offer up a grain offering.
\q1 Will I relent \add in taking action about those activities\add*?
\b
\q1
\v 7 You \add slept up high at the hilltop shrines\add*
\q1 where you went up to also offer a sacrifice,
\q1
\v 8 and you’ve put your symbols behind the door and doorposts.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* away from me you \add stripped off\add*
\q1 and \add filled your bed with others\add*.
\q1 You had an agreement with those whose bed you loved—
\q1 \add enjoying their bodies\add*.
\q1
\v 9 You took oil and travelled to the king,
\q1 \add along with lots of\add* perfumes.
\q1 Then you sent your ambassadors \add to distant places\add*,
\q1 and even descended to \add the world of the dead\add*.
\q1
\v 10 You were tired from your \add long\add* journey,
\q1 but you didn’t say that \add it’s all just hopeless\add*.
\q1 You found \add new things to do\add* so then you didn’t become weak.
\b
\q1
\v 11 Who \add very you so afraid of\add* that you lie,
\q1 and don’t remember me \add or think about me\add*?
\q1 Haven’t I been silent for a long \add time now\add*
\q1 so it’s not me that you’re afraid of.
\q1
\v 12 I’ll talk about your deeds and \add how you do what’s right\add*
\q1 \add but\add* they won’t benefit you.
\q1
\v 13 When you call out \add for help\add*, let your collection rescue you,
\q1 \add but\add* a wind will carry them all away—
\q1 a breath will take them away.
\q1 \add But\add* those who \add rely on me for safety\add* will inherit the land,
\q1 and will \add take possession of\add* my \add holy\add* mountain.
\s1 God will help and heal
\p
\v 14 Then he’ll say:
\q1 Pile it up, pile it up, make a track \add through\add*.
\q1 \add Remove\add* the stumbling blocks from the path for my people.
\b
\p
\v 15 The \add one\add* who’s high and honoured, who lives forever and whose name is holy, says:
\q1 I live in a place that’s holy and up high,
\q1 \add but also\add* with the oppressed \add person\add* and with the humble \add person\add*,
\q1 →to restore the spirit of the humble and to \add encourage\add* those who \add feel\add* crushed.
\q1
\v 16 \add However,\add* I won’t \add argue the point\add* forever,
\q1 and I won’t remain permanently angry,
\q1 because \add those who stand in front of me\add* would faint—
\q1 \add the creatures\add* that I myself made.
\q1
\v 17 I was angry at the wickedness of \add their\add* dishonest gain and I struck \add them\add*.
\q1 I hid and I was angry, \add but\add* \add they\add* \add decided to go against me\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 18 I’ve seen \add their\add* ways and I’ll heal \add them\add*,
\q1 and I’ll lead \add them\add* and comfort \add them\add* and \add their\add* mourners.
\q1
\v 19 I’ll \add enable them to shout happily\add*,
\q1 ‘Peace, peace, to those \add both\add* near and far,’
\q1 and I will heal \add them\add* says Yahweh.
\q1
\v 20 \add But\add* the wicked are like the ocean \add in a storm\add*,
\q1 because it’s unable to stay calm, \add but rather\add* it stirs up slush and mud.
\q1
\v 21 My god says that there’s no peace for those who are wicked.
\c 58
\s1 Don’t fast just for looks
\p
\v 1 \add Shout loudly\add*. Don’t hold back.
\q1 Raise your voice like a trumpet
\q1 and \add confront\add* my people with their wickedness,
\q1 and Yakov’s \add descendants\add* with their \add disobedience\add*.
\q1
\v 2 They search for me \add every\add* day
\q1 and want \add to learn about\add* my ways like a nation that \add does what is right\add*,
\q1 and they haven’t abandoned the \add values\add* of their god.
\q1 They ask me to make judgements \add that are far and right\add*.
\q1 They want god to approach \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 3 Why did we fast, as you \add didn’t even look\add*?
\q1 We humbled ourselves and you \add didn’t even notice\add*?
\b
\q1 Listen, when you fasted \add was it just for your own needs\add*?
\q1 You all certainly drive your labourers hard!
\q1
\v 4 Look, you all fast \add with\add* strife and contention,
\q1 and strike out with \add vicious clenched\add* fists.
\q1 You all don’t fast today to make your voices heard up on high.
\q1
\v 5 Is that the \add kind of fasting\add* that I would choose?
\q1 A day when a \add person\add* humbles themself and bows their head down like a bulrush does.
\q1 \add They wear\add* sackcloth and \add form a bed of\add* ashes \add to sit on\add*.
\q1 Is that \add really\add* a fast that’s acceptable to Yahweh?
\b
\q1
\v 6 Isn’t this the fast that I would \add prefer\add*?
\q1 \add When you all\add* remove chains that were wickedly \add put on others\add*,
\q1 and undo the ropes from the yoke \add that forced them to comply\add*?
\q1 Let go all those who’ve been crushed,
\q1 and break every yoke \add that burdened them\add*.
\q1
\v 7 Isn’t it to \add share\add* your food \add with those who are hungry\add*,
\q1 and to bring the poor, homeless \add people\add* into your house?
\q1 When you see \add someone\add* naked, clothe them,
\q1 and don’t hide yourself from your own \add relatives\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 8 Then your light will break through like the dawn,
\q1 and your healing will quickly spring up.
\q1 Your \add right actions will go ahead of you\add*
\q1 and Yahweh’s honour will \add follow along behind you\add*.
\q1
\v 9 Then you’ll call out and Yahweh will answer.
\q1 You’’ll cry for help and he’ll say, ‘Here I am.’
\b
\q1 If you remove the \add burden of\add* the yoke from among you,
\q1 \add as well as\add* the pointing finger and wicked speech,
\q1
\v 10 give yourself to the hungry
\q1 and \add give those who are suffering what they need\add*
\q1 then your light will rise in the darkness
\q1 and your darkness will be like the noonday.
\q1
\v 11 Then Yahweh will continually lead you
\q1 and satisfy your appetite in arid regions.
\q1 He’ll strengthen your bones and will be like a watered garden,
\q1 and like a spring \add that never runs dry\add*.
\q1
\v 12 Then some of you will rebuild the ancient ruins—
\q1 you’ll \add restore\add* the foundations \add from generations ago\add*
\q1 and you’ll be called the repairer of the wall—
\q1 the one who restores streets to live in.
\s1 Blessings for keeping the rest day
\p
\v 13 If on the rest day, you turn back \add from what you wanted to do\add*
\q1 and don’t \add try to please yourself\add* on my sacred day,
\q1 \add enjoy\add* Yahweh’s sacred and honourable rest day,
\q1 and honour it instead of doing your own \add activities\add* such as finding your own pleasure or \add delivering a speech\add*,
\q1
\v 14 then you’ll take delight in Yahweh.
\q1 I’ll make you ride on the heights of the earth,
\q1 and I’ll \add give you the same blessings that I gave your ancestor\add*, Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*.
\q1 That’s what Yahweh has spoken.
\c 59
\s1 Yisrael’s sins and punishment
\p
\v 1 Listen, \add don’t think that Yahweh can’t\add* rescue \add you\add*,
\q1 \add or that he won’t be able to hear\add* \add you\add*.
\q1
\v 2 However, your \add disobedience causes separation\add* between you all and your god,
\q1 and your sins have \add made him turn away from listening\add* to you,
\q1
\v 3 because your \add hands\add* are defiled with blood,
\q1 and your fingers with sin.
\q1 Your lips \add spew out\add* lies
\q1 and your tongue \add works against justice\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 4 No one \add stands up\add* for \add justice\add*,
\q1 and no one \add pleads their case truthfully\add*.
\q1 They rely on \add being meaningless\add*, \add or fancy words of no value\add*—
\q1 conceiving mischief and \add advancing\add* wickedness.
\q1
\v 5 They hatch vipers’ eggs
\q1 and weave spiders’ webs
\q1 Anyone who eats any of their eggs will die—
\q1 when they’re \add cracked open\add*, a viper will be hatched.
\q1
\v 6 Their \add weavings\add* aren’t for clothes,
\q1 \add so\add* they don’t cover themselves with their products.
\q1 Their products are products of wickedness,
\q1 and their \add hands are involved in\add* violence.
\q1
\v 7 Their feet run towards evil,
\q1 and they’re quick to shed innocent blood.
\q1 \add They’re always thinking\add* about wickedness—
\q1 \add they walk the paths\add* of \add causing\add* ruin and destruction.
\q1
\v 8 They don’t know the way of peace,
\q1 and there’s no justice on their tracks.
\q1 They’ve make their paths crooked—
\q1 \add none of those who\add* tread on them will experience peace.
\s1 Societal sinfulness
\p
\v 9 Therefore, justice is far from \add us\add*
\q1 and righteousness doesn’t reach us.
\q1 We wait for light, \add but\add* look, \add we get\add* darkness.
\q1 \add We wait\add* for gleams of light, \add but\add* walk in the gloom.
\q1
\v 10 We grope \add along\add* the wall like the blind,
\q1 and \add feel around\add* as though we had no eyes.
\q1 Even at midday, we stumble as if it’s twilight—
\q1 among the \add living\add* \add but behaving\add* like the dead.
\q1
\v 11 All of us growl like bears,
\q1 and moan mournfully like doves.
\q1 We \add keep hoping\add* for justice, \add but none comes\add*,
\q1 for rescue, but it’s far away
\q1
\v 12 because our transgressions \add in front of\add* you are many.
\q1 Our sins have testified against us
\q1 because our transgressions are with us,
\q2 and as for our iniquities, we know them.
\q1
\v 13 \add We’ve\add* rebelled and denied Yahweh,
\q1 and turned away from \add following\add* our god—
\q1 \add promoting\add* oppression and rebellion \add instead\add*.
\q1 We’ve conceived and \add told lies as if they were the heart-felt truth\add*.
\q1
\v 14 Justice is driven \add right\add* back,
\q1 and righteousness stands off at a distance,
\q1 because truth has stumbled in the public square,
\q1 and \add honesty\add* can’t enter.
\q1
\v 15 \add So then\add* truth went missing,
\q1 and the one who turned away from evil got robbed.
\q1 Yahweh saw it and wasn’t pleased that there was no justice.
\s1 The assisting of Master of his people
\q1
\v 16 \add Yahweh\add* saw that there wasn’t anyone \add to make a stand\add*,
\q1 and was appalled that there was no one to intervene.
\q1 \add So he applied his own power to bring\add* salvation,
\q1 and his own \add desire to do what’s right,\add* sustained him.\x + \xo 59:16: \xt Isa 63:5.\x*
\q1
\v 17 He put righteousness on like armour,
\q1 and a helmet of salvation on his head.\x + \xo 59:17: \xt Eph 6:14-17; 1Th 5:8.\x*
\q1 He dressed in clothes of vengeance
\q1 and wrapped himself with zeal like a robe.
\q1
\v 18 He will repay his enemies \add for the evil things that they have done\add*.
\q1 He will repay the islands \add with the appropriate reward\add*.
\q1
\v 19 Then \add those in the west\add* will \add respect Yahweh’s reputation\add*,
\q1 and \add in the east\add*, \add will respect\add* his splendour,
\q1 →because he’ll come like a \add swift\add* river with Yahweh’s wind driving it.
\p
\v 20 Then a redeemer will come to Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*
\q1 and to those \add descendants of\add* Yakov \add (Jacob)\add* who repent of \add their disobedience\add*.
\m That’s what Yahweh \add declares\add*.
\p
\v 21 Then Yahweh says:
\q1 This is my agreement with them.
\q1 My spirit which is on you and my messages that I’ve put in your mouth,
\q1 they won’t leave your mouth or the mouths of your descendants,
\q1 \add even the distant generations\add* from now and forever onwards.
\m That is Yahweh’s \add declaration\add*.
\c 60
\s1 Yerushalem’s future splendour
\q1
\v 1 \add Take action\add*, shine, because your light has come,
\q1 and Yahweh’s \add brilliance\add* has risen to shine on you,
\q1
\v 2 \add Yes,\add* listen, darkness will cover the earth.
\q1 and thick darkness \add will blanket\add* the \add nations\add*,
\q1 and then Yahweh will dawn over you,
\q1 and his \add brilliance\add* will appear over you.
\q1
\v 3 Nations will come to your light,
\q1 and kings to your rising brightness.
\q1
\v 4 \add Look up and all around\add* and see all of them gathered together.
\q1 Your sons will come from far away,
\q1 and your \add little\add* daughters will be carried \add back\add* on the hip.
\q1
\v 5 Then you’ll see and be radiant,
\q1 and your heart will be in awe, and broaden,
\q1 because plenty of \add international shipping will come to\add* you,
\q1
\b
\q1
\v 6 Plenty of camels will cover your \add land\add*—
\q1 young camels from Midyan and Efah.
\q1 All of them will come from Sheba.
\q1 They’ll bring gold and frankincense
\q1 and will announce praises to Yahweh.
\q1
\v 7 All the flocks from Kedar will be gathered for you.
\q1 The rams from Nevayot will serve you.
\q1 They’ll be accepted to go up onto my altar,
\q1 and I’ll decorate my house beautifully.
\b
\q1
\v 8 Who are these who fly like a cloud,
\q1 and like doves to their windows?
\q1
\v 9 The islands wait for me, and the ships from Tarshish
\q1 will be first to bring your sons from far away
\q1 along with their gold and silver \add to honour\add* your god Yahweh
\q1 and for Yisrael’s holy \add one\add* because he’s honoured you.
\p
\v 10 The sons of foreigners will rebuild your \add city\add* walls,
\q1 and their kings will serve you,
\q1 because although I struck you in my severe anger,
\q1 \add yet\add* in my favour I’ve had compassion towards you.
\q1
\v 11 Then your \add city\add* gates will be always open—
\q1 they won’t be shut day or night,\x + \xo 60:11: \xt Rev 21:25-26.\x*
\q1 \add so\add* the wealth from \add other\add* nations can be brought to you,
\q1 with their kings being led \add captive\add*.
\q1
\v 12 \add Yes,\add* any nation or kingdom that won’t serve you will perish,
\q1 and the nations will be \add completely destroyed\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 13 Lebanon’s \add best\add* will come to you—
\q1 cypress, fir, and cedar \add timber\add* \add all at once\add*,
\q1 to make my sanctuary beautiful
\q1 and I’ll honour the place \add where I stand\add*.
\q1
\v 14 The descendants of those who oppressed you will come to you
\q1 and all those who despised you will bow down at your feet.\x + \xo 60:14: \xt Rev 3:9.\x*
\q1 They will call you Yahweh’s city—
\q1 Yisrael’s holy \add one\add*—Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 15 Instead of your being abandoned and hated, with no one passing through you,
\q1 I’ll make you a \add thing\add* of perpetual pride—the joy of \add future generations\add*.
\q1
\v 16 You’ll suckle the milk from the nations,
\q1 and feed from the breast of kings,
\q1 and you know that I, Yahweh, am your rescuer and your redeemer—Yakov’s powerful \add one\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 17 Instead of bronze and iron, I’ll bring gold and silver,
\q1 and instead of timber and stones, bronze and iron.
\q1 Then I’ll \add appoint\add* peace as your overseer,
\q1 and righteousness as your supervisors.
\q1
\v 18 Violence won’t be \add experienced\add* in your land—
\q1 \add no more\add* devastation or destruction in your territories.
\q1 You’ll \add realise that salvation protects you like\add* \add city\add* walls
\q1 and praise \add like\add* \add your city\add* gates.
\b
\q1
\v 19 The sun will no longer be your light \add during\add* the day,\x + \xo 60:19: \xt Rev 21:23; 22:5.\x*
\q1 nor will the moon’s brightness shine for you,
\q1 \add but rather,\add* Yahweh will be your perpetual light,
\q1 and your god will be your \add brilliant light\add*.
\q1
\v 20 Your sun will no longer set,
\q1 and your moon will no longer disappear,
\q1 because Yahweh will be your perpetual light,
\q1 and your days of mourning will be \add over\add*.
\q1
\v 21 As for your people, all of them will \add do what is right\add*.
\q1 They will permanently possess the land—the shoot that I planted—
\q1 my handiwork to \add showcase my greatness\add*.
\q1
\v 22 The little \add one\add* will become a thousand,
\q1 and the little nation will become powerful.
\q1 I, Yahweh, will quickly accomplish it at the appropriate time.
\c 61
\s1 The assisting of Yisrael
\q1
\v 1 My master, Yahweh’s spirit is on me
\q1 because Yahweh has \add chosen\add* me
\q1 →to bring good news to those who are suffering.\x + \xo 61:1: \xt Mat 11:5; Luk 7:22.\x*
\q1 He’s sent me to bandage up the brokenhearted,
\q1 to decree freedom for those taken captive,
\q1 and to liberate those who are chained up.
\q1
\v 2 \add He’s sent me\add* to proclaim the year of Yahweh’s favour,\x + \xo 61:2: \xt Mat 5:4.\x*
\q1 and a day of our god’s vengeance,
\q1 and to comfort all those who mourn.
\q1
\v 3 \add It’ll be a time\add* to give Tsiyyon’s mourners a \add nice\add* turban instead of ashes \add on their heads\add*,
\q1 oil \add to show\add* joy \add on their faces\add* instead of mourning,
\q1 a cloak of praise instead of a \add discouraged\add* spirit.
\q1 Then they’ll be called ‘oaks of righteousness’ that Yahweh planted to \add display his splendour\add*.
\q1
\v 4 They’ll rebuild the ancient ruins—
\q1 restoring the places \add that had become deserted\add*.
\q1 They’ll rebuild the devastated cities,
\q1 and places \add that have been in ruins for generations\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 5 Strangers will stand \add out in your fields\add* and shepherd your flocks,
\q1 and sons of foreigners will \add take care of your farms and vineyards\add*.
\q1
\v 6 Then you’ll all be called Yahweh’s priests,
\q1 and it’ll be said that you’re servants of our god.
\q1 You’ll consume the wealth from the nations
\q1 →and you’ll also boast \add because there’ll be so much of it\add*.
\q1
\v 7 Instead of shame, you’ll all have a double \add blessing\add*,
\q1 and \add instead of\add* dishonour, they’ll shout happily about their portion,
\q1 \add Yes,\add* they’ll possess a double portion in their land
\q1 and they’ll have permanent happiness
\q1
\v 8 because I, Yahweh, love justice and hate theft and \add crime\add*.
\q1 Due to \add my\add* faithfulness, I’ll \add repay them for what they’ve been through\add*,
\q1 and I’ll make a permanent agreement with them.
\q1
\v 9 Then their descendants will be known among the nations,
\q1 and their offspring among the people \add groups\add*.
\q1 Everyone who sees them will recognise them
\q1 because they are the \add people\add* who Yahweh has blessed.
\b
\q1
\v 10 I’m \add going to really celebrate\add* Yahweh.
\q1 My inner being will be glad about my god
\q1 because he has dressed me in clothes of a \add free person\add*.
\q1 He’s clothed me with the robe of a \add person declared innocent\add*\x + \xo 61:10: \xt Rev 21:2.\x*
\q1 like the groom puts on a \add nice\add* turban,
\q1 and the bride adorns herself with jewelry.
\q1
\v 11 Just as the \add soil\add* produces growth,
\q1 and as the seeds in the garden start to sprout,
\q1 so too my master, Yahweh, will make righteousness grow
\q1 as well as praise towards all the nations.
\c 62
\s1 Yerushalem’s coming rescue
\q1
\v 1 For the sake of Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*, I won’t be silent.
\q1 and for Yerushalem’s sake, I won’t be quiet,
\q1 until its righteousness proceeds as brightness
\q1 and its salvation like a burning torch.
\q1
\v 2 Then the \add other\add* nations will see your righteousness,
\q1 and all kings \add will see\add* your glory.
\q1 and you’ll be called by a new name that Yahweh \add himself\add* will \add give\add*.
\q1
\v 3 You’ll be a beautiful crown in Yahweh’s hand,
\q1 and a royal turban in your god’s palm.
\q1
\v 4 They won’t \add claim\add* any longer that you’ve been abandoned,
\q1 and they won’t say again that your land has been \add deserted\add*,
\q1 because you’ll be called ‘\add the place that\add* Yahweh likes’.
\q1 \add Also,\add* your land \add will be called\add* ‘married’
\q1 because your land will be married \add to him\add*.
\q1
\v 5 Just like a young man marries a young woman,
\q1 your sons will marry you,
\q1 and as the groom \add is full of happiness about\add* his bride,
\q1 your god will \add be full of happiness about\add* you.
\b
\q1
\v 6 I’ve put watchmen on your walls, Yerushalem.
\q1 They’ll never be silent—night or day.
\q1 You all who are reminding Yahweh, don’t ever stop to rest—
\q1
\v 7 don’t let him rest until he reestablishes \add Yerushalem\add*,
\q1 and until he makes \add it\add* \add something to be praised by the world\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 8 Yahweh has using the strength \add from his power\add*,
\q1 and \add raised his right hand to make a promise\add*:
\q1 I’ll won’t give your grain to your enemies again for their food,
\q1 and foreigners’ children won’t be drinking the new wine that you worked so hard \add to make\add*,
\q1
\v 9 because those who \add harvested\add* \add the grain\add* will eat it,
\q1 and those who collected \add the grapes\add* will drink in my sacred courtyards.
\b
\q1
\v 10 \add Go through, head out\add* the \add city\add* gates. Clear the way for the people.
\q1 Build up, build up the highway. Clear away the stones to raise up a banner for the nations.
\q1
\v 11 Listen, Yahweh has proclaimed to the \add ends\add* of the earth:
\q1 Tell Tsiyyon’s daughter to look because her rescue is about to \add happen\add*.\x + \xo 62:11: \xt Isa 40:10; Rev 22:12.\x*
\q1 Look, he’s brought his reward with him,
\q1 and his wages \add go ahead of\add* him.
\q1
\v 12 The ones that Yahweh \add has paid to have freed\add*
\q1 will be called ‘the sacred people’ by \add others\add*.
\q1 \add Also,\add* you’ll be called ‘the desirable city’—
\q1 the \add one\add* which hasn’t been abandoned.
\c 63
\s1 Yahweh’s vengeance
\p
\v 1 Who’s that coming from Edom,\x + \xo 63:1-6: \xt Isa 34:5-17; Jer 49:7-22; Eze 25:12-14; 35:1-15; Amos 1:11-12; Oba 1-14; Mal 1:2-5.\x*
\q1 \add coming\add* from Botsrah dressed in crimson?
\q1 This one \add dressed like an honoured person\add*,
\q1 \add marching\add* in the greatness of his strength?
\q1 It’s me, \add Yahweh\add*, \add proclaiming what’s right\add*—powerful to rescue.
\b
\q1
\v 2 What’s that red on your clothes?
\q1 Your clothes look like \add you’be been treading\add* \add grapes\add* in a wine-pressing \add pit\add*?
\b
\q1
\v 3 I’ve trodden in the wine-pressing \add pit\add* alone,
\q1 and there wasn’t anyone from the nations with me.
\q1 I trod them in my \add anger\add*,
\q1 and trampled them in my fury.\x + \xo 63:3: \xt Rev 14:20; 19:15.\x*
\q1 and their blood is splattered onto my clothes.\x + \xo 63:3: \xt Rev 19:13.\x*
\q1 All my clothes are \add stained\add*
\q1
\v 4 because \add I had decided that this was\add* the day of vengeance,
\q1 and the year had come \add for me to buy my people’s freedom\add*.
\q1
\v 5 I looked and there wasn’t anyone to help,\x + \xo 63:5: \xt Isa 59:16.\x*
\q1 and I was appalled that no one \add assisted\add*,
\q1 \add but\add* my power gave me victory,
\q1 and my rage sustained me.
\q1
\v 6 I trod down peoples in my \add anger\add*,
\q1 and in my rage, I made them drunk,
\q1 and I \add poured their blood out on\add* the ground.
\s1 Remembering Yahweh’s goodness
\q1
\v 7 I’ll \add tell others about\add* Yahweh’s loyal commitment—
\q1 praising \add him\add* \add for his treatment of\add* us.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* for his \add amazing\add* goodness to Yisrael’s \add descendants\add*,
\q1 which he’s shown us according to his mercy,
\q1 and according to his \add incredible\add* loyal commitment,
\p
\v 8 and he said, “They’re definitely my people—
\q1 children who \add wouldn’t be disloyal\add*,”
\q1 and he became their rescuer.
\q1
\v 9 In all their suffering, \add he also suffered\add*,
\q1 and his messenger \add went ahead of him\add* to rescue them.
\q1 In his love and mercy, he \add paid the price for their freedom\add*,
\q1 through that \add era\add*, he lifted them up and carried them.
\q1
\v 10 \add However,\add* they rebelled and grieved his holy spirit,
\q1 →\add so\add* he turned into their enemy who fought against them.
\b
\q1
\v 11 Then his people recalled \add that era with\add* Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*,
\q1 Where is the \add one\add* who brought them up from the sea
\q1 along with \add those\add* shepherds of his flock?
\q1 Where is the \add one\add* who sent his holy spirit to be among \add them\add*,
\q2
\v 12 who \add transferred his glorious power\add* to Mosheh,
\q1 \add who then\add* divided the \add sea in front of them\add*\x + \xo 63:12: \xt Exo 14:21.\x*
\q1 to gain himself a \add lasting reputation\add*,
\q1
\v 13 who led them through the depths?
\q1 Like a horse in the wilderness, they didn’t stumble.
\q1
\v 14 Like cattle going down a valley, Yahweh’s spirit gave them \add peace\add*,
\q1 so you led your people to give yourself an \add incredible reputation\add*.
\s1 The mercy
\q1
\v 15 Look from heaven
\q1 and see from your wonderful, holy residence.
\q1 Where’s your actions \add full of\add* zeal and power?
\q1 Your \add inner motivation\add* and your compassion have restrained themselves from me.
\q1
\v 16 \add Yes,\add* you are our father, although Avraham doesn’t know us
\q1 and Yisrael doesn’t recognise us.
\q1 You, Yahweh, are our father
\q1 and the one who \add bought us our freedom\add* long ago.
\q1
\v 17 Yahweh, why do you make us wander from your paths—
\q1 hardening our hearts \add so we don’t want to obey\add* you.
\q1 Return for your servants’ sake—
\q1 the tribes \add who are\add* your inheritance.
\q1
\v 18 For a \add while\add*, your holy people possessed your sanctuary.
\q1 \add Now\add* our enemies have trampled over your \add sacred place\add*.
\q1
\v 19 We’ve become like those who you never ruled over—
\q1 like those who never called \add to you for help\add*.
\c 64
\p
\v 1 If you’d torn the skies open, \add then\add* had come down,
\q1 the mountains would have shaken \add in front of\add* you.
\q1
\v 2 Just as fire ignites twigs and boils water,
\q1 making your name known to your enemies \add will make\add* the nations tremble \add in front of\add* you.
\q1
\v 3 When you did \add amazing things\add* that we weren’t expecting, you came down.
\q1 The mountains shook \add in front of\add* you.
\q1
\v 4 Since ancient times, no one has heard,
\q1 and people’s ears haven’t listened \add to anything like that\add*.
\q1 No eye has seen any god other than you,
\q1 →who \add takes action\add* for \add those who\add* wait, \add expecting his help\add*.\x + \xo 64:4: \xt 1Cor 2:9.\x*
\q1
\v 5 You meet the \add one who\add* is happy and who does \add what is right\add*—
\q1 who remembers your \add instructions\add*.
\q1 Listen, you were angry \add because\add* we sinned over a long period
\q1 \add but now\add* we will be saved.
\q1
\v 6 We’ve all become like \add someone\add* ‘unclean’
\q1 and all \add the good things we do\add* are like a \add used\add* menstrual rag.
\q1 \add Because of\add* our \add acts of disobedience\add*,
\q1 all of us have been like leaves that withered and were carried off like the wind.
\b
\q1
\v 7 There’s no one \add left\add* who calls on your name—
\q1 \add no one\add* who stirs themself up to take hold of you,
\q1 because you’ve hidden \add yourself\add* from us
\q1 and \add allowed our acts of disobedience to dissolve us away\add*.
\q1
\v 8 \add But now,\add* Yahweh, you are our father.
\q1 We are the clay, and you’re our potter,
\q1 and all of us are the your handiwork.
\q1
\v 9 Don’t be excessively angry, Yahweh,
\q1 and don’t remember \add our\add* \add disobedience\add* forever.
\q1 Wow, please look \add here\add*—all of us are your people.
\q1
\v 10 Your sacred cities have become a wilderness:
\q1 Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* has become a wilderness.
\q1 Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* \add became\add* a desolation.
\q1
\v 11 Our sacred and beautiful \add temple\add*, where our ancestors praised you,
\q1 has \add now\add* been burnt,
\q1 and \add everything that we liked there\add* is in ruins.
\q1
\v 12 \add After\add* those, will you restrain yourself, Yahweh?
\q1 Will you remain silent \add as you\add* make us suffer so much?
\c 65
\s1 Judgement from Yahweh
\p
\v 1 “I let myself be consulted by \add those who\add* hadn’t asked,
\q1 I let myself be found by \add those who\add* hadn’t searched for me.\x + \xo 65:1: \xt Rom 10:20.\x*
\q1 I said, ‘Here I am. Here I am.’ to a nation that wasn’t \add even\add* calling out my name.
\q1
\v 2 All day \add long,\add* I held my hands out to a rebellious people,\x + \xo 65:2: \xt Rom 10:21.\x*
\q1 who \add do just what they want rather than\add* walking the good path—
\q1
\v 3 a people who continually provoke me to anger.
\q1 They regularly sacrifice in gardens
\q1 and \add burn incense\add* on brick \add altars\add*.
\q1
\v 4 They sit among graves and spend the night in \add such\add* places.
\q1 They eat pork, and soup made from ‘unclean’ meat,
\q1
\v 5 saying, ‘Don’t come near me because I’m more holy than you!’
\q1 Those \add people\add* make me angry \add like\add* a fire burning all day \add long\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 6 “Listen, it’s written \add in front of me\add*.
\q1 I won’t stay silent because I’ll repay—
\q1 I’ll repay \add where it hurts\add*—
\q1
\v 7 your disobedience and that of your ancestors together.”
\q1 Yahweh says, “They \add burnt incense\add* on the mountains,
\q1 and taunted me on the hills,
\q1 \add so\add* I’ll measure out their wages \add where it hurts\add*.”
\b
\q1
\v 8 This is what Yahweh says:
\q1 When juice is found in \add some\add* grapes \add on the vine\add*,
\q1 then \add someone\add* will say, ‘Don’t destroy it because there’s good in it,’
\q1 so too for the sake of my servants, I won’t destroy everyone.
\q1
\v 9 I’ll bring \add descendants\add* out of Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*,
\q1 and someone to possess my mountains out of Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*,
\q1 and my chosen \add ones\add* will take possession of it,
\q1 and my servants will live there.
\q1
\v 10 The Sharon \add plain\add* will become a pasture for the flocks,
\q1 and the Akor valley will be a resting place for cattle
\q1 for my people who search for me.\x + \xo 65:10: \xt Josh 7:24-26.\x*
\b
\q1
\v 11 \add But\add* you all who abandon Yahweh,
\q1 who forget my sacred mountain,
\q1 who prepare a table for Fortune,
\q1 and fill mixed wine for Destiny,
\q1
\v 12 I’ll appoint you all for the sword.
\q1 You’ll all bow down for slaughter
\q1 because I called and you all didn’t answer.
\q1 I spoke and you all didn’t listen,
\q1 and did \add what I considered to be\add* evil
\q1 and you chose what I \add didn’t like\add*.
\p
\v 13 So my master, Yahweh, says this:
\q1 Listen, my servants will eat, \add but\add* you’ll all be hungry.
\q1 Look, my servants will drink, \add but\add* you’ll all be thirsty.
\q1 Watch, my servants will celebrate, \add but\add* you’ll all be \add put to shame\add*.
\q1
\v 14 Listen, my servants will shout happily as \add they celebrate\add*,
\q1 ^\add but\add* you’ll all cry out from \add mental anguish\add*,
\q2 and you’ll all wail because of your broken spirits.
\q1
\v 15 Your names will \add remain in your language\add* as curse \add words\add* for my chosen \add ones\add*,
\q1 \add but\add* my master Yahweh will put you to death,
\q1 and then he will call his servants \add by\add* another name.
\q1
\v 16 Anyone who blesses themself on earth, will bless themself by the god of certainty,
\q1 and anyone who \add makes a vow\add* on earth, will promise by the god of certainty,
\q1 because \add their\add* former troubles will be forgotten because they’ll be hidden from my eyes.
\s1 Yahweh’s new creation
\p
\v 17 Listen, I’m about to create new skies and a new earth,\x + \xo 65:17: \xt Isa 66:22; 2Pe 3:13; Rev 21:1.\x*
\q1 and then the previous \add things\add* won’t be remembered \add or thought about\add*
\q1
\v 18 because you’ll celebrate and be forever happy with what I’m about to create,
\q1 because listen, I’m about to create a happy Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* \add with\add* celebrating people.
\q1
\v 19 Then I’ll celebrate about Yerushalem and be happy about my people,
\q1 and the \add sounds\add* of weeping and distress will no longer be heard \add there\add*.\x + \xo 65:19: \xt Rev 21:4.\x*
\q1
\v 20 There won’t be any more babies \add die\add* there \add at a few days old\add*,
\q1 or an elderly \add person\add* who doesn’t \add enjoy their full life\add*.
\q1 Someone who’s a hundred years old will \add seem like\add* a young man,
\q1 and someone who doesn’t reach one hundred will be \add considered\add* cursed.
\q1
\v 21 They’ll build houses and live in them,
\q1 and they’ll plant vineyards and \add get to\add* eat \add their\add* fruit.
\q1
\v 22 They won’t build then \add end up\add* \add having someone else live there\add*,
\q1 and they won’t plant then \add end up\add* \add with someone else eating\add* \add the produce\add*,
\q1 because my people will live \add as long as\add* trees,
\q1 and my chosen \add ones\add* will fully enjoy \add everything they’ve worked at\add*.
\q1
\v 23 \add Their work won’t be wasted\add*, and they won’t \add end up discouraged\add*,
\q1 →because they’ll be Yahweh’s \add children\add* who are blessed, along with their descendants.
\q1
\v 24 Before they \add even\add* call out, I’ll answer \add them\add*—
\q1 while they’re still speaking, I’ll hear \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 25 The wolf and the lamb will graze together,\x + \xo 65:25: \xt Isa 11:6-9.\x*
\q1 and the lion will eat straw like the cow.
\q1 The snake’s food will be dirt and they won’t cause any harm,
\q1 and \add nothing will be destroyed\add* on my sacred mountain says Yahweh.
\c 66
\s1 Hypocrisy in worship
\p
\v 1 Yahweh says this:\x + \xo 66:1: a \xt Mat 5:34; 23:22; \xo b \xt Mat 5:35.\x*
\q1 The heavens are my throne and the earth is my footstool.
\q1 Where \add then,\add* could you all build a house for me,
\q1 and where could be a place for me to \add relax\add*?
\q1
\v 2 My hand made all those \add things\add*
\q1 and they came to be \add by\add* Yahweh’s declaration.
\q1 The \add people\add* \add that I take notice of\add*
\q1 are those who are humble and contrite,
\q1 and who \add sincerely respect and honour\add* my message.
\b
\q1
\v 3 \add The same person\add* who slaughters a bull \add (to sacrifice)\add*, also \add murders\add* a person.
\q1 The one who sacrifices a lamb, breaks a dog’s neck.
\q1 Someone who brings up a grain offering, \add also brings\add* pigs’ blood.
\q1 A person who offers incense as a memorial, blesses wickedness as well.
\q1 →They’ve chosen their own ways, and enjoy their detestable \add behaviour\add*.
\q1
\v 4 \add So\add* I will choose their punishment,
\q1 →and I’ll \add cause their fears to come to be\add*.
\q1 because I called \add but\add* no one answered.
\q1 I spoke and no one listened.
\q1 They did evil \add things\add* \add as I watched\add*,
\q1 and chose \add to do\add* what I didn’t like.
\b
\q1
\v 5 Listen to Yahweh’s message \add you\add* \add who respect and honour\add* \add it\add*.
\q1 Your relatives who hate you \add and\add* who exclude you all for my name’s sake, have said,
\q1 ‘Let Yahweh be \add honoured\add* so we can see your happiness,’
\q1 \add however, they’ll be put to shame\add*.
\q1
\v 6 There’s a sound of uproar from the city—
\q1 noise coming from the temple:
\q1 the sound of Yahweh \add giving his enemies what they deserve\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 7 Before it went into labour, it \add already\add* gave birth.\x + \xo 66:7: \xt Rev 12:5.\x*
\q1 Before the pain hit it, it delivered a son.
\q1
\v 8 Who’s heard anything like that \add before\add*?
\q1 Who’s seen those \add sorts of\add* things?
\q1 Can a land be given birth to in one day?
\q1 Can a nation be born in an \add instant\add*,
\q1 →because Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* gave birth to her children \add so soon as\add* she went into labour?
\q1
\v 9 “Do I bring \add a baby\add* to the birth \add canal\add* and then not deliver it?” Yahweh asks.
\q1 “Or do I bring it \add to the point of delivery\add* and then hold it back?” asks your god.
\q1
\v 10 Celebrate with Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* all of you who love it, and be glad.
\q1 Happily celebrate with it, all of you who mourned over it,
\q1
\v 11 because you’ll all suckle and be satisfied from her comforting breasts.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* you’ll all drink deeply and delight yourselves from her gushing nipple,
\p
\v 12 because Yahweh says this:
\q1 Listen, I’m about to extend peace to \add Yerushalem\add* like a river,
\q1 and the wealth of the nations \add to her\add* like an overflowing stream.
\q1 Then you’ll all suckle \add and\add* be carried on the hip,
\q1 and bounced on her knees.
\q1
\v 13 I’ll comfort you all like a mother comforts \add her child\add*,
\q1 and you’ll all be comforted in Yerushalem.
\q1
\v 14 You’ll all see \add that\add* and \add it’ll warm your heart\add*,
\q1 and your bones will sprout like the grass.
\q1 Yahweh will reveal his \add power\add* to his servants,
\q1 and he’ll be indignant at his enemies,
\b
\q1
\v 15 because listen, Yahweh will come in fire with his chariots like a windstorm,
\q1 →to bring his raging anger and to rebuke with flames of fire.
\q1
\v 16 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh judges all humanity with fire and his sword,
\q1 and many \add people\add* will be killed by \add him\add*.
\p
\v 17 Those who consecrate themselves, and purify themselves for the gardens,
\q1 and those who eat \add pork\add*, \add rats\add*, and other detestable things, will all be destroyed together.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 18 I \add know\add* their thoughts and \add what they’ve done\add*. \add The time\add* is coming to gather all the nations and the language \add groups\add*, and they’ll come and see my glory.
\v 19 I’ll perform a \add miracle\add* among them, and will send survivors from them to the nations: Tarshishm, Put, Lud (home of archers), Tuval, Yavan, and to the distant islands where they haven’t heard \add about me\add* or seen my \add splendour\add*. They’ll tell \add other\add* nations about my \add greatness\add*.
\v 20 Then they’ll bring all your relatives back from all the nations to my sacred mountain Yerushalem, on horses, and in chariots and wagons, and on mules and camels, as an offering to Yahweh like how the \add Israelis\add* bring a grain offering in a clean vessel into the house of Yahweh.
\m That’s what Yahweh says.
\p
\v 21 Then I’ll \add choose\add* some of them to be priests and \add temple workers\add*.
\m That’s what Yahweh says.
\p
\v 22 Just as the new skies and the new earth will stand \add in front of me\add*,\x + \xo 66:22: \xt Isa 65:17; 2Pe 3:13; Rev 21:1.\x*
\q1 so your descendants and your name will endure.
\m That’s what Yahweh declares.
\q1
\v 23 Then from month to month and week to week,
\q1 all \add creatures\add* will come to bow down in front of me.
\m That’s what Yahweh says.
\p
\v 24 Then they’ll go out and see the corpses of those who rebelled against me,
\q1 because the maggots won’t die and their fire won’t be extinguished,
\q1 and all \add creatures\add* will \add find them\add* abhorrent.\x + \xo 66:24: \xt Mrk 9:48.\x*
